				  </content>
			  </section>
			  <section id="1.1.2 Salient Features" level="4">
				  <title>1.1.2 Salient Features</title>
				  <content>
					  <para>The main salient features of NTDS are as follows:</para
  >
					  <para>(a) Capable of detecting the incoming torpedoes.</para>
					  <para>
						  (b) Capable of deploying and recovering the Fiber Optic Tow Cable
						  (FOTC).
					  </para>

					  <para>
						  (c) Capable of launching EADs by EDL to counter the threats of incoming
						  torpedoes to ships.
					  </para>

					  <para>
						  (d) Capability to transmit EAD status to the processing units through
						  RS485 link.
					  </para>
					  <para>(e) A provision to detect EIGHT types of EADs (stores) loaded.</para>
					  <para>
						  (f) Capable of controlling EDL locally (LCU) or remotely (RCU) for
						  launching the EAD.
					  </para>
					  <para>
						  (g) Uses Pressure sensors, Proximity Sensors and copper coils to detect
						  and display the status of the Firing Valve Assemblies (FVAs).
					  </para>
					  <para>(h) High speed signal processing capability.</para>
					  <para>(i) High reliability / rugged design to suit tactical requirements.</para>
					  <para>(j) Interface to processing cabinet.</para>


				  </content>
			  </section>
		  </section>
		  <section id="1.2 Interfaces and Power Supply" level="3">
			  <title>1.2 Interfaces and Power Supply</title>
			  <section id="1.2.1 Processing Cabinet Interface" level="4">
				  <title>1.2.1 Processing Cabinet Interface</title>
				  <content>
					  <para>
						  The NTDS interfaces with the Processing Cabinet. It
						  takes 32 byte data information from the LCU, RCU and Winch for facilitating
						  threat assessment and proposes defensive actions to be taken by the
						  ship in the face of the detected threat.
					  </para>
				  </content>
			  </section>
