				  <section id="1.3.2.1 Expendable Device Launcher EDL" level="5">
					  <title>1.3.2.1 Expendable Device Launcher (EDL)</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The pictorial view of EDL is shown in
							  Fig. 1.3.
						  </para>

						  <para>Each EDL accommodates LCU and 10 FVAs/Device launch barrels which are Line Replaceable Units (LRUs) that can be removed or installed with standard tools. Each barrel assembly has a length of approximately 1m and diameter of 0.175m with a weight of 13kg. The EDL has a provision to detect the presence/absence by means of ‘AVL’ indicator on LCU and information on type of EADs loaded to Processing Cabinet via RS485 communication link. The EDL can be locally (LCU) or remotely (RCU) controlled for launching the EAD. Each FVA is independently controllable. The EDL transmits its status to the Processing Cabinet through a standard RS485 link. The EDL operates on 115VAC, 50Hz/60Hz, 1Ø or 380VAC, 415VAC, 450VAC, 50Hz/60Hz, 3Ø ship’s supply. Supply is routed through the EDL power switch. A Sounder mounted within the body of the EDL. It is used to generate a two-tone alarm to warn personnel when the firing mode selected that is, when 3-way Key Switch is momentarily changed to LOCAL ARM on LCU or REMOTE ARM on RCU. A Built-In Test Equipment facility is provided in the EDL for fault diagnosis upto the LRU level.</para>
						  <para>
							  <figure>
								  <graphic
								  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_3.gif"
></graphic>
								  <figtitle>Fig. 1.3: Pictorial view of EDL</figtitle>
							  </figure>
						  </para>
					  </content>
					  <section id="1.3.2.1.1 Firing Valve Assembly FVA" level="6">
						  <title>1.3.2.1.1 Firing Valve Assembly (FVA)</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  See Fig. 1.4. The
								  FVA is used to eject the EAD from                   the launcher tube.
								  It receives air supply and electrical signals from
								  the Air Supply Inlet and Electrical Cable Inlet of the EDL plinth
								  at the bottom of the EDL.
							  </para
>
							  <para>
								  The main components of
								  the FVA                   are:
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <ol type="a">
									  <li>
										  <h6>Reservoir:</h6> The reservoir has the
										  capacity to store 1                       litre volume of dry compressed
										  air, and can be charged to a minimum                       of 90bar
										  in less than 1 minute. It has a capacity to store air upto
										  a pressure of 200 bar. On firing the launcher, the
										  pressure reduces                       to zero or less than 0.65bar.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  <h6>5 Way Mechanical Selector Switch:</h6
> The 5-way mechanical                       selector switch is used
										  to select the modes, CHARGE, SAFE, VENT and
										  ARM.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  <h6>Solenoid valve:</h6> Receives the firing
										  signal from the RCU,                       LCU or Processing Cabinet.
										  When actuated, compressed air is released                       into
										  the Piston Assembly, which displaces the Piston ejecting the
										  EAD.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  <h6>Interface sleeve:</h6> Is the interface
										  between the FVA and                       the EAD.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  <h6>Contact plug assembly: </h6>Is used
										  to identify the availability                       of the store (EAD)
										  and the type of store loaded onto corresponding
										  FVA.
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic
									  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_4.gif"
></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 1.4: Firing Valve Assembly</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="1.3.2.1.2 Local Control Unit LCU" level="6">
						  <title>1.3.2.1.2 Local Control Unit (LCU)</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The pictorial view of LCU is shown
								  in Fig. 1.5.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  The LCU
								  is mounted on the side of the EDL. It is used to operate
								  the EDL from the local position. The LCU can operate on 115
								  VAC, 50Hz/60Hz,                   1∅ or 380 VAC / 415 VAC / 450 VAC,
								  50Hz / 60Hz, 3∅ with a power consumption                   of 50W,
								  it receives power supply through J4 connector on LCU connected
								  to J1 connector at the bottom of the carcass. A provision
								  has been                   made to RS485 connection in the LCU such
								  that it can be connected                   to the Processing Cabinet
								  at J9 (LCU end) and at J3/P3 Plinth end.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic
									  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_5.gif"
></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 1.5: Local Control Unit</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
				  </section>
				  <section id="1.3.2.2 Remote Control Unit RCU for EDL" level="5">
					  <title>1.3.2.2 Remote Control Unit (RCU) for EDL</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The pictorial view of RCU is shown in
							  Fig. 1.6.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  RCU is used
							  to operate the EDL from a position other than from
							  the launcher. The RCU can be used to operate and control EDL (Port/Stbd)
							  remotely. When the LOCAL ARM/SAFE/REMOTE key switch
							  located on the                 LCU (Port/Stbd) is put to the “REMOTE”
							  position, fire commands are                 routed to the RCU and
							  permits the operator to control independent                 EDLs.
							  Auto Fire of the EDL is possible via RCU from Cabinet. This
							  unit can operate at 115 VAC, 50Hz/60Hz, 1∅ or 380VAC/415VAC/450VAC
							  50Hz/60Hz, 3∅ with a power consumption of 50 W (Approx.).
							  A provision                 has been made to RS485 connection in the
							  RCU such that it can be connected                 to the Processing
							  Cabinet through J6/P6 (RCU end).
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <figure>
								  <graphic
								  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_6.gif"
></graphic>
								  <figtitle>Fig. 1.6: Pictorial view of RCU</figtitle>
							  </figure>
						  </para>
					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="1.3.2.3 Winch" level="5">
					  <title>1.3.2.3 Winch</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  See Fig. 1.7 for a pictorial view of
							  Winch.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  The Winch is used
							  to deploy and recover the Fiber Optic Tow Cable.                 It
							  consists of a single drum with shaft mounted on a support structure,
							  Level Wind Assembly, Encoder Housing Assembly, Worm
							  and Worm Gear                 Box, Main Control Panel (MCP), Slip
							  Ring assembly, Motors (for Level                 Wind &amp; Drum)
							  and Junction Boxes (SRJB and WDJB). The winch drum
							  is driven by an electric motor coupled through a gear box, it can
							  also be operated manually. A Main Control Panel (MCP)
							  is provided                 for electric operation of the Winch Drum
							  and Level Wind. Manual operation                 of the Drum and Level
							  Wind is accomplished by a hand wheel. A level                 wind
							  assembly is provided on the aft side of the winch drum as a cable
							  guide controlling the lateral movement of the cable
							  to be wound on                 the drum of the winch. A band of drum
							  brake covering the drum flange                 is provided for locking
							  the winch during maintenance and for locking                 the drum
							  rotation when idle. The Gear Drum-Brake Assembly and Level
							  Wind Assembly is mounted on a winch plinth welded to the
							  ship.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <figure>
								  <graphic
								  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_7.gif"
></graphic>
								  <figtitle>Fig. 1.7: Winch</figtitle>
							  </figure>
						  </para>
					  </content>
					  <section id="1.3.2.3.1 Level Wind Assembly" level="6">
						  <title>1.3.2.3.1 Level Wind Assembly</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  Level Wind Assembly is shown in Fig.
								  1.8.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  The Level Wind
								  Assembly is a stand-alone system. This guiding mechanism
								  is used to correctly lay the FOTC onto the winch drum during
								  recovery.                   It protects the towed components from
								  damage during retrieval, Nylon                   66 is used in parts
								  of the mechanism that are in contact with the                   tow
								  to minimize abrasion. The mechanism operates under a cable tension
								  of 13.3kN and allows the operator to position the
								  towed components                   at any desired position over the
								  internal width of the drum during                   recovery only.
								  The height of the Level Wind assembly can be adjusted
								  to suit the ship’s requirement.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic
									  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_8.gif"
></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 1.8: Level Wind Assembly</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  The level wind mechanism is driven by a variable
								  speed reversible electric motor and is operated by a single
								  operator                   from the MCP using the joystick. The joystick
								  is spring loaded to ensure                   its return to the stop
								  position when released. A “dead man” switch                   on joystick
								  is used to allow normal operations of the MCP when activated
								  and will stop the winch motor when released thus avoids
								  an accidental                   rotation of the drum. The MCP panel is mounted such that the operator stands
								  to the side of the towline on the starboard side of the winch and can be used to start, stop, and vary the speed and direction of the mechanism. Two proximity switches are used to stop motor operation at the extremities of its  travel.
							  </para
>
							  <para>
								  In the absence of power,
								  the mechanism can be manually operated                   by means
								  of a removable handle provided on the port side of the mechanism.
								  When the tow is being deployed the mechanism is
								  parked on the port                   side with one flap locked in
								  the horizontal position by a locking                   pin, as it
								  is not required to operate during deployment. The mechanism
								  can be switched from deployment mode to recovery mode
								  by changing                   the position of the guide flap from
								  horizontal position to vertical                   position and vice
								  versa. The level wind mechanism can be easily detached
								  and can be slung using the lifting eyes provided.
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="1.3.2.3.2 Rotary Housing" level="6">
						  <title>1.3.2.3.2 Rotary Housing</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>Rotary Housing is shown in Fig. 1.9.</para
>
							  <para>
								  The                   Rotary
								  Housing is attached to the Drum Shaft at Port side on the support
								  structure. It contains the Rotary Encoder
								  and Rotary Cam Limit                   Switch to measure length deployed
								  from Winch Drum. Interface of Rotary                   Encoder and
								  Rotary cam limit switch along with drum shaft is achieved
								  by Timing belt mechanism, which transfers the drum rotation
								  to Rotary                   Encoder and Rotary Cam Limit Switch.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic
									  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_9.gif"
></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 1.9: Rotary Housing</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="1.3.2.3.3 Main Control Panel MCP" level="6">
						  <title>1.3.2.3.3 Main Control Panel (MCP)</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  See Fig. 1.10 for Main Control Panel
								  (MCP)
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  The MCP is mounted
								  on the Winch. It is used to control the operation
								  of the Winch when the LOCAL/REMOTE function switch is set to LOCAL.
								  It acts as a Human Machine Interface (HMI).
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic
									  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_10.gif"
></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 1.10: Main Control Panel (MCP)</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="1.3.2.3.4 Slip Ring Assembly" level="6">
						  <title>1.3.2.3.4 Slip Ring Assembly</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  It is fitted inside
								  the hollow drum shaft. The purpose                   of slip ring
								  assembly is to provide Electrical as well as optical
								  connection between Stationary part and Rotary Part of the winch.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic
									  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_1_3_2_3_4.gif"
></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 1.10(a): Representation of Slip Ring Assembly</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="1.3.2.3.5 Motors" level="6">
						  <title>1.3.2.3.5 Motors</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The winch has two
								  motors, one for Drum rotation and                   another for Level
								  Wind Guide Structure movement. The drum motor is
								  equipped with an Electric Brake and both the motors are operated
								  by                   Dead man Switch on Joystick of Main Control Panel.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic
									  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_1_3_2_3_5_b.gif"
></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 1.10(b): View of Winch Drum Motor</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic
									  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_1_3_2_3_5_c.gif"
></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 1.10(c): View of Level Wind Motor</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="1.3.2.3.6 Junction Boxes" level="6">
						  <title>1.3.2.3.6 Junction Boxes</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  Winch electrical
								  connections terminate at both Rotary                   part and stationary
								  part. Winch Drum Junction Box (WDJB) forms the                   rotary
								  part which is housed inside the drum and Slip Ring Junction
								  Box (SRJB) forms the stationary part bolted to the stationary
								  support                   structure.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic
									  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_1_3_2_3_6.gif"
></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 1.10(d): View of Winch Drum Junction Box</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic
									  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_1_3_2_3_6_e.gif"
></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 1.10(e): View of Slip Ring Junction Box (SRJB)</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="1.3.2.3.7 Connectors on Winch Plinth" level="6">
						  <title>1.3.2.3.7 Connectors on Winch Plinth</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  There are four
								  connectors are on a winch plinth as                   J1 (Power),
								  J2 (High Voltage), J3 (Low Voltage) and J4 (Optical Fiber).
								  J1 is connected to the MCP panel to Power up the Winch.
								  J2, J3 and                   J4 are connected to FOTC Connector with
								  Two junction Boxes and Slip                   ring Assembly.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic
									  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_1_3_2_3_7.gif"
></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 1.10(f): Connectors on Winch Plinth</figtitle>
								  </figure>
