      <section id="1.4 Detailed Circuit Description" level="3">
        <title>1.4 Detailed Circuit Description</title>
        <section id="1.4.1 Expendable Device Launcher EDL" level="4">
          <title>1.4.1 Expendable Device Launcher (EDL)</title>
          <content>
            <para>
              <h6>Introduction</h6>
              <para>
                For Introduction to EDL,
                <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V3_intro_EDL.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
                  Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
                </a>
              </para>
            </para>
            <para>
              The pictorial view
              of EDL (Carcass &amp; Plinth) is shown in Fig. 1.15.
            </para>
            <para>
              The
              launcher comprises of a Firing Valve Assembly (FVA), Expendable Device
              Launcher (EDL) and a Local Control Unit (LCU). The EDL consists of
              a Carcass bolted on a Plinth at an angle of 25° to the horizontal.
              An electrical connector box to interface the EDL with the LCU, RCU
              &amp; Processing Cabinet, is welded directly to the EDL structure.
              The rear end of the Carcass is closed with a hinged door plate. The
              launcher can be operated locally from the LCU or remotely from the
              RCU. The launcher is capable of accepting 10 device launch barrels
              of length 1m or less, each barrel can be independently operated. The
              weight of the EDL is less than 650kgs.
            </para>
            <para>
              <figure>
                <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_15.gif"></graphic>
                <figtitle>Fig. 1.15: Carcass &amp; Plinth</figtitle>
              </figure>
            </para>
            <para>
              <h6>Main Units</h6>
            </para>
            <para>
              The functional
              block diagram of the EDL is shown in Fig.1.16
            </para>
            <para>
              An inner
              view of EDL is shown in Fig. 1.17.
            </para>
            <para>
              The EDL houses the
              following:
            </para>
            <para>
              <ol type="1">
                <li>Firing Valve Assemblies (10 No’s)</li>
                <li>Pneumatic charging and venting lines</li>
                <li>Inlet high-pressure air supply connection</li>
                <li>Local Control Unit (LCU)</li>
                <li>Sounder</li>
                <li>Launcher electrical connections</li>
                <li>Electrical &amp; Pneumatic Lines</li>
              </ol>
            </para>
            <para>
              The components of the main units and detailed description
              of each subsystem is given in the following paragraphs:<a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/1_4_1_fig_1_16.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="user">
                Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;"/>
              </a>
            </para>
            <para
  >
              <figure>
                <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_16.gif"></graphic>
                <figtitle>Fig. 1.16: Functional Block Diagram of EDL</figtitle>
              </figure>
            </para>
            <para>
              <figure>
                <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_17.gif"></graphic>
                <figtitle>Fig. 1.17: Inner view of EDL</figtitle>
              </figure>
            </para>
            <para>
              <figure>
                <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_17(a).gif"
  ></graphic>
                <figtitle>Fig. 1.17(a): EDL</figtitle>
              </figure>
            </para>
          </content>
          <section id="1.4.1.1 Firing Valve Assembly FVA" level="5">
            <title>1.4.1.1 Firing Valve Assembly (FVA)</title>
            <content>
              <para>
                <h6>Introduction</h6>
                <para>
                  For Introduction to FVA,
                  <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V4_intro_FVA.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
                    Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
                  </a>
                </para>
              </para>
              <para>
                The FVA is designed
                to propel the EAD at a minimum firing velocity of 25m/s. The assembly
                is bolted on to the EDL and can be removed from the front of the EDL
                during maintenance. The FVA weighs less than 20kgs. Two electrical
                contacts provide indications of the presence and type of EAD in the
                barrel. FVA consists of a reservoir containing one liter of dry air
                at a minimum pressure of 90bar. Firing signal received from the LCU/RCU
                is used to operate a solenoid valve. Operation of the solenoid valve
                results in air from the reservoir being released to a piston valve
                assembly. The piston valve assembly launches the EAD and propels it
                at a minimum velocity of 25m/s. An interface sleeve is provided to
                house the EAD. A 5-Way Mechanical Selector Switch is used to select
                CHARGE, VENT, ARM and SAFE modes of the FVA.
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>FVA Functions</h6
  >
              </para>
              <para>The primary functions are as follows:</para>
              <para>(a) Pneumatically operated device to launch the EAD.</para>
              <para>(b) Charge: To receive compressed air (charging)</para>
              <para>(c) Charged: To store compressed air for 45 days</para>
              <para>
                (d) Discharge (firing)
              </para>

              <para>
                (i)  To discharge compressed air to the barrel (firing) under Remote
                Control, (or)
              </para>
              <para>
                (ii) To discharge compressed air to the barrel (firing) under Local
                Control (or)
              </para>
              <para>
                (iii) To discharge compressed air to the barrel (firing) under Auto
                mode (from Processing Cabinet)
              </para>

              <para>(e) Communicate its state with the LCU, RCU and processing Cabinet.</para>
              <para>
                (f) Vent air: To allow controlled venting of compressed air to atmosphere
                when required for maintenance, decommissioning etc. Air pressure after
                venting is less than &lt; 65kPa (0.65 Bar).
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>Functional description</h6>
              </para>
              <para>
                The
                functional block diagram of the FVA is shown in Fig. 1.18
              </para>
              <para
  >
                Air pressure at 300 bar is received from the ship’s pneumatic system.
                The air pressure is reduced to 105 bar by a pressure regulator. Air
                at 105bar is fed to a 5-way Mechanical Selector Switch. This switch
                positions are CHARGE, SAFE, ARM and VENT. In the charge position air
                is directed to the Reservoir for charging, in the Safe position air
                is not fed to the system, this ensures that inadvertent firing of
                the launcher does not take place; in the Arm position air from the
                Reservoir is fed to the Firing Valve through a Solenoid Valve which
                opens when a firing pulse is received either from the LCU or the RCU
                or Processing Cabinet. The firing valve propels the EAD out of the
                barrel.
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_18.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.18: Functional diagram of FVA</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>Exploded view of FVA</h6>
              </para>
              <para>
                See
                Fig. 1.19
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_19.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.19: Exploded view of FVA</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>Main components in FVA</h6>
              </para>
              <para
  >The FVA consists of the following:</para>
              <para>
                <ol type="1">
                  <li>Reservoir</li>
                  <li>5-way selector valve</li>
                  <li>Non-return valve</li>
                  <li>Pressure gauge</li>
                  <li>Pressure Relief valve</li>
                  <li>Solenoid valve</li>
                  <li>Pressure switch</li>
                  <li>Pressure Regulator</li>
                  <li>Isolation Valve (3-way Ball Valve)</li>
                  <li>Air Filter</li>
                  <li>Proximity Sensors (SAFE, ARM and VENT position)</li>
                  <li>Piston-valve assembly</li>
                  <li>Contact plug assembly</li>
                  <li>Valve body</li>
                  <li>Upper plates 1 &amp; 2</li>
                  <li>Interface sleeve</li>
                  <li>Pneumatic tubes</li>
                </ol>
              </para>

            </content>
            <section id="1.4.1.1.1 Reservoir" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.1.1 Reservoir</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  The reservoir is a high-pressure air vessel made of
                  aluminum weighing less than 20kg. It has a diameter of 102mm, length
                  of 225mm and has a capacity of 1 litre of dry compressed air. The
                  reservoir can be charged to a maximum pressure of 200bar (Capacity)
                </para
  >
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.1.1.2 5-Way Selector Valve" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.1.2 5-Way Selector Valve</title>
              <content>
                <para>See Fig. 1.20</para>
                <para>
                  The 5-way mechanical selector
                  switch mounted on the FVA is used to select the mode of operation
                  of the FVA. The valve has positions, CHARGE, SAFE, ARM and VENT.
                </para
  >
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_20.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.20: 5-Way Selector Valve</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>a) Safe Mode:</h6> The system configuration
                  in Safe Mode is shown in Fig. 1.21 and a pictorial view is shown in
                  Fig. 1.22. In the Safe Mode, all functions are inhibited including
                  the mechanical parts of the Firing Valve.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_21.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.21: System Configuration in Safe Mode</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_22.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.22: 5-Way Selector Valve – Safe Position</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>b) Charge Mode:</h6> The system configuration
                  in Charge Mode is shown in Fig. 1.23. In the CHARGE Mode the reservoir
                  is charged to a minimum of 90bar, the path between the barrel and
                  the reservoir is inhibited in this position. The reservoir charges
                  up to 90 bar pressure in less than a minute, and stores 1 litre of
                  compressed air. Once charged up to 105 bar no leakage will occur for
                  up to 45 days, 2% leakage is expected beyond 45 days up to 60 days. Refer
                  Fig. 1.23(a) for location of Charging NRV 5-Way Selector Valve.
                </para
  >
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_23.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.23: 5-Way Selector Valve – Charge position</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_23(a).gif"
  ></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.23(a): 5-Way Selector Valve – Charge position</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>c) Vent Mode:</h6> See Fig. 1.24. The system
                  configuration in Vent Mode is shown in Fig. 1.25. In the Vent Mode,
                  pressure is reduced to 65kPa (0.65bar) and air vented out between
                  the barrel and the reservoir.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_24.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.24: 5-Way Selector Valve –Vent position</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_25.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.25: System Configuration in Vent Mode</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>d) Arm Mode:</h6> The system configuration
                  in Arm Mode is shown in Fig. 1.26 and a pictorial view (5-Way Selector
                  Valve–Arm Position) is shown in Fig. 1.27. See Fig. 1.28 for system
                  configuration for firing. In the Arm Mode the reservoir contents are
                  released to the barrel when the firing button is pressed. When the
                  5-way mechanical selector is in the Arm position, firing signal received
                  from the LCU/RCU operates the solenoid valve and connects the reservoir
                  to the firing valve which directs the compressed air into the barrels
                  for launching the EADs, the solenoid operates on 24V DC, 0.25A. The
                  Firing Valve returns to the closed position automatically. The valve
                  has provisions to transmit a signal on the current selected state
                  to the LCU/RCU.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_26.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.26: System Configuration in Arm Mode</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_27.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.27: 5-Way Selector Valve –Arm Position</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_28.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.28: System Configuration for Firing</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.1.1.3 Non-return Valve" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.1.3 Non-return Valve</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  A pictorial view of Non-return valve is shown in Fig.
                  1.29. The non-return valve is connected between the Pressure Regulator
                  and the 5-way mechanical selector valve.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_29.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.29: Non-return Valve</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.1.1.4 Pressure gauge" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.1.4 Pressure gauge</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  The pressure gauge is used to measure and display pressure
                  being used or delivered by the reservoir. It can measure reservoir
                  pressure continuously from 0 to 160 bar.
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.1.1.5 Relief Valve" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.1.5 Relief Valve</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  A pictorial view of Relief valve is shown in Fig. 1.30.
                  A relief valve is provided on the reservoir to avoid overpressure.
                  The valve is set to operate at a pressure above 105bar.
                </para>
                <para
  >
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_30.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.30: Relief Valve</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.1.1.6 Solenoid Valve" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.1.6 Solenoid Valve</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  A pictorial view of Solenoid valve is shown in Fig.
                  1.31. The solenoid valve receives the firing signal and operates the
                  firing valve assembly to launch the EAD. It is a type 3/2-way NC solenoid
                  valve with an operating pressure of 90bar (max operating pressure
                  105bar). It operates on 24 V DC supply and has a reaction time of
                  15ms for 63% opening.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_31.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.31: Solenoid Valve</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.1.1.7 Pressure Sensor" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.1.7 Pressure Sensor</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  A pictorial view of Pressure switch is shown in Fig.
                  1.32. The pressure sensor is mounted on the valve body. The function of
                  this sensor is to sense pressure if it lies within the 90 to 105 bar
                  and convey pressure status (as good) to LCU.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_32.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.32: Pressure Switch</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.1.1.8 Pressure Regulator" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.1.8 Pressure Regulator</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  A pictorial view of Pressure Regulator is shown in
                  Fig. 1.33. The pressure regulator is fitted after the isolation valve.
                  It reduces the air pressure from 300bar to 105bar.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_33.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.33: Pressure Regulator</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.1.1.9 Isolation Valve" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.1.9 Isolation Valve</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  The isolation valve (a 3 Way Ball Valve) is connected
                  between the ship`s pneumatic system and the pressure regulator used
                  to charge the FVA`s and discharge the excess air from EDL pneumatic
                  lines.
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.1.1.10 Air Filter" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.1.10 Air Filter</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  A pictorial view of Air Filter is shown in Fig. 1.34.
                  An air filter is connected between the isolating valve and the pressure
                  regulator to filter out any impurities in the air supply.
                </para>
                <para
  >
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_34.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.34: Air Filter</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.1.1.11 FVA-Proximity Sensor" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.1.11 FVA-Proximity Sensor</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  Refer Fig. 1.35. Three proximity sensors are provided
                  on the FVA to indicate the position of the 5-way Mechanical Selector
                  Switch. These positions are SAFE, ARM and VENT.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_35.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.35: Proximity Sensor</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.1.1.12 Firing Valve Body" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.1.12 Firing Valve Body</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  The Firing Valve Body houses a piston assembly that
                  is used to propel the EAD at a velocity of 25m/s from the barrel.
                  The main parts of the Valve Body consist of a Cylinder and Piston
                  Assembly (Piston, Piston Sleeve, Spring, Piston Seat and a Piston
                  Cap). After firing the valve returns to the closed position automatically.
                  The valve is designed to open to an extent of 63% in 15ms on receipt
                  of the firing pulse. The Piston body is located in the Piston Sleeve.
                  The Sleeve has two ports, one connecting the assembly to the Charging
                  Port at 90 bar - 105 bar pressure and the other connecting it to the
                  Reservoir.
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.1.1.13 Interface sleeve" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.1.13 Interface sleeve</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  A pictorial view of Interface Sleeve and Contact Plug
                  is shown in Fig. 1.36. A flange is provided at the end of the FVA
                  to interface it with the EDL. The flange carries two copper contact
                  plug assemblies. The plugs are used to interface with the EAD and
                  convey information on the type of EAD loaded (store type) and the
                  presence (store present) of the EAD in the barrel. The flange also
                  carries an interface sleeve, this sleeve is used to load the EAD on
                  the EDL.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_36.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.36: Interface Flange-Design and Contact Plug</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.1.2 Pneumatic Charging  Venting lines" level="5">
            <title>1.4.1.2 Pneumatic Charging &amp; Venting lines</title>
            <content>
              <para>
                The pneumatic system of the EDL consists of Charging
                &amp; Venting lines. Charging lines are used to fill dry air in the
                reservoir to a minimum pressure of 90bar needed to launch the EAD.
                Venting lines are used to discharge air from the pneumatic system.
              </para
  >
              <para>
                Air at 300bar is received from the ship’s air supply system,
                the air pressure is reduced to 105bar by the pressure regulator, air
                at 105bar is received at three inlet manifold from where it is distributed
                to the Firing Valve Assemblies. Fig. 1.38 shows the charging arrangement
                of the EDL.
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_38.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.38: Charging Arrangement of EDL</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                Air from the reservoirs of the FVAs are vented
                through venting pipes. The arrangement of venting pipes within the
                EDL is shown in Fig. 1.39 and Fig. 1.40. Flexible pipes convey air
                from the FVAs to three venting manifold from where air is discharged
                to the atmosphere. Air trapped in the connecting pneumatic tubes inside
                EDL can be vented to the atmosphere from the 3-way isolation ball
                valve (when the FVA’s are not in Vent mode). The charging and venting
                manifold arrangement is shown in Fig. 1.41.
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_39.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.39: Venting arrangement</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_40.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.40: Venting arrangement</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_41.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.41: Charging and Venting Manifold arrangement</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
            </content>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.1.3 Inlet High-pressure Air Supply Connection"
          level="5">
            <title>1.4.1.3 Inlet High-pressure Air Supply Connection</title>
            <content>
              <para>
                Refer Fig. 1.42 &amp; Fig. 1.43. It consists of Pressure
                reducer, Isolation valve and an Air Filter. Air at 300bar from the
                ship’s pneumatic system is received at a 3-way Ball valve (isolation
                valve). From the isolation valve air is directed to a pressure reducer
                or pressure regulator, here the inlet pressure is reduced to 105bar.
                Air at 105bar is passed through a non-return valve to the charging
                manifold. Flexible pipes convey air from the manifold to a 5-way selector
                valve on each FVA.
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_-1_42.gif"
  ></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.42: Block Diagram of EDL showing Inlet Air System</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_43.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.43: Inlet High-pressure Air Supply Connection</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
            </content>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.1.4 Local Control Unit LCU" level="5">
            <title>1.4.1.4 Local Control Unit (LCU)</title>
            <content>
              <para>
                <h6>Introduction</h6>
                <para>
                  For Introduction to LCU,
                  <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V5_intro_LCU.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
                    Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
                  </a>
                </para>
              </para>
              <para>
                A view of LCU is
                shown in Fig. 1.44.
              </para>
              <para>
                The LCU is mounted on the side of
                the EDL. It is used to operate the EDL from the launcher in local
                position. The LCU receives power supply through the electrical connector
                box located at the bottom of the carcass. The LCU can operate on 115
                VAC, 50Hz/60Hz, 1∅ or 380VAC/415VAC/450VAC 50Hz/60Hz, 3∅ with a power
                rating of 50 W.
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_44.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.44: Location of LCU</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>Functions</h6>
              </para>
              <para>
                The functions
                of LCU are enumerated below:
              </para>


              <para>(a) LCU acts as master controller for the EDL.</para>
              <para>
                (b) Capable of controlling each launch barrel independently by means
                of individual push buttons &amp; controlled keys.
              </para>
              <para>
                (c) Allow operator to relinquish control of the EDL when set to remote
                mode.
              </para>
              <para>(d) Coordinate the operation of the EDL, FVA and RCU.</para>
              <para>(e) Selection of the mode of operation for the EDL, LOCAL/REMOTE.</para>
              <para>
                (f) Indicate availability of an EAD in the barrel by means of glowing
                lamp in blue on LCU front panel when the following conditions are
                met:
              </para>
              <para>(g) SAFE/ENABLE switch is ENABLE position</para>


              <para>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;(i) Power good</para>
              <para>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;(ii) Pressure good</para>
              <para>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;(iii) FVA at ARM position</para>
              <para>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;(iv) EAD present</para>


              <para>
                (h) Indicate launcher readiness to fire by means of glowing lamp in
                green on LCU front panel.
              </para>
              <para>
                (i) `Available` signal with Remote/Safe/Local Arm switch when it is in Local Arm position.
              </para>
              <para>
                (j)  Sends availability of an EAD in the barrel and other information
                about the FAV and launcher readiness to the RCU via RS-485 serial
                link.
              </para>
              <para>(k) Provide communication with RCU and Cabinet.</para>
              <para>(l) Receives commands from RCU.</para>
              <para>(m) Generates the fire commands.</para>
              <para>(n) Verifies the lamps operational status by carrying out a lamp-test.</para>
              <para>
                (o) Built-in Test Equipment (BITE) facility for identifying the defects
                up to LRU level.
              </para>
              <para>
                (p) Perform self test with the power ON to verify the health of the
                CPU card.
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>Controls and Indicators</h6>
              </para>
              <para>
                The
                various controls &amp; indicators provided on the front panel of the
                LCU are given in the Table-1.
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>
                  Table-1: Controls &amp;
                  Indicators on LCU
                </h6>
              </para>
              <para>
                <table frame="box" rules="all">
                  <colgroup>
                    <col width="13*"/>
                    <col width="42*"/>
                    <col width="42*"/>
                  </colgroup>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td align="center">
                        <h6>Sl.No.</h6>
                      </td>
                      <td align="center">
                        <h6>Switch/Control/Indicator</h6>
                      </td>
                      <td align="center">
                        <h6>Significance</h6>
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td align="center">1</td>
                      <td>2 Way key switch (ON-OFF)</td>
                      <td>This switch toggles the launcher between SAFE and ENABLE modes.</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td align="center">2</td>
                      <td>Power ON/OFF switch</td>
                      <td>This switch is used for switching ON power to the launcher.</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td align="center">3</td>
                      <td>3 Way key switch (ON-OFF-ON)</td>
                      <td>
                        This switch is the “REMOTE-SAFE-LOCAL ARM”, it is used to select
                        the mode of operation of the launcher to ARM/SAFE and also whether
                        to launch Locally from LCU or Remotely from the RCU.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td align="center">4</td>
                      <td>Push button switches</td>
                      <td>
                        There are 10 push button switches for 10 barrels. These switches
                        are used as firing buttons.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td align="center" valign="top">5</td>
                      <td valign="top">AVL Indicator</td>
                      <td>
                        This indicator illuminates in Blue and indicate the readiness
                        of the launcher when the following conditions are met:<para>
                          <para>(a) SAFE/ENABLE Key Switch on LCU is in ENABLE Position</para>
                          <para>(b) Power Good</para>
                          <para>(c) Pressure Good</para>
                          <para>(d) In FVA, 5 way Mechanical Selector Switch at ‘ARM’ position</para>
                          <para>(e) Store(EAD) present</para>

                        </para>
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td align="center">6</td>
                      <td>RDY Indicator</td>
                      <td>
                        This indicator illuminates in Green when the switch ‘REMOTE/SAFE/LOCAL
                        ARM’ is set to ‘LOCAL ARM’ position.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td align="center">7</td>
                      <td>POWER AVL Indicator</td>
                      <td>White indicator indicates the availability of power to the launcher</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td align="center">8</td>
                      <td>Lamp Test</td>
                      <td>
                        It is a push button switch provided for conducting a Lamp Test
                        to verify whether all the lamps on the LCU panel are working. This
                        confirms the health status of all the lamps provided.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td align="center">9</td>
                      <td>Fuse-1 &amp; 2</td>
                      <td>
                        Fuse-1 connected across single phase input while fuse-2 connected
                        across 3 phase input. These fuses protect the LCU from excessive current.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td align="center">10</td>
                      <td>Remote Selected Indicator</td>
                      <td>Illuminated when remote selected.</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>Inputs / Outputs of LCU</h6>
              </para>
              <para
  >The major inputs and outputs of the LCU are shown in Fig. 1.45.</para
  >
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_45.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.45: Inputs / Outputs of LCU</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>LCU connector details</h6>
              </para>
              <para>
                The
                details of connectors located at bottom of the LCU are shown in the
                Table-2 below:
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_45_2.gif"
  ></graphic>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>Table-2: LCU connector details</h6>
              </para
  >
              <para>
                <table frame="box" rules="all">
                  <colgroup>
                    <col/>
                    <col/>
                    <col/>
                    <col/>
                  </colgroup>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td align="center">
                        <h6>Connector No.</h6>
