            <section id="1.4.1.4.2 LCU-CPU Card" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.4.2 LCU-CPU Card</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  The LCU CPU card is mounted in C-Channel in the middle
                  of the enclosure. The functions of this card are as follows:
                </para>
                <para>(a) Accept 50 analog input signals from 10 FVA sensors.</para>
                <para>
                  (b)
                  Processes analog input signals and converts them into digital
                  data.
                </para>
                <para>(c) Generate Ready and Available status signals.</para>
                <para>(d) Sends status to the RCU and PC/cabinet via serial link RS485.</para>
                <para>(e) Receive barrel feedback signal from EDL.</para>
                <para>
                  (f) Generate +5V, -5V, 3.3V, &amp; 5V REF power supplies required
                  to its internal circuitry.
                </para>

                <para>
                  <h6>Block diagram description</h6>
                </para>
                <para>
                  The
                  block diagram of LCU CPU Card is shown in Fig. 1.49. It consists of
                  the following blocks:
                </para>
                <para>(a) Input signal conditioning block</para>
                <para>(b) Controller block</para>
                <para>(c) Output signal conditioning block</para>
                <para>(d) Communication block</para>
                <para>(e) DC-DC convertor block</para>

                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_49.gif"></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.49: Block diagram of LCU CPU Card</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
                <para>
                  This card contains various sections like power
                  supply, Analog input, Digital input, Digital output, Serial port,
                  CPU. Power Supply section contains various DC to DC Converters which
                  provide different voltage levels to various ICs in the circuitry and
                  also provide isolated ground. Analog input section will collect 50
                  Analog inputs from sensors and provide it to controller on single
                  analog input one after another by multiplexing it. Digital input section
                  will gather digital inputs from switches and provide it to controller
                  for operation. Digital output section contents 20 outputs which indicate
                  status of Analog inputs. 2 serial (UART) ports will communicate with
                  RCU CPU card and Processing Cabinet &amp; will send status of analog
                  inputs to RCU and Processing continuously every 1 second.
                </para>
                <para
  >
                  <h6>Circuit Description</h6>
                </para>

                <para>
                  The circuit description
                  of this card is explained below:
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>
                    (a) Analog Input
                    Block:
                  </h6>Analog input section accepts 4 to 20 rnA analog input
                  from the sensors and provides it to CPU for operation. This card is
                  integrated with ten 8-channel multiplexers (CD4051), ICs U17, U18,
                  U19, U20, U21, U22, U23, U24, U25 &amp; U26. Each multiplexer receives
                  five analog inputs (PRES, VENT, SAFE, ARM, OPRES) corresponding to
                  one barrel such that a total of 50 analog inputs receive from the
                  sensors. All inputs are of 4 to 20mA except only resistor input is
                  impedance quantity. Each multiplexer selects one input on corresponding
                  time slice and provides its output to the IC IS0-122, analog isolator.
                  It gives an isolated input to ADC channel of CPU. Selection of particular
                  sensor output on decided time slice is done by CPU using SPI I/O ex-pander
                  IC MCP23S17 &amp; MCP23S08.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>(b) Digital Input Block:</h6
  > All switches located on front panel provide an output of 24V. Five
                  digital inputs are ENABLE, SAFE, LOCAL ARM, REMOTE, Lamp Test. Isolation
                  provided before switch output goes to CPU input. Voltage level also
                  shifted to 5V using opto-coupler IC MCT6 as input.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6
  >(c) Digital Output Block:</h6> This card has 20 digital outputs,
                  of which, 10 correspond to ‘(AVL) Available’ and 10 ‘RDY (Ready)’.
                  One Available &amp; Ready lamp each cater for one barrel to indicate
                  its status. Depends on ENABLE switch (ON) and STPR flag set corresponding
                  barrel Available lamp turns ON. Where if LOCAL ARM switch is ON as
                  well as Available output for corresponding barrel is set then RDY(Ready)
                  output for that barrel is set.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>(d) Controller block:</h6
  > The CPU card is built around the 16-bit microcontroller, IC-U1.
                  It accepts all analog inputs, processes and converts them into digital
                  data. First, it sets select lines of ADC MUX and reads analog inputs
                  for each barrel. It saves status of all 50 analog inputs to memory
                  array Ml. It processes the same and creates copy of it M2. From here
                  it creates 32-byte data which is then sent on both of the serial ports.
                  As well as considering different conditions it sets and resets available
                  and ready digital outputs. The IC-U1 contains the program (software)
                  and can be programmed using external connector CN2 provided on the
                  card. The clock to the U1 is provided by a 16 MHz crystal oscillator,
                  Y1.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>(e) Communication block:</h6> There are 2 serial
                  ports provided on LCU CPU Card, one for communicating with RCU and
                  the other for external use (Processing Cabinet). The serial ports
                  are isolated from CPU using high speed isolation IC IL717. It works
                  on RS485 (DART) protocol using IC MAX485.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>
                    (f) Power
                    Supply:
                  </h6>This block consists of 3 DC to DC converters which provides
                  3 different output voltage levels such as +3.3V, +5V, -5V etc. It
                  provides constant voltage to different ICs in the circuitry as well
                  as provides isolated ground. All DC to DC converters accepts 24V DC
                  input.
                </para>
                <para>
                  The LED indicators located on the facial of the
                  CPU card are as follows:
                </para>
                <para>
                  (a) 5V: This LED glows red when
                  5VREF output is available to the card.
                </para>
                <para>
                  (b) 3.3V: This
                  LED glows red when 3.3V output is available to the card.
                </para>
                <para
  >
                  (c) +5V: This LED glows green when +5V output is available to the
                  card.
                </para>
                <para>
                  (d) -5V: This LED glows red when -5V output is available
                  to the card.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>CPU Card connector details</h6>
                </para
  >
                <para>
                  The details of connectors located at facial of this card are
                  shown in the Table-4 below:
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>
                    Table-4: CPU Card connector’s
                    details
                  </h6>
                </para>
                <para>
                  <table frame="box" rules="all">
