              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.1.4.3 Power Supply Card" level="6">
              <title>1.4.1.4.3 Power Supply Card</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  The power supply card is mounted on the studs provided
                  inside the enclosure. It acts as an interface between the ships power
                  supply and power supplies of the various cards in the LCU. This card
                  accepts 115VAC, 50/60Hz, 1Ø or 380VAC/415VAC/450VAC, 50/60Hz, 3Ø from
                  the ship and converts it to the 24 VDC. It distributes 24VDC to the
                  LCU PLD Card and LCU CPU Card. The functions of power supply card
                  are as follows:
                </para>


                <para>
                  (a)
                  Convert 115VAC, 50/60Hz, 1Ø or 380VAC/415VAC/450VAC, 50/60Hz,
                  3Ø to 24V.
                </para>
                <para>(b) Distribute 24V DC supply to LCU CPU Card and LCU PLD Card.</para>
                <para>(c) Protects against spurious voltages and currents.</para>
                <para>
                  (d)  Display the availability of the power supply by means of glowing
                  LED on front panel
                </para>


                <para>
                  <h6>Functional Description</h6>
                </para>


                <para>
                  The power supply card consists of R Core Transformer,
                  Power Supply Unit (PSU), Filter and DC-DC converters. The 2 phases
                  of 380VAC/415VAC/450VAC, 50/60Hz, 3Ø supply coming from the ships
                  mains is fed to the primary of the transformer through fuse 1. It
                  steps it down to 115V. This is given as input to the rectifier. The
                  rectifier output is “OR”ed and routed to a filter. The filter eliminates
                  line spikes and spurious line interferences. The filtered output voltage
                  is then routed to the ON/OFF Switch located on LCU front panel. When
                  switched ON the LED lights up and power supply routes to the DC-DC
                  converter. It converts input voltage to 24VDC/50W. The output is then
                  distributed to the CPU card and PLD card. The power supply card is
                  provisioned with 2 different inputs, 3 phase and 1 phase, either can
                  be used based on the power supply availability.
                </para>

              </content>
            </section>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.1.5 Sounder" level="5">
            <title>1.4.1.5 Sounder</title>
            <content>
              <para>
                The sounder is a two-toned alarm located inside the
                EDL. It is used to warn personnel when the firing mode selected that
                is, when 3-way Key Switch is momentarily changed to LOCAL ARM on LCU
                or REMOTE ARM on RCU. Location of the sounder within the Carcass is
                shown in Fig. 1.51.
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_51.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.51: Location of the Sounder</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                The EDL incorporates a sounder which is activated
                when the following conditions are met:
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>
                  (a) Under LOCAL
                  Control:
                </h6>
              </para>
              <para>
                (i) The LCU, on the EDL in use, is switched
                ON
              </para>
              <para>
                (ii) SAFE/ENABLE switch, on the EDL in use, is set
                to ENABLE.
              </para>
              <para>
                (iii) LOCAL ARM/SAFE/REMOTE switch, on the
                EDL in use, is set to LOCAL ARM.
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>
                  (b) Under REMOTE
                  Control:
                </h6>
              </para>
              <para>
                (i) The LCU, on the EDL in use, is switched
                ON
              </para>
              <para>
                (ii) SAFE/ENABLE Key Switch, on the EDL in use, is
                set to ENABLE
              </para>
              <para>
                (iii) LOCAL ARM/SAFE/REMOTE Key Switch,
                on the EDL in use, is set to REMOTE
              </para>
              <para>
                (iv) RCU is switched
                ON
              </para>
              <para>
                (v) AUTO/MANUAL Key Switch, on the RCU in use, is set
                to AUTO.
              </para>
              <para>
                (vi) “REMOTEARM/SAFE/AUTO ARM” Key Switch
                is set to REMOTE ARM.
              </para>
            </content>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.1.6 Launcher electrical connections" level="5">
            <title>1.4.1.6 Launcher electrical connections</title>
            <content>
              <para>
                Functional block diagram of the electrical connections
                of the launcher is shown in Fig. 1.52. The electrical interfaces of
                the EDL consists of the following:
              </para>
              <para>
                1. Electrical interface
                between EDL and LCU
              </para>
              <para>
                2. Electrical interface between LCU
                and FVA
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_52.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>
                    Fig. 1.52: Functional Block Diagram-Launcher Electrical
                    Connections
                  </figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
            </content>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.1.7 Interface between EDL and LCU" level="5">
            <title>1.4.1.7 Interface between EDL and LCU</title>
            <content>
              <para>
                The electrical interface between the LCU and the EDL
                consists of a cable harness consisting of 3 cables as shown in Fig.
                1.53. The functions of the three cables are as follows:
              </para>
              <para
  >
                (a) A 5-core cable (J1) is used to receive 3phase/1phase power supply
                from the ships electrical supply.
              </para>
              <para>
                (b) A 12 core RS485
                communication cable (J3) is used to convey the status of the launcher
                to the Cabinet and the RCU
              </para>
              <para>
                (c) A 36-core cable (J2), from
                the RCU, is used to receive firing pulse signals and for sounder operation.
              </para
  >
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_53.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.53: Electrical interface between LCU &amp; EDL</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>Electrical interface between LCU and FVA</h6
  >
              </para>
              <para>
                The electrical interface between the LCU and the FVA
                consists of a cable harness consisting of 2 cables as shown in Fig.
                1.54. The functions of the two cables are as follows:
              </para>
              <para
  >(a) A 10-core feedback status line is used to convey the following:</para
  >
              <para>
                <ol type="i">
                  <li>EAD status signal</li>
                  <li>Pressure sensor signal</li>
                  <li>
                    5 way Mechanical Selector Switch position signal (SAFE,ARM and
                    VENT)
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </para>
              <para>
                (b) A 3-core cable is used to convey the firing
                pulse to the solenoid
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_54.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.54: Electrical interface between LCU and FVA</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                The LCU interfaces are shown in the Fig. 1.55
                below:
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_55.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.55: LCU Interfaces</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>Electrical &amp; Pneumatic Lines</h6>
              </para
  >
              <para>
                A functional diagram showing all electrical and pneumatic lines
                of the EDL is shown in Fig. 1.56.
              </para>
              <para>
