            <para>
              <h6>Hardware Implementation of the RCU</h6>
            </para
  >
            <para>The wiring block diagram of RCU is shown in Fig. 1.60.</para
  >
            <para>
              The RCU hardware is integrated with the following hardware
              in a 19” inches enclosure.
            </para>
            <para>
              <ol type="1">
                <li>RCU PLD Card (4 No’s)</li>
                <li>RCU CPU Card (2 No’s)</li>
                <li>Power Supply Card (2 No’s)</li>
                <li>Autofire Card</li>
                <li>Motherboard</li>
              </ol>
            </para>
            <para>
              The RCU has 2 Power Supply cards (PSU 1 and PSU
              2), 3 CPU cards (CPU 1, CPU 2and CPU3/Cabinet), 1 Auto fire Card and
              4 PLD cards (PLD 1, PLD2, PLD 3 and PLD 4). 1 Power Supply Card, 1
              CPU card and 2 PLD cards for each EDL. The RCU also has 1 RCU Auto
              fire, CPU card (CPU3/Cabinet) . These cards are mounted in the 19-inch
              rack, interconnected by a motherboard. The PLD cards are used for
              fire control, one card controls 5 barrels. The output of the PLD card
              is a firing pulse to the solenoid valve and also gives a signal to
              the sounder. The CPU card (CPU 1 and CPU 2) is used for displaying
              the status of the EDL and for communications. Launcher available/ready
              indications for each launcher are also sent from this card. ‘D’ located
              in PLD Card-1, 2, 3 &amp; 4 is a driver whose output is given to the
              solenoid valve, T is a monostable multi-vibrator which is used for
              timing the output pulse.. The input power supply to these cards 24V
              DC, which comes from power supply card. The RCU accommodates independent
              power supply cards cater for PORT &amp; STBD Launchers. Power redundancy
              is provided for the Auto fire CPU card (CPU3/Cabinet) and Auto fire
              PLD card. <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Fig_1_60_Wiring_Block_diagram_RCU.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="user">
                Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
              </a>
            </para>
            <para>
              <figure>
                <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_60.gif"></graphic>
                <figtitle>Fig. 1.60: Wiring Block diagram-RCU</figtitle>
              </figure>
            </para>
            <para>
              <h6>RCU Interfaces</h6
  >
            </para>
            <para>The RCU interfaces are shown in the Fig. 1.63 below:</para
  >
            <para>
              <figure>
                <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_63.gif"> </graphic>
                <figtitle>Fig. 1.63: RCU Interfaces</figtitle>
              </figure>
            </para>
          </content>
          <section id="1.4.2.1 RCU PLD Card" level="5">
            <title>1.4.2.1 RCU PLD Card</title>
            <content>
              <para>
                The RCU accommodates 4 PLD Cards, 2 PLD Cards for each
                EDL. PLD Cards, PLD1, PLD2, PLD3 &amp; PLD4, mounted on Slot 8, 9,
                2 &amp; 3 of the motherboard respectively. +5V, -5V, 3.3V &amp; 5V
                REF power supplies required are generated by the power supply card.
                The functions of these cards are as follows:
              </para>
              <para>(a) Receive 10-bit auto fire commands from the Auto fire PLD Card.</para>
              <para>(b) Receive 10-bit Remote fire commands from the front Push switches.</para>

              <para>
                <h6>Block diagram description</h6>
              </para>
              <para>
                The
                block diagram of the RCU PLD card is shown Fig. 1.61.
              </para>
              <para
  >
                For schematic diagram of RCU PLD Card, <h6>

                  <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_3_4.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="user">
                    Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
                  </a>
                </h6>
              </para
  >
              <para>
                It consists of Digital inputs block, Controller block (PLD),
                Digital outputs block and Power supply block.
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_61.gif"></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.61: Block diagram of RCU PLD Card</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                The description each block is shown in the following
                paragraphs:
              </para>
              <para>
                <ol type="a">
                  <li>
                    <h6>Digital inputs block: </h6>LCU have 14 digital inputs, of
                    which, 8 are isolated and 6 are non-isolated. Isolated digital inputs
                    pertain to Remote fire. It takes 24V DC input signal from the system
                    and converts it to 5V output for PLD as input. Non-isolated digital
                    inputs pertain to Auto fire. It takes 5VDC input signal from system
                    to PLD.
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <h6>Controller block:</h6> This block takes inputs from the isolated
                    and non-isolated input from the system and generate output as per
                    internal logic. PLD is operating on maximum 5V supply voltage. PLD
                    is having ISP programming capability.
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <h6>Digital outputs block:</h6> RCU is having total 6 Nos of isolated
                    outputs. It takes 5VDC input from the PLD and converts it to 24VDC
                    output signal for driving the solenoid.
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <h6>Power supply block: </h6>This section has DC-DC converter.
                    It takes 24V DC/200mA and gives 5VDC/500mA output.
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>Logical description:</h6> RCU PLD is operating
                in 2 modes, Auto fire and Remote fire. When ENABLE signal is given
                to RCU then RCU take action on Auto fire and Remote fire input signal
                and generate respected outputs. If ENABLE signal is not present then
                RCU will not take any action.
              </para>
              <para>
                <ol type="a">
                  <li>
                    <para>
                      <h6>Auto Fire mode: </h6>When the input signals ENABLE,
                      AUTO, AUTO FIRE-1 inputs are given to the PLD then PLD will check
                      following condition true then PLD will ON the Solenoid output-1 for
                      time 1.4 to 1.5 sec and then OFF. If you are in Auto fire mode and
                      give any Remote fire input signal PLD will not generate outputs
                    </para
  >
                    <para>Solenoid 1 = Enable &amp; Auto &amp; Auto Fire 1 &amp; Timer1</para
  >
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <para>
                      <h6>Remote Fire mode:</h6> When the input signals ENABLE,
                      REMOTE, REMOTE FIRE-1 inputs are given to the PLD then PLD will check
                      following condition true then PLD will ON the Solenoid output-1 for
                      time 1.4 to 1.5 sec and then OFF. If you are in Remote fire mode and
                      give any Auto fire input signal PLD will not generate outputs.
                    </para
  >
                    <para>
                      Solenoid 1 = Enable &amp; Remote &amp; Remote Fire 1 &amp;
                      Timer1
                    </para>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </para>
            </content>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.2.2 RCU CPU Card" level="5">
            <title>1.4.2.2 RCU CPU Card</title>
            <content>
              <para>
                For schematic diagram of RCU CPU Card, <h6>
                  <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_3_6.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="user">
                    Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
                  </a>
                </h6
  >
              </para>
              <para>
                The RCU accommodates 3 CPU Cards, CPU1, CPU2 &amp;
                CPU3 (Cabinet), mounted on Slot 6, 5 &amp; 4 of the motherboard respectively.
                The functions of CPU1 and CPU2 cards are as follows:
              </para>
              <para>
                <ol
          type="a">
                  <li>Accept 32-byte data coming from Launcher.</li>
                  <li>Processes 32-byte data and converts them into digital data.</li>
                  <li>
                    Generate 10 bit each ‘RDY (Ready)’ &amp; ‘AVL (Available)’ commands
                    from 32-byte data.
                  </li>
                  <li>Display status of each Launcher.</li>
                  <li>
                    Generate +5V, -5V, 3.3V, &amp; 5V REF power supplies required
                    to its circuitry.
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>Schematic description: </h6>The functioning
                and operation of the RCU CPU1 and CPU2 Cards are different from the
                LCU CPU, in that there is no data to be taken from the FVA and checked
                for availability and readiness. These cards are not interchangeable.
                The third CPU card is used when the RCU is put to Auto fire mode.
              </para
  >
              <para>
                For the schematic diagram of RCU Auto fire, refer to <h6>
                  <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_3_7.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="user">
                    Plate 3.6(a)
                    <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
                  </a>
                </h6>
              </para>
            </content>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.2.3 Power Supply Card" level="5">
            <title>1.4.2.3 Power Supply Card</title>
            <content>

              <para>
                The functioning and operation of the power
                supply card of RCU is identical to that of the LCU power supply card.
                These cards are interchangeable.
              </para>

            </content>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.2.4 Motherboard" level="5">
            <title>1.4.2.4 Motherboard</title>
            <content>

              <para>
                The RCU motherboard is mounted at bottom of the 19”
                rack. It contains different connectors on which various cards are
                plugged. The external inter connections are terminated on different
                types of connectors on backplane via connector panel. The backplane
                distributes firing signals, communication paths and power supplies
                required for various cards in the rack.
              </para>

            </content>
          </section>
        </section>
        <section id="1.4.3 Winch" level="4">
          <title>1.4.3 Winch</title>
          <content>
            <para>
              <h6>Purpose</h6>
              <para>
                For Introduction to Winch,
                <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V7_intro_winch.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
                  Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
                </a>
              </para>
            </para>
            <para>
              The Winch is used to deploy and recover the Fiber Optic Tow Cable (FOTC) which is deployed and recovered through a fairlead located at the stern of the ship. The Winch can be operated locally from the MCP.
            </para>
            <para>
              <h6>Brief Description</h6>
            </para>
            <para>
              The
              pictorial view of Winch is shown in Fig. 1.64 (a) &amp; (b).
            </para
  >
            <para>
              For Winch wiring layout,<h6>
                <a
          onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_3_10.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="user">
                  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
                </a>
              </h6>
            </para>
            <para>
              The Winch consists
              of a single drum whose shaft is driven by an electric motor through
              a gear box. Electric operation of the winch is through a Main Control
              Panel (MCP), a hand wheel is provided for manually rotating the winch
              drum in case of non-availability of electric control. A Level Wind
              assembly located at forward of the winch drum acts as a cable guide
              mechanism controlling the lateral movement of the cable when wound
              on the drum i.e. during recovery. Level Wind assembly is fitted with
              a hand wheel for rotating it manually in case of power failure. A
              drum brake mounted on a drum flange is provided for locking the winch
              during maintenance. The winch and its components are mounted on a
              winch plinth, the plinth is welded to the ship’s deck.
            </para>
            <para
  >
              <figure>
                <graphic
                fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_64(a).gif"
  ></graphic>
                <figtitle>Fig. 1.64(a): Isometric view of Winch</figtitle>
              </figure>
            </para>
            <para>
              <figure>
                <graphic
                fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_64(b).gif"
  ></graphic>
                <figtitle>Fig. 1.64(b): Front view of Winch</figtitle>
              </figure>
            </para>
            <para>
              <h6>Features of Winch</h6>
            </para>
            <para>
              The following
              are the features of the Winch:
            </para>


            <para>(a) The winch can deploy the complete tow within 25 minutes.</para>
            <para>(b) Recovery of the complete tow within 30 minutes</para>
            <para>
              (c) The winch can tow and operate a fully deployed system at platform
              speeds up to A9 knots.
            </para>
            <para>
              (d) The winch can deploy/recover the towed sub-system upto and including
              Sea State 7.
            </para>
            <para>
              (e) The winch is capable of towing a fully deployed system upto and
              including Sea State 8.
            </para>
            <para>
              (f) In the absence of electrical power, the winch will not be capable
              of powered deployment or recovery; it is possible to manually recover
              the tow.
            </para>
            <para>
              (g) The Winch is capable of a warm re-start to full functionality
              within  1 minute.
            </para>
            <para>
              (h) The Winch is capable of being fully functional from its powered
              down state within 2 minutes.
            </para>


            <para>
              <h6>Main Units of Winch</h6>
            </para>
            <para>
              The block
              diagram of Winch is shown in Fig. 1.65.
            </para>
            <para>
              The main units
              of the Winch are as follows:
            </para>
            <para>
              <ol type="1">
                <li>Winch Drum Assembly</li>
                <li>Worm &amp; Worm Gear Box Assembly</li>
                <li>Drum Brake Assembly</li>
                <li>Encoder Housing Assembly</li>
                <li>Winch Drum Motor with Motor Terminal Box</li>
                <li>Level Wind Assembly</li>
                <li>Slip Ring Assembly </li>
                <li>Slip Ring Junction Box (SRJB)</li>
                <li>Winch Drum Junction Box (WDJB)</li>
                <li>Main Control Panel (MCP)</li>
                <li>Fair Lead Assembly with its Plinth</li>
                <li>Winch Plinth Assembly</li>
              </ol>
            </para>
            <para>
              The description of each unit is explained in the
              following paragraphs.
            </para>
            <para>
              <figure>
                <graphic
                fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_65.gif"
  ></graphic>
                <figtitle>Fig. 1.65: Block Diagram of Winch</figtitle>
              </figure>
            </para>

          </content>
          <section id="1.4.3.1 Winch Drum Assembly" level="5">
            <title>1.4.3.1 Winch Drum Assembly</title>
            <content>
              <para>
                See Fig. 1.66 for a pictorial view of Winch Drum &amp;
                Flange.
              </para>
              <para>
                The winch drum has a Guide sleeve its having grooved
                surface and is used to store or spool the FOTC, it also houses the
                Optical Repeater and other electronic components in Winch Drum Junction
                Box (WDJB). The drum houses the Winch Drum Junction Box (WDJB), containing
                the deck end of the FOTC and its deck end connector. Access to the
                junction box is provided through that are water tight when covered.
                It provides a mounting surface for the FOTC mating connector. The
                surface provides a watertight seal between the winch drum and the
                FOTC mating connector.
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic
                  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_66.gif"
  ></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.66: Winch Drum &amp; Flange</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
            </content>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.3.2 Worm  Worm Gear Box Assembly" level="5">
            <title>1.4.3.2 Worm &amp; Worm Gear Box Assembly </title>
            <content>
              <para>
                A pictorial view of Worm &amp; Worm Gear Box Assembly
                is shown in Fig. 1.67
              </para>
              <para>
                The winch drum is rotated by an
                electric motor through a gear box containing a worm gear assembly.
                The worm gear has a self-locking system and can sustain a brake load
                of 44.5kN. The winch drum can be rotated through this gear box from
                10 to 15 rpm.
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic
                  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_67.gif"
  ></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.67: Worm &amp; Worm Gear Box Assembly</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
            </content>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.3.3 Drum Brake Assembly" level="5">
            <title>1.4.3.3 Drum Brake Assembly</title>
            <content>
              <para>Fig. 1.68 shows the drum brake assembly.</para>
              <para
  >
                The Drum Brake is used to manually lock/release the winch drum. The
                brake is made out of an WA8 material and mounted on the Drum Flange.
                A hand wheel is provided for operating the brake. The brake has a
                holding capacity of 44.5kN without slippage in wet conditions.
              </para
  >
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic
                  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_68.gif"
  ></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.68: Representation of Drum Brake Assembly</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
            </content>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.3.4 Encoder Housing Assembly" level="5">
            <title>1.4.3.4 Encoder Housing Assembly</title>
            <content>
              <para>An inner view of Encoder housing is shown in Fig. 1.69</para
  >

              <para>
                The Encoder Housing
                is attached to the Drum Shaft at Port side on the support structure.
                It is fitted along with Rotary Encoder and Rotary Cam Limit Switch
                to measure length deployed from Winch Drum. Interface of Rotary Encoder
                and Rotary cam limit switch along with drum shaft is achieved by Timing
                belt mechanism, which transfers the drum rotation to Rotary Encoder
                and Rotary Cam Limit Switch.
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic
                  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_69.gif"
  ></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.69: Encoder Housing</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
            </content>
            <section id="1.4.3.4.1 Rotary Cam limit switch" level="6">
              <title>1.4.3.4.1 Rotary Cam limit switch</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  The logic diagram of the limit switch is shown in Fig.
                  1.70.
                </para>

                <para>
                  The configuration
                  of the limit switch interface is shown in Fig. 1.71
                </para>
                <para>
                  This
                  switch is mounted on the base of the Encoder housing. It is used to
                  control and measure the amount of FOTC deployed/recovered by reading/counting
                  the number of revolutions of the drum shaft with timing belt, the
                  switch sends the FOTC cable length status to the Cabinet. The drum
                  shaft is attached to the shaft of the rotary cam limit switch along
                  with a timing belt to pass the mechanical rotation. The rotary cam
                  limit switch operates on +24V DC from MCP for Run off and Negative
                  recovery and +12 VDC from Cabinet for length-oriented switch sensing.
                  The specifications of Rotary Cam limit switch are as follows:
                </para>



                <para>(a) Total number of Contacts:   5 </para>
                <para>(b) Gear Ratio:   315:1</para>
                <para>(c) Rating:   48 VDC / 1.5 A</para>


                <para>
                  The Rotary Cam limit switch is integrated with 5
                  limit switches whose function is described below:
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic
                    fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_70.gif"
  ></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.70: Limit switch logic diagram</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>(a)</h6>Switch 1 (SW 1): During deployment
                  this switch will close (enable) when 466 meter or less of Tow cable
                  length is still remaining on the winch drum. During recovery, SW 1
                  opens (disables) when more than 466 meter of Tow cable length on Drum.
                  This switch remains open when emergency stop button is pressed from
                  MCP. It also sends cable length status to Cabinet.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6
  >(b)</h6>Switch 2 (SW2): During deployment this switch will close
                  (enable) when 305 meter or less of Tow Cable length is still remaining
                  on the winch drum. During recovery, SW2 opens (disables) when 305
                  m of Tow Cable length is on drum. The switch remains open when emergency
                  stop button is pressed from MCP. It also sends cable length status
                  to Cabinet.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>(c)</h6>Switch 3 (SW3): During deployment
                  this switch will close (enable) when 75 meter or less of Tow Cable
                  length is still remaining on the winch drum. During recovery SW3 opens
                  (disables) when more than 75 meters of Tow Cable length on drum. The
                  switch remains open when emergency stop button is pressed from MCP.
                  It also sends cable length status to Cabinet.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>(d)</h6
  >Switch 4 (SW4): The SW4 is used as an ‘Over Release Stop’ on the
                  drum. SW4 stops the winch by activating a “run off” stop so that the
                  Tow Cable cannot be extended greater than its length. The “run off”
                  is normally preconfigured to three turns (7 meter or less) remaining
                  on the winch drum, this happens when the status of SW1 is changed
                  from open (disable) to close (enable).
                </para>
                <para>
                  The “run off” stop
                  is provided with a maintenance override function to disable the run-off
                  stop for cleaning and maintenance. The functionality of the “run off”
                  stop is similar to the Emergency Stop push button switch with the
                  following exceptions:
                  <para>(i)	Once engaged, the Emergency stop prevents the winch from veering until it is manually reset</para>
                  <para>(ii) Once engaged, the Emergency stop allows the winch to be hauled</para>
                </para>
                <para>
                  <h6>(e)</h6> Switch 5 (SW5): This switch will close
                  after 337 rotations of drum (assuming 913 m + 100 m) and remains closed
                  till 341 rotations of drum are completed. When status of SW5 is changed
                  from open (disable) to close, no further recovery is possible by motor,
                  motor will get cut off in recovery mode. SW5 can be overridden for
                  maintenance purpose during ‘Maintenance’ mode.
                </para>
                <para>
                  <figure>
                    <graphic
                    fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_71.gif"
  ></graphic>
                    <figtitle>Fig. 1.71: Configuration of Limit switch interface</figtitle>
                  </figure>
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.3.4.2 Rotary Encoder" level="6">
              <title>1.4.3.4.2 Rotary Encoder</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  The drum shaft is attached to the shaft of the Rotary Encoder along with a
                  timing belt to detect the number of rotations of drum and its direction during
                  deployment or recovery of Tow cable. It is mounted inside the Encoder housing
                  which is located on the port side of the winch support structure.
                  The specifications of Rotary encoder are as follows:
                </para>


                <para>(a) Shaft diameter:  8 mm</para>
                <para>(b) Pulse/1 revolution:  1000</para>
                <para>(c) Supply Voltage:  24 VDC</para>
              </content>
            </section>
          </section>
