            <section id="1.4.3.5.1 Electric brake" level="6">
              <title>1.4.3.5.1 Electric brake</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  A spring energized electric brake is mounted on the
                  motor for locking the winch drum when the motor is switched OFF, the
                  brake is automatically released when the motor is powered ON. The
                  brake can be manually released and electric break disengaged from
                  motor shaft to manually turn the winch drum by loosening the release
                  screw of the brake. The specifications of the Electric brake are as
                  follows:
                </para>



                <para>(a) Braking Torque: 450 Nm</para>
                <para>(b) Brake Coil voltage: 190 VDC</para>
                <para>(c) Bridge Rectifier: Input 415 VAC / 190 VDC @ 2 Amp.</para>

              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.3.5.2 Motor Terminal Box" level="6">
              <title>1.4.3.5.2 Motor Terminal Box</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  The terminal box is mounted on top of the drum motor.
                  It houses the terminal strip on which motor wiring leads, thermistor
                  leads and anti-condensation &amp; heater cable connections are connected.
                  These are accessible in the terminal box by removing a cover plate
                  of the terminal box.
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
            <section id="1.4.3.5.3 Motor Junction Box" level="6">
              <title>1.4.3.5.3 Motor Junction Box</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  The Motor Junction box is mounted on support structure
                  (STBD) beneath the drum motor. It houses the terminal strip on which
                  Motor thermistor, Motor anti-condensation heater, Electric Brake Supply
                  and Electric Brake Feedback terminals are connected to the MCP cables.
                  These are accessible by removing a cover plate of the junction box
                </para
  >
              </content>
            </section>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.3.6 Level Wind Assembly" level="5">
            <title>1.4.3.6 Level Wind Assembly</title>
            <content>
              <para>See Fig. 1.73 for Level Wind Assembly.</para>

              <para>
                This guiding mechanism
                is used to safely recover the towed components and to correctly lay-up
                the same on the winch drum. It protects the towed components from
                damage during retrieval, Nylon 66 is used in parts of the mechanism
                that are in contact with the tow to minimize abrasion. The mechanism
                operates under a cable tension of 13.3kN and allows the operator to
                position the towed components at any desired position over the internal
                width of the drum during recovery only. The operation is controlled
                by a joystick mounted on the MCP (HMI panel).
              </para>
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic
                  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_73.gif"
  ></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.73: Level Wind Assembly</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
            </content>
            <section id="1.4.3.6.1 Level Wind Assembly-Drive" level="6">
              <title>1.4.3.6.1 Level Wind Assembly-Drive</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  The Level Wind Mechanism is driven by a variable speed
                  reversible electric motor and is operated by a single operator from
                  an MCP (HMI panel), using joystick. The joystick is spring loaded
                  to ensure it will return to the stop position when released. A “dead
                  man” switch on joystick is used to allow normal operations of the
                  MCP when activated and will stop the winch motor when released thus
                  avoids an accidental movement of level wind. The MCP panel is mounted
                  such that the operator stands to the side of the towline on the starboard
                  side of the winch and can be used to start, stop and vary the speed
                  and direction of the mechanism. Two proximity sensors are used to
                  stop motor operation at the extremities of its travel. In the absence
                  of power, the mechanism can be manually operated by means of a removable
                  handle provided on the port side of the mechanism. When the tow is
                  being deployed the mechanism is parked on the port side with one flap
                  locked in the horizontal position by a locking pin as it is not required
                  to operate during deployment. The mechanism can be switched from deployment
                  mode to recovery mode by changing the position of the guide flap from
                  horizontal position to vertical position and vice versa. The level
                  wind mechanism can be easily detached and can be slung using the lifting
                  eyes provided.
                </para>
