              <para></para>
            </content>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.3.9 Winch Drum Junction Box WDJB" level="5">
            <title>1.4.3.9 Winch Drum Junction Box (WDJB)</title>
            <content>
              <para>See Fig. 1.78 for a view of WDJB</para>

              <para>
                The winch drum junction
                box is located on the port side of the winch drum. The pigtails on
                the slip ring and FOTC end terminates in the winch drum junction box
                terminal strips and fiber optic terminations. The FOTC mating connector
                penetrates the winch drum junction box and forms a water tight seal.
              </para
  >
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic
                  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_78.gif"
  ></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.78: Winch Drum Junction Box</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
            </content>
            <section id="1.4.3.9.1 Optical Repeater" level="6">
              <title>1.4.3.9.1 Optical Repeater</title>
              <content>
                <para>
                  The optical repeater is mounted in the watertight segments
                  of the winch drum. The repeater is used to amplify the optical signals
                  from the towed array before the signal enters the optical slip rings.
                  It is capable of amplifying 1300nm, 62.5/125/optical signals as low
                  as -32dBm and provides gain to achieve a minimum output of -8dBm and
                  a maximum of 0dBm. It operates with ATM OC3c format data at a rate
                  of 155.52MHz. 24VDC is supplied to the repeater through two dedicated
                  electrical power rings on the slip ring assembly.
                </para>
              </content>
            </section>
          </section>
          <section id="1.4.3.10 Main Control Panel MCP" level="5">
            <title>1.4.3.10 Main Control Panel (MCP)</title>
            <content>
              <para>See Fig. 1.79.</para>

              <para>
                The Main Control Panel
                is used to operate the Winch drum, Level Wind Assembly and to display
                the scope of tow. The MCP has a joystick to control the operations
                of the level wind mechanism. The joystick provides variable motor
                speed and direction control of the level wind motor. The joystick
                is spring loaded to ensure its return to the stop position when released.
                A “dead man” switch is used to allow normal operations of the MCP
                when activated and will stop the winch motor when released.
              </para
  >
              <para>
                <figure>
                  <graphic
                  fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_1_79.gif"
  ></graphic>
                  <figtitle>Fig. 1.79: Controls &amp; indicators on MCP (change image</figtitle>
                </figure>
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>Main features of MCP</h6>
              </para>
              <para>
                Following
                are the main features of the MCP:
              </para>
              <para>
                (a) The Winch Drum and Level Wind Assembly can be operated by a single operator or by two operators.
              </para>
              <para>
                (b) The winch operator stands on the starboard side of the winch system during operation.
              </para>
              <para>
                (c) The MCP is mounted on the winch and can be operated in locally.
              </para>
              <para>(d) Two Joysticks operate the Winch drum and Level Wind Assembly.</para>
              <para>
                (e) The Aft joystick (Left of operator) controls the Level Wind Assembly. The joystick is moved to port side to move the Level Wind Assembly away from the operator and to starboard side to move the Level Wind Assembly towards the operator.
              </para>
              <para>
                (f) The Forward (Right of operator) controls the Winch drum. To payout the towed sub-system the joystick is moved towards Aft and to recover the towed sub-system the joystick is moved forward.
              </para>
              <!--<para>
                (g) If no Remote-Control Panel is connected to the Main Control Panel
                the system will operate in the Local mode by default even if the Remote
                push-button is operated.
              </para>
              <para>
                (h) The Emergency Stop on the Main Control Panel operates in both
                Local and Remote modes. Emergency Stop can be reset only at the Main
                Control Panel.
              </para>
              <para>
                (i) When the winch is operating in the Remote mode all controls except
                Emergency Stop are disabled on MCP.
              </para>
              <para>
                (j) All indicators on the Local panel are available on the Remote
                panel.
              </para>-->
              <para>
                <h6>Controls and indicators of MCP</h6>
              </para>
              <para
  >The controls and indicators of MCP are listed in Table-10:</para
  >
              <para>
                <h6>Table-10: Controls and indicators of MCP</h6>
              </para>
              <para
  >
                <table frame="box" rules="all">
                  <colgroup>
                    <col width="16*"/>
                    <col width="41*"/>
                    <col width="41*"/>
                  </colgroup>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td align="center">
                        <h6>Sl.No.</h6>
                      </td>
                      <td align="center">
                        <h6>Switch/Control/Indicator</h6>
                      </td>
                      <td align="center">
                        <h6>Significance</h6>
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">1</td>
                      <td valign="top">System Ready Indicator</td>
                      <td>
                        This lamp will glow when Emergency control is Released, Standby/Operation
                        switch on operation, VFD 1 No Fault, VFD 2 No Fault, Supply Healthy.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">2</td>
                      <td valign="top">Supply Available Indicator</td>
                      <td>
                        Shows the availability of 380V/415V/450VAC 50Hz/60Hz, 3&#8709; voltage
                        from the ship’s main power supply.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">3</td>
                      <td valign="top">Standby / Operation Key Switch</td>
                      <td>
                        <para>
                          In standby, the MCP is switched ON, the system is in immediate
                          readiness, but no deployment or recover is possible. In this mode,
                          subunits Level Wind VFD and Drum VFD are in shutdown.
                        </para>
                        <para
  >In Operation, System is Ready for Deployment or Recovery.</para>
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">4</td>
                      <td valign="top">Over temp indicator</td>
                      <td>
                        It indicates over temperature of the motor. If temperature exceeds
                        800C, then this lamp will light up. This is just a warning. This will
                        not hamper any operation like recovery and deployment of winch.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">5</td>
                      <td valign="top">Maintenance switch </td>
                      <td>
                        This switch allows the operator to select Maintenance mode. When
                        this switch is set to Maintenance mode, Limit switches for RUN OFF
                        and OVER RECOVERY are bypassed. Allowing user to run winch without
                        any limitation. Note: TO BE DONE BY AUTHORISED PERSON ONLY.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">6</td>
                      <td valign="top">Level Wind Joystick</td>
                      <td>
                        <para>
                          Movement of the level wind Starboard to port (away from
                          the operator) and starboard to port (towards to the operator) is by
                          the joystick on the left side of the panel with Dead Man Switch.
                        </para
  >
                        <para>
                          It Provides variable speed and direction control of the Level
                          Wind Motor; it has a spring return to the stop position. The joystick
                          has a “Dead man” switch which allows normal operation of the joystick
                          when the switch is activated and will stop the Level wind motor when
                          the switch is released.
                        </para>
                        <para>
                          <note>
                            <para style="color:red">NOTE:Level wind will operate only during recovery.</para>
                          </note>
                        </para>
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">7</td>
                      <td valign="top">Winch Drum Joystick</td>
                      <td>
                        <para>
                          Movement of the Winch Drum in Recovery direction by Move
                          the joystick in FWD side and Movement of the Winch Drum in deployment
                          direction by Move the joystick in AFT side. Winch Drum Joystick is
                          at right side of the panel with Dead Man Switch.
                        </para>
                        <para>
                          Provides
                          variable speed and direction control of the winch motor, it has a
                          spring return to the stop position. The joystick has a “Dead man”
                          switch, which allows normal operation of the joystick when the switch
                          is activated and will stop the winch motor when the switch is released
                        </para
  >
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">8</td>
                      <td valign="top">Emergency Stop Switch</td>
                      <td>
                        <para>
                          To stop the winch in an emergency during Operation, press
                          the “Emergency Stop Switch” and ensure that the “Emergency Stop indicator”
                          comes ON.
                        </para>
                        <para>
                          To resume operation, Pull up  the “Emergency
                          Stop Switch” and ensure that the “Emergency Stop indicator” goes OFF
                          &amp; System Ready indicator turns ON
                        </para>
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">9</td>
                      <td valign="top">Display</td>
                      <td>
                        The Length and Depth of TOW which is paid out can be read on the
                        display.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">10</td>
                      <td valign="top">Brightness Control Push Button</td>
                      <td>
                        Press the “Brightness Control” to change the brightness of the
                        Length and Depth Display. Operation of the switch causes the display
                        brightness to increment one step for each press until maximum brightness
                        is reached, the display will then revert to minimum brightness.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">11</td>
                      <td valign="top">Zero Dimmer Push Button</td>
                      <td>
                        Press the “Zero Dimmer” switch to avoid any visible light from
                        the MCP Panel.  Press the “Zero Dimmer” switch again for normal operation.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">12</td>
                      <td valign="top">Cable Reset Push Button</td>
                      <td>To set the tow value to zero, press the “Cable Reset” switch. </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">13</td>
                      <td valign="top">Drive Reset Push Button</td>
                      <td>
                        It resets the VFD drive when it is in error mode. It is a switch
                        used to acknowledge the render buzzer. It does not give a sound when
                        switches off the system from remote control panel.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">14</td>
                      <td valign="top">Lamp Test Push Button</td>
                      <td>Press this button to check the serviceability of all lamps.</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top">15</td>
                      <td valign="top">Alarm Render</td>
                      <td>
                        <para>
                          The Render Alarm is a normally close contact which operates
                          to indicate that the drum is not rotating while the electric brake
                          is applied. If the tow continues to render with the electric brake
                          applied the contacts open and remain open till the tow renders. The
                          alarm functions when Supply Available, System Ready (Local/Remote)
                          and Emergency stop ON or OFF.
                        </para>
                        <para>
                          When the winch is operated
                          in Remote Mode any movement or operation of the winch is preceded
                          by an audible alarm warning at the winch.
                        </para>
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </para>
              <para>
                <h6>Hardware Implementation of the MCP</h6>
              </para
  >
              <para>See Fig. 1.80 for inner view of MCP.</para>
              <para>
                The block
                diagram of MCP is shown in Fig.1.81
              </para>
              <para>
                The MCP is integrated
                with the following hardware:
              </para>
              <para>
                <ol type="1">
                  <li>24VDC Power Supply Unit</li>
                  <li>Drum Motor VFD</li>
                  <li>Level Wind Motor VFD</li>
                  <li>Contactors (2 No’s)</li>
                  <li>MCB (3 No’s)</li>
                  <li>Switch Fuse Unit (SFU) </li>
