				  <section id="2.1.3 Packing Instructions " level="4">
					  <title>2.1.3 Packing Instructions </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The following instructions must be strictly adhered
							  to:
						  </para>

						  <para>
							  (a)
							  All equipment, materials and parts must be thoroughly cleaned
							  and should be free from grease, oil, rust and all other foreign matter
							  prior to packing/preservation.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (b)
							  The equipment must be packed as per the packaging document (or
							  packing list), using standard packaging materials.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (c)
							  All items and accessories waiting for packing must be covered
							  with polythene bags to prevent entry of dust / moisture.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (d)
							  The packing procedure consists of:
						  </para>

						  <para>
							  (i)
							  Primary wrapping of the item using polythene/paper/or other barrier
							  material called inner packing.
						  </para>
						  <para>(ii) Cushioning material around the inner packing.</para>
						  <para>(iii) Shipping container called outer packing.</para>
						  <para>
							  (iv)
							  Closure methods using adhesive tapes, wires, straps, nuts, bolts
							  etc.,
						  </para>



						  <para>
							  (e)
							  Finished packing cases must be normally stored under cover on
							  concrete floor to avoid attack by termites, white ants etc. In case
							  the packing cases are stored in open yard, they should be covered
							  with waterproof covering.
						  </para>

					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.1.4 Scheme of Packing" level="4">
					  <title>2.1.4 Scheme of Packing</title>
					  <section id="2.1.4.1 Wooden Crate Packing for Launcher  " level="5">
						  <title>2.1.4.1 Wooden Crate Packing for Launcher </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The Launcher consists of EDL with plinth, LCU and 10
								  in no’s FVA’s. These units are fitted on carcass. The Launcher being
								  heavy weight unit (925 Kgs), wooden panel or pallet being used should
								  have adequate thickness and strength. The packaging box sizes should
								  be appropriately selected in reference to the dimensions mentioned
								  in the  <a
			onclick="javascript:parent.treeID(&quot;Page-110_Sy&quot;);" href="#"
			id="TopicID">Para 2.1.2</a>. It shall be packed by means of wrapping water proof
								  thick polythene cover/cushioning material around the unit and taped.
								  The silica gel bags (desiccant material) shall be placed in the packing
								  case. Before final packing, Rubberized coir mating shall be provided
								  at various places between the equipment and wooden casing to protect
								  and minimize shocks during transportation and handling.
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.1.4.2 Cardboard Packing for RCU" level="5">
						  <title>2.1.4.2 Cardboard Packing for RCU</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  See  <a
			   onclick="javascript:parent.treeID(&quot;Page-110_Sy&quot;);" href="#"
			   id="TopicID">Para 2.1.2</a> for packaging box sizes of the RCU.
								  RCU being a light weight unit (20kgs), it shall be packed by means
								  of wrapping a water proof thick polythene cover around the unit. Thermocol
								  mating shall be provided at all sides of the unit to protect and minimize
								  the shocks during transportation and handling. The silica gel bags
								  shall be placed in the packing case.
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.1.4.3 Wooden Crate Packing for Winch-Gear Box " level="5">
						  <title>2.1.4.3 Wooden Crate Packing for Winch-Gear Box </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The Winch-Gear Box Assembly being a heavy weight unit
								  (3400 Kgs), wooden panel or pallet being used should have adequate
								  thickness and strength. The packaging box sizes should be appropriately
								  selected in reference to the dimensions mentioned in the  <a href="#" id="TopicID" onclick="javascript:parent.treeID(&quot;Page-110_Sy&quot;);" >Para 2.1.2.</a>
								  The whole assembly shall be packed by means of wrapping water proof
								  thick polythene cover/cushioning material around each unit and taped.
								  The shafts of Gear box assembly shall be packed by means of wrapping
								  a sheet of cardboard or flexible plastic around it. The Main Control
								  Panel (MCP) shall be wrapped with plastic bag or polythene cover/cushioning
								  material separately and taped. The silica gel bags shall be placed
								  in the packing case. Before final packing, Rubberized coir mating
								  shall be provided at various places between the equipment and wooden
								  casing to protect and minimize shocks during transportation and handling.
							  </para
  >
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section
					  id="2.1.4.4 Wooden Crate Packing for Winch-Level Wind Assembly "
					  level="5">
						  <title>2.1.4.4 Wooden Crate Packing for Winch-Level Wind Assembly </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The Winch-Level Wind Assembly being a heavy weight
								  unit (500 Kgs), wooden panel or pallet being used should have adequate
								  thickness and strength. The packaging box sizes should be appropriately
								  selected in reference to the dimensions mentioned in the <a
  onclick="javascript:parent.treeID(&quot;Page-110_Sy&quot;);" href="#"
  id="TopicID">Para 2.1.2.</a>
								  The shafts of Level Wind Assembly shall be packed by means of wrapping
								  a sheet of cardboard or flexible plastic around it. The lead screws
								  shall be packed by means of wrapping a sheet of flexible plastic around
								  it. The whole assembly shall be packed by means of wrapping water
								  proof thick polythene cover/cushioning material around each unit and
								  taped. Before final packing, Rubberized coir mating shall be provided
								  at various places between the equipment and wooden casing to protect
								  and minimize shocks during transportation and handling.
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.1.4.5 Wooden Crate Packing for Winch-Plinth" level="5">
						  <title>2.1.4.5 Wooden Crate Packing for Winch-Plinth</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The Winch Plinth being heavy weight unit (1044 Kgs),
								  wooden panel or pallet being used should have adequate thickness and
								  strength. The packaging box sizes should be appropriately selected
								  in reference to the dimensions mentioned in the <a
  onclick="javascript:parent.treeID(&quot;Page-110_Sy&quot;);" href="#"
  id="TopicID">Para 2.1.2.</a> The plinth
								  shall be packed by means of wrapping water proof thick polythene cover/cushioning
								  material around it and taped. The plinth shall be mounted on specially
								  made frames (wooden type) for transportation. These frames are bolted
								  to the wooden base of the packing cases. Before final packing, Rubberized
								  coir mating shall be provided at various places between the plinth
								  and wooden casing to protect and minimize shocks during transportation
								  and handling.
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section
					  id="2.1.4.6 Wooden Crate Packing for Winch-Fairlead with plinth  "
					  level="5">
						  <title>2.1.4.6 Wooden Crate Packing for Winch-Fairlead with plinth</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The Winch Fairlead with Plinth being heavy weight unit
								  (350 Kgs), wooden panel or pallet being used should have adequate
								  thickness and strength. The packaging box sizes should be appropriately
								  selected in reference to the dimensions mentioned in the <a
  onclick="javascript:parent.treeID(&quot;Page-110_Sy&quot;);" href="#"  id="TopicID">Para 2.1.2.</a>
								  The Winch Fairlead with plinth shall be packed by means of wrapping
								  water proof thick polythene cover/cushioning material around it and
								  taped. It shall be mounted on specially made frames (wooden type)
								  for transportation. These frames are bolted to the wooden base of
								  the packing cases. Before final packing, Rubberized coir mating shall
								  be provided at various places between the plinth and wooden casing
								  to protect and minimize shocks during transportation and handling.
							  </para
  >
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.1.4.7  Cardboard Wooden Crate Packing for Console "
					  level="5">
						  <title>2.1.4.7  Cardboard/Wooden Crate Packing for Console</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The packaging box sizes of the Console should be appropriately
								  selected in reference to the dimensions mentioned in the <a
  onclick="javascript:parent.treeID(&quot;Page-110_Sy&quot;);" href="#"
  id="TopicID">Para 2.1.2.</a>
								  The Console being a medium weight unit (40 kgs), the unit shall be
								  wrapped with plastic bag or polythene cover/cushioning material and
								  tape it. The unit shall be placed in a cardboard box by means of providing
								  thermocol mating at all sides of the unit. The silica gel bags shall
								  be placed in the packing case. The box shall be secured using packaging
								  straps. The packing case shall be placed in the wooden crate in such
								  a way that movement of internal packing case will be impossible so
								  that it can protect and minimize shocks during transportation and
								  handling. Close the wooden crate top cover and screw/nail it to its
								  structure.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <note>
									  <para style="color:red">
										  Note:	Liquid Crystal Display (LCD) is made of glass. Avoid excessive
										  mechanical shock or applying strong pressure on to the surface of
										  display area.
									  </para>
								  </note>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.1.4.8" level="5">


					  </section>
					  <section id="2.1.4.9" level="5">


					  </section>


				  </section>
				  <section id="2.1.5 Marking and Labeling" level="4">
					  <title>2.1.5 Marking and Labeling</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  Marking shall be permanent, legible. The shipping labels
							  shall be placed on the top of the box and the handling symbol on opposite
							  sides of the box. The mark must not be hand drawn. The labels and
							  symbols of all the boxes must be visible. Each unit with a package/container
							  shall be clearly marked for identification. The use of red or orange
							  should be avoided because these colours are used in the labelling
							  of dangerous goods.
						  </para>
					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.1.6 Preservation  Packing " level="4">
					  <title>2.1.6 Preservation &amp; Packing </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The following preservation/packing guidelines must
							  be followed:
						  </para>


						  <para>
							  (a)
							  Initial preservation/packing shall be carried out at the manufacturer’s
							  works; this must be valid for a period of 24 months.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (b)
							  Preservation/packing must be suitable for tropical conditions
							  and the equipment must be protected against high humidity and relevant
							  environmental conditions.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (c)
							  If storage is to be extended beyond a period of 24 months, re-preservation
							  is to be carried out for twelve-month extensions.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (d)
							  All equipment shall be adequately packed and protected with supports
							  to ensure adequate protection during all modes of transportation.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (e)
							  Re-preservation of the equipment onboard post installation must
							  be done by means of polythene wrap.
						  </para>
					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.1.7 Transportation Instructions  " level="4">
					  <title>2.1.7 Transportation Instructions  </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The following instructions must be strictly adhered
							  to:
						  </para>

						  <para>
							  (a)
							  It is prohibited to transport the equipment without permission from the respective stakeholders.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (b)
							  The equipment must be packed according to “Transit Standard Package”
							  procedures, so as to ensure the serviceability of the packaged product
							  till it reaches the destination.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (c)
							  The equipment may be transported by normal means of transport
							  viz. Rail, road, air or sea.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (d)
							  During transportation, “full weather protection” must be provided.
							  Full weather protection means avoidance of direct exposure to sin,
							  rain, water and wind. This may involve no additional protection than
							  that is provided by a lashed down tarpaulin.
						  </para>

					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.1.8 Unpacking " level="4">
					  <title>2.1.8 Unpacking </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The instructions herein shall be considered for unpacking
							  and removal of preservatives of the NTDS. The various units are divided
							  into convenient shipping sections for ease of transport and handling.
							  Before final packing in wooden cases these are wrapped in water proof
							  thick polythene covers. Rubberized coir mating is provided at various
							  places between the equipment and wooden casing to protect and minimize
							  shocks during transportation and handling. The following procedure
							  should be observed immediately on receipt of the panels:
						  </para>

						  <para>(a) Inspect the cases for any visible external damage.</para>
						  <para>
							  (b)
							  Report the transient damages, if any, to the goods carrier and
							  immediately lodge the claim with the MDSL.
						  </para>

					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.1.9 Storage" level="4">
					  <title>2.1.9 Storage</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  In case it is necessary to store the NTDS, the following
							  care should be taken:
						  </para>

						  <para>
							  (a)
							  Open the wooden cases and inspect for damages and tally the equipment
							  with the packing slip provided in each transport section. Damage if
							  any, should be reported within 2 weeks of receipt of material.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (b)
							  After inspection close all the doors, replace the polythene wrappers
							  and ensure protection against ingress of dust, moisture, vermin etc.,
							  into the panels.
						  </para>
						  <para>(c) Store in a clean, dry and covered area or building.</para>

					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.1.10 Preservation Packing " level="4">
					  <title>2.1.10 Preservation/Packing</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The following preservation/packing guidelines must
							  be followed:
						  </para>

						  <para>
							  (a)
							  Initial preservation/packing is to be carried out at the manufacturer’s
							  works; this must be valid for a period of 24 months.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (b)
							  Preservation/packing must be suitable for tropical conditions
							  and the equipment must be protected against high humidity and relevant
							  environmental conditions.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (c)
							  If storage is to be extended beyond a period of 24 months, re-preservation
							  is to be carried out for twelve-month extensions.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (d)
							  All equipment shall be adequately packed and protected with supports
							  to ensure adequate protection during all modes of transportation.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (e)
							  Each unit with a package/container shall be clearly marked for
							  identification.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (f)
							  Re-preservation of the equipment onboard post installation must
							  be done by means of polythene wrap.
						  </para>
					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.1.11 Unpacking of Equipment" level="4">
					  <title>2.1.11 Unpacking of Equipment</title>
					  <content>

						  <para>
							  (a)
							  The subunits are mounted on specially made frames for transportation.
							  These frames are bolted to the wooden base of the packing cases. The
							  top of the packing cases is to be removed to access the equipment
							  inside.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (b)
							  The necessary accessories are packed in separate packing cases.
							  These are provided with packing lists clearly identifying the items
							  contained within.
						  </para>

					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.1.12 Unpacking and Removal of Spares" level="4">
					  <title>2.1.12 Unpacking and Removal of Spares</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The NTDS is provided with onboard (OB) and B&amp;D; spares.
							  These spares are to be used by a trained maintainer as and when necessary.
							  Spares are wrapped with bubble sheets and placed in anti-static covers
							  and covering boxes. These boxes when kept in storage racks are identified
							  by the marking stickers that indicate the part number and serial number
							  of the spares within. The procedure for unpacking is to identify the
							  spare by part number and remove the required spare from the storage
							  rack.
						  </para>
					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.1.13 Initial Checks  after unpacking" level="4">
					  <title>2.1.13 Initial Checks  after unpacking</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>Carryout the following checks immediately after unpacking.</para
  >
						  <para>
							  (a)
							  Inspect the equipment and accessories for any external damage
							  such as bends, cracks, dents and any other abnormalities.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (b)
							  Inspect all controls, connectors and external fittings for loose
							  fittings, misplacements, missing parts and damages.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (c)
							  Operate all the knobs, controls and switches and check for their
							  smooth operation without applying excessive force.
						  </para>
						  <para>(d) Check that the panels are properly secured in the rack/cabinet.</para>

					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.1.14 Preservatives" level="4">
					  <title>2.1.14 Preservatives</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>Following are the general list of preservation related lubricants for guidance. In case of non-availability of specified lubricant, equivalent as suggested by the inspection agency can be used:</para>
						  <para>(a)	Winch: Grease (NLGI3 (HP) or equivalent) should be applied on Level wind lead screw, support shaft, lead screw of band brake, and locking pin of band brakes.</para>
						  <para>(b)	Electrical &amp; Electronic units – Desiccant or preservative doing equivalent function.</para>
						  <para>(c)	Fasteners &amp; threaded points - Grease NLGI3 (HP) or equivalent.</para>
						  <para>(d)	Sub-units / sub-assemblies / items (units under packing)(UUP)) are covered with VPCI blue / equivalent sheet (Vapor phase corrosion inhibitor film)</para>
						  <para>(e)	The UUP is then wrapped with thin cling film then again it is wrapped with bubble wrap &amp; a final covering of cling film.</para>
						  <para>(f)	Thermocol is used to protect protruding parts wherever required.</para>
						  <para>(g)	Small size (OBS / BDS) individual items are packed in polythene bag &amp; carton box, a small pack of silica gel is added along with the packing list.</para>

					  </content>
				  </section>
			  </section>
			  <section id="2.2 Installation Procedure" level="3">
				  <title>2.2 Installation Procedure</title>
				  <content>
					  <para>
						  <h6>Setting Up Instructions  </h6>
					  </para>
					  <para>
						  The
						  detailed setting up instructions for the NTDS including installation
						  procedure, cabinet fixation, foundation diagrams and setting to work
						  is covered in this section. No special tools are required for fixing
						  the units / cabinets. The limitations on the location and position
						  of each unit / cabinet and the configuration (inter unit connectivity)
						  diagram is also provided in this section.
					  </para>
					  <para>
						  <h6>
							  Initial
							  Inspection
						  </h6>
					  </para>
					  <para>
						  Remove all the units / cabinets from
						  the wooden packing boxes. Check the packing list for each wooden box
						  and identify the number of items including quantity and serial numbers.
						  Identify the material and carry out physical inspection of each item
						  for damages. In case of any damage, inform the concern organization
						  along with the inspection report for immediate action.
					  </para>
				  </content>
				  <section id="2.2.1 General Installation Precautions " level="4">
					  <title>2.2.1 General Installation Precautions </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The following precautions shall be taken during the
							  installation process:
						  </para>

						  <para>
							  (a)
							  The units and related cables shall be installed in an orderly
							  manner to minimize obstruction.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (b)
							  The units shall be installed such that easy maintenance operation
							  on them is possible.
						  </para>
						  <para>(c) The units shall not be installed near heat sources.</para>
						  <para>
							  (d)
							  RCU, Console, Processing Cabinet and MCP shall be so located as
							  to allow unobstructed air flow.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (e)
							  Working tools or any other device producing metallic shavings
							  or dust shall not be used near the equipment without precautions,
							  to prevent metallic pieces from entering the equipment.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (f)
							  The units shall be so installed that there is no mechanical interference
							  between them.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (g)
							  All exposed moving components shall be guarded with the exception
							  of the winch drum and the level wind screw.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (h)
							  The equipment installed in various compartments / rooms / locations
							  are interconnected through cables running on cable ducts of shafts.
							  There should be no sharp corners or anything that could damage the
							  installed cables. The cable ducts dimensions and the relative position
							  of the holes for the cable passing from one room to the other is such
							  that the cables are within the minimum bending radius.
						  </para>
					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.2.2 Interconnection between the units  " level="4">
					  <title>2.2.2 Interconnection between the units</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The interconnections between the units of NTDS are
							  to be done as per the inter unit connectivity diagram. <h6>
								  <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_4_1_Interconn_diagram.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;">
									  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>
							  </h6
  >
						  </para>
					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.2.3 Grounding requirements" level="4">
					  <title>2.2.3 Grounding requirements</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  All subsystems ‘Ground’ is connected to ‘Prime Earth
							  Point’ available on the ship. The equipment ground connection is capable
							  of protecting personnel against electrical shocks due to degradation
							  of electrically powered equipment. It is also able to refer to a fixed
							  electric potential for all the signals generated in the equipment.
						  </para
  >
						  <para>
							  The ground connection for all main units shall be established
							  through the shielding of the connector that is to be fastened to the
							  structure. The ground terminals to be connected to the EDL, RCU and
							  Winch are the standard twisted mesh flat cable/copper cable, screwed
							  onto the unit frame on one side and to the ship structure on the other
							  side.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  Ensure that all the ground terminals are well fastened
							  by means of screw/clamp/lugs with plain and spring washers. Electric
							  resistance between unit and hull terminal shall not be greater than
							  0.5 ohm.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  Measure the resistance between the prime earth
							  and unit earth points. The resistance must also be measured between
							  the Prime Earth and the Earthing Point. The impedance between the
							  Earthing points and the prime earth stud shall be &lt;0.1ohms.
						  </para
  >
					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.2.4 Air cooling requirements  " level="4">
					  <title>2.2.4 Air cooling requirements  </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  As the EDL and Winch are deck mounted units, these
							  units do not require any cooling arrangement. The MCP located on the
							  Winch has provided heat sink  inside  to dissipate heat during overheating
							  conditions.
						  </para>
					  </content>
				  </section>
