				  <section id="2.2.12 Installation Requirements " level="4">
					  <title>2.2.12 Installation Requirements </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  When attaching the systems to the deck/structure, perform
							  the following:
						  </para>

						  <para>
							  (a)
							  Before the unit/subunit is mounted on its platform, carryout visual
							  inspection and check for any defects caused during transportation.
							  Pay special attention to the connectors, impacts, scratches and the
							  tightness of the O-rings. Make sure there are no exposed metallic
							  parts and the screws are properly protected with gummed paint.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (b)
							  Follow the correct orientation of the system provided by the system
							  manufacturer.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (c)
							  Once the unit is positioned, its continuity with the structure
							  shall be measured with multimeter to verify its proper ground connection.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (d)
							  If the cables are not going to be connected immediately after
							  the attachment of the systems to the structure, the systems connectors
							  must be protected with vulcanizing tape.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (e)
							  The screws used for the systems attachment must be protected with
							  materials resistant to corrosion, such as gummed paint, in order to
							  avoid oxidation.
						  </para>

					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.2.13 Installation Procedure   " level="4">
					  <title>2.2.13 Installation Procedure</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>The installation procedure consists of:</para>

						  <para>(a) Lifting and placing the subunits at desired location.</para>
						  <para>(b) Grouting with appropriate fasteners.</para>
						  <para>
							  (c)
							  Interconnect the units as per the details provided in inter unit
							  connectivity diagram, <h6>
								  <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_4_1_Interconn_diagram.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;">
									  Plate 4.1<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>
							  </h6>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (d)
							  The units are provided with special hoisting hooks / eyebolts
							  (especially for EDLs and Winch).
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (e)
							  The deck and bulkhead fixing details for each unit is provided
							  in the installation procedures. Standard tools like double ended spanners,
							  adjustable spanners and box spanners are to be employed for this purpose.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (f)
							  Cabling: Cabling consists of preparation of cable, fixing the
							  connector on to the wires and fixing the cable to the unit. Arrangements
							  are to be used to hold the cable properly to avoid tension on the
							  wires and to have effective and proper grounding of the shield.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (g)
							  After installing the equipment, a final check must be carried
							  out. For details, <h6>
								  <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Finalchecks.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;">
									  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>
							  </h6>
						  </para>

					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.2.14 Installation of units" level="4">
					  <title>2.2.14 Installation of units</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>The installation of main units is described below:</para
  >
					  </content>
					  <section id="2.2.14.1 Expandable Device Launcher EDL  " level="5">
						  <title>2.2.14.1 Expandable Device Launcher (EDL)  </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  EDL accommodates 10 FVAs per launcher and are Line
								  Replaceable Units (LRUs) that can be removed or installed without
								  special tools. EDL is mounted on the plinth which is welded to deck.
								  The dimensions of EDL without doors open are 1528mmx1173mmx1692mm
								  (WxDxH). The weight of the EDL is 825 Kg.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  For correct
								  installation of the EDL and plinth assembly, the following factors
								  must be taken into consideration:
							  </para>

							  <para>(a) Safe and easy access for maintenance purpose. </para>
							  <para>
								  (b)
								  In order to achieve correct orientation, the EDL with plinth and
								  its surrounding area shall not be obstructed with metallic objects
								  i.e. communications antennas, masts etc.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (c)
								  The EDLs must be installed keeping barrel pointing outwards at
								  Port &amp; STBD of the ship.
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  <h6>Location</h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  The EDL plinth must
								  be placed as high as possible on the ship’s deck (as recommended in
								  the board proceedings) to provide an obstacle-free area of vision
								  when the barrels pointing outwards.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Service Area </h6
  >
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  The dimensions 1700mm (H) x 3100mm (L) x 2400mm (W)
								  shall be considered (which includes installation) for maintenance
								  tasks.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Fasteners Required for EDL Mounting </h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>See Table 2.2.</para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>
									  Table 2.2: Fasteners required
									  for EDL mounting
								  </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <table frame="box" rules="all">
									  <colgroup>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
									  </colgroup>
									  <tbody>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">
												  <h6>Sl. No.</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td>
												  <h6>Item</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td>
												  <h6>Qty.</h6>
											  </td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">1</td>
											  <td>Flange hex bolt M16x2.0</td>
											  <td>20</td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">2</td>
											  <td>Nyloc nut M16x2.0</td>
											  <td>20</td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">3</td>
											  <td>Plain Washers M16 X 3 THK</td>
											  <td>40</td>
										  </tr>
									  </tbody>
								  </table>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Length of cable between Units</h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  For the estimated length of cables to be maintained between
								  the units,<h6>
									  <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Lengthofcable.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;">
										  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
									  </a>
								  </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Connections</h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  All connectors are on the base of the inner surface of the
								  carcass, supporting structures shall allow access for connection and
								  correct routing of the cables. The connectors must be protected with
								  vulcanizing tape.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Power Supply and Consumption</h6
  >
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Since the EDL comprises of the LCU, power supply 115VAC
								  50 / 60Hz 1Ø or 380 VAC / 415AC / 440VAC, 50 / 60Hz 3Ø (Delta configuration)
								  for this unit comes from the ship’s mains, which is terminated at
								  connectors provided on the inner surface area of the carcass. The
								  power consumption of LCU is 50 W.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Cooling</h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>EDL unit does not require any cooling arrangement.</para>
							  <para
  >
								  <h6>Installation Drawings</h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  The attachment details
								  and connectors are specified in the Fig. 2.1 below:
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_1.gif"></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 2.1: Plinth dimensional requirements</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Installation of EDL-Plinth </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para
  >To install the Plinth &amp; EDL, perform the following:</para>

							  <para>
								  (a)
								  Lift the EDL plinth with the help of appropriate lifting crane
								  (of capacity 0.5 ton) &amp; lifting tools. (The EDL plinth weighs
								  155 Kg. approximately).
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (b)
								  Place the plinth on upper deck of the ship, one on the port side
								  and the other on the starboard side, keeping topmost height of the
								  plinth facing sea.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (c)
								  The four vertical legs of the EDL plinth are provided with an
								  additional height of 66mm that can be removed from bottom side to
								  accommodate for uneven deck surfaces. It may be noted that the height
								  of the EDL plinth should not be less than 656±4mm after installation.
								  Refer Fig 2.1 above.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (d)
								  The welding of EDL plinth on to the deck surface to be carried
								  out as per AWS D1.1 or as per ship standard procedure by a qualified
								  welder. (Material of construction of EDL plinth is Duplex 2205 grade)
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (e)
								  After completion of EDL plinth welding to ship deck, Dye Penetration
								  (DP) test to be carried out at all welded joints to detect the defects.
								  If no weld defect found, the surface shall be painted with RAL 7040
								  paint.
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  <h6>Installation Procedure - EDL (Port)  </h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>See Fig. 2.2. To install the EDL (Port), carryout the following:</para
  >

							  <para>
								  (a)
								  After completion of EDL plinth installation, install the EDL assembly
								  (integrated with FVA’s-10 No’s and LCU) on the welded plinth assembly.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (b)
								  The EDL assembly is provided with three lifting hooks on topside
								  of the carcass (when EDL is lifted with all the three lifting hooks,
								  the bottom face of the EDL assembly will remain parallel to the ground
								  and hence used during shipment. While the lifting with front two lifting
								  hooks will align the EDL assembly parallel to the top face of the
								  plinth and hence provide ease of installation) and shall be lifted
								  with a crane of capacity 1 ton.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (c)
								  Lift the EDL assembly (using all the three lifting hooks) and
								  take it to the location of the plinth being installed.<para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_2.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.2: Carcass &amp; Plinth of EDL</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (d)
								  Lift the EDL assembly (using front two lifting hooks) and place
								  it on plinth (with EDL assembly facing towards Sea) and aligning it
								  with the help of location pins / lugs (2 no’s) provided on the top
								  face of the plinth. This will align the holes at the EDL- Plinth interface.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (e)
								  Secure the EDL assembly in its position and insert the 20 nos’
								  of M16x2Px70L Hex. Bolts &amp; Washers at the EDL-Plinth interface.
								  Ensure that the lifting arrangement engaged until all fasteners are
								  inserted and pre tightened with M16 Nyloc nuts.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (f)
								  Remove the lifting arrangement (Anchor Shackle -Type D) once the
								  all bolts are pre tightened and fastened.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (g)
								  With the help of ratchet socket wrench and torque wrench tighten
								  all 20 no’s fasteners diagonally (it is advisable fasten the bolts
								  diagonally starting from FVA end to outside) at a 162 Nm torque.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (h)
								  Make all the connectors (J1, J2 &amp; J3) (See Fig. 2.3) at the
								  electrical connector box located inside, at bottom of the EDL carcass.
								  (Ring marks to ensure proper fitment. <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_3.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.3: EDL Plinth Connectors</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>(i) Protect the connectors using vulcanizing tape.</para>
							  <para>
								  (j)
								  Check if the unit is properly grounded. (Using Earth Resistance
								  Meter, measure the resistance between the prime earth stud, all panel
								  mount connectors &amp; launcher earth points. The resistance measured
								  between the Earthing point and the prime earth stud shall be &lt;
								  0.1 Ohms.)
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  <note>
									  <para style="color:red">
										  Note:	The installation procedure for the EDL (Stbd) is identical
										  to that of 	the EDL (Port).
									  </para>
								  </note>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.2.14.2 Remote Control Unit RCU  " level="5">
						  <title>2.2.14.2 Remote Control Unit (RCU)</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  This unit is used to fire the charges remotely. It
								  has the dimensions (in mm) of 430x190x330 (W x D x H). The weight
								  of this unit is 20 Kg.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  A pictorial view of the RCU is
								  shown in Fig. 2.4.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_4.gif"></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 2.4: Pictorial View of RCU</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Location</h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  The unit must
								  be installed in a watertight compartment (Ops Room) as recommended
								  in the Board Proceedings.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Service Area</h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  A free space of at least 500 mm shall be left in front of the
								  panel for maintenance tasks.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Material Required</h6
  >
							  </para>
							  <para>See Table 2.3.</para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>
									  Table 2.3: Material Required
									  for RCU
								  </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <table frame="box" rules="all">
									  <colgroup>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
									  </colgroup>
									  <tbody>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">
												  <h6>Sl. No.</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td>
												  <h6>Item</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td>
												  <h6>Qty.</h6>
											  </td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">1</td>
											  <td>SCR HEX SST M8X25</td>
											  <td>4</td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">2</td>
											  <td>WASHER PLAIN SST – M8</td>
											  <td>4</td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">3</td>
											  <td>WASHER SPRING SST – M8</td>
											  <td>4</td>
										  </tr>
									  </tbody>
								  </table>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Length of cable between Units</h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  For the estimated length of cables to be maintained between
								  the units, <h6>
									  <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Lengthofcable.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;">
										  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
									  </a>
								  </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Connections</h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  All connectors (J1-J6, 06 No’s) are located on the rear panel.
								  A space of at least 500 mm shall be left on the rear side of the unit
								  to allow correct routing and bending of wires.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>
									  Power
									  supply and consumption
								  </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  This unit is powered at
								  115 VAC, 50Hz/60Hz, 1 or 380VAC/415VAC/450VAC 50Hz/60Hz, 3 with
								  a power consumption of 50 W.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Cooling</h6>
							  </para>
							  <para
  >
								  The unit must be installed in an area with controlled temperature
								  and ventilation (air flow) such that the air passing over the unit
								  provides a suitable cooling.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Installation Procedure </h6
  >
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  (a)
								  This unit is a bulkhead mounted. The mounting plate / base is
								  to be attached to the bulkhead as per location recommended in the
								  Board Proceedings.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (b)
								  Place the unit on the mounting plate / base as shown in Fig. 2.5
								  below: <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_5.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.5: Installation of RCU</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (C)
								  Secure the unit by using M8x25 screws along with plain and spring
								  washers.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (d)
								  Connectorise the external wires (J1-J5, 5 No’s) considering the
								  correct routing and bending of the cables to the unit.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (e)
								  Check that the unit is properly grounded. (Using Earth Resistance
								  Meter, measure the resistance between the prime earth stud, all panel
								  mount connectors &amp; units earth points. The resistance measured
								  between the Earthing point and the prime earth stud shall be &lt;
								  0.1 Ohms.)
							  </para>

						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.2.14.3 Console" level="5">
						  <title>2.2.14.3 Console</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The Console provides the Man Machine Interface (MMI)
								  of the system. Its dimensions (in mm) are 510x225x510 (W x D x H).
								  The weight of the console is 40 Kg.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  A pictorial view of
								  Console is shown in Fig. 2.6.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_6.gif"></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 2.6: Pictorial view of Console </figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Location </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  The Console must
								  be installed in a watertight and cooled compartment. The NTDS uses
								  two consoles one shall be installed in Ops Room and other in Bridge.
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  <h6>Material required for Console</h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  See Table
								  2.4.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Table 2.4: Material Required for Console</h6
  >
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <table frame="box" rules="all">
									  <colgroup>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
									  </colgroup>
									  <tbody>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">
												  <h6>Sl. No.</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td>
												  <h6>Item</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td>
												  <h6>Qty.</h6>
											  </td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">1</td>
											  <td>Console mounting bracket</td>
											  <td>1</td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">2</td>
											  <td>Hex Screw SST M10X20</td>
											  <td>9</td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">3</td>
											  <td>M6 NyLock Nuts</td>
											  <td>2</td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">4</td>
											  <td>Plain Washer Fiber</td>
											  <td>4</td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">5</td>
											  <td>Tilt Knob</td>
											  <td>1</td>
