											  <td>Tilt Knob Assembly Plate</td>
											  <td>1</td>
										  </tr>
									  </tbody>
								  </table>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Length of cable between Units</h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  For the estimated length of cables to be maintained between
								  the units, <h6>
									  <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Lengthofcable.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;">
										  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
									  </a>
								  </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Service Area</h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  A free space at least 280 mm (see Fig. 2.7) must be left either
								  side of the console and 647 mm must be left in the front for opening
								  the front door / maintenance tasks.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_7.gif"></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 2.7: Maintenance Envelope</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Connections</h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  All connectors
								  of the Console are located on the bottom. A space of at least 901
								  mm shall be left at the bottom of the unit (See Fig. 2.8) to allow
								  correct routing and bending of wires.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_8.gif"></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 2.8: Maintenance access for cabling</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Console Mounting Kit Locations</h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  See Fig. 2.9 for dimensional details and Console mounting kit
								  locations.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_9.gif"></graphic>
									  <figtitle>
										  Fig. 2.9: Console Mounting Kit Locations (Rear view mounting
										  pattern)
									  </figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Power supply and consumption</h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  The Console can be powered at 115 VAC, 50Hz/60Hz, 1&#8709; or 380VAC/415VAC/450VAC,
								  50Hz/60Hz, 3&#8709;  with a power consumption of less than 180VA.
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  <h6>Cooling </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  The Console must be installed
								  in an area with controlled temperature and ventilation (air flow)
								  such that the air passing over the unit provides suitable cooling.
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  <h6>Installation Procedure:</h6>
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  (a)
								  Fix the mounting bracket to the console and secure it by means
								  of screws.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (b)
								  Fix the mounting bracket to the bulkhead plate and tighten the
								  screws (Refer Fig. 2.9 above).
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (c)
								  Take out the Keyboard from its holding bracket before assembling
								  the Console to the mounting bracket.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (d)
								  Assemble the Console to mounting bracket by engaging M6-02No’s
								  Nylock Nuts Plain Fiber Washers.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (e)
								  Integrate Tilt Knob Locking Mechanism and Tilt Knob to lock the
								  Console.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (f)
								  Connectorise Fiber Optic &amp; Power connections and connect all
								  the earthing wires to prime earth stud on Console considering the
								  correct routing and bending of the cables to the unit.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (g)
								  Check that the unit is properly grounded. (Measure earth resistance
								  between the prime earth stud, all panel mount connector and earthing
								  points.  The Earth Resistance between the earthing point and the prime
								  earth stud shall be &lt;0.1ohms.)
							  </para>

						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.2.14.4 Winch" level="5">
						  <title>2.2.14.4 Winch</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The winch is used to deploy and recover the Fiber Optic
								  Tow cable. The Winch is mounted on its plinth which is welded to the
								  ship’s deck. The Winch including plinth has the dimensions of 2540mmx1910mmx1850mm
								  (W x D x H) and weight 4.9 Ton.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Winch divided into three
								  major subassemblies for installation as follows:
							  </para>

							  <para>(a) Winch Plinth.</para>
							  <para>
								  (b)
								  Gear-Drum-Brake Assembly (comprises of Gear Box Assembly, Drum-Flange
								  Assembly, Rotary Encoder Housing Assembly, Band Brake Assembly Support
								  Structures and the Main Control Panel (MCP) assembled on common platform/structure).
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (c)
								  Level Wind Assembly (comprises of Level Wind and Motor with Gear
								  Box).
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  For correct installation of the Winch with plinth,
								  the following factors must be taken into consideration:
							  </para>
							  <para>(a) Safe and easy access for maintenance purposes. </para>
							  <para>
								  (b)
								  In order to achieve correct orientation, the plinth and its surrounding
								  area should not be obstructed with the metallic objects.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (c)
								  No loose materials, components or swarf shall be permitted within
								  the winch housings before the plinth is welded.
							  </para>
							  <para>(d) Repaint the interior surface of the Winch Plinth prior installation. </para>
							  <para>(e) Plinth height shall not be more than 178 mm post installation. </para>
							  <para>
								  (f)
								  The plinth is supplied with an additional material of 22 mm height
								  (in addition to 178 mm). This facilitates in modifying the plinth
								  base to accommodate for uneven deck surfaces during installation.
								  Prior installation of Winch Assembly onto plinth, ensure the flatness
								  of the winch plinth.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (g)
								  The metalwork shall be suitably cleaned and prepared before any
								  welding takes place.
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  <h6>Location </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Plinth shall be positioned
								  with deck end connectors (J1, J2, J3 and J4) towards the AFT of the
								  ship. The fairlead shall be mounted on the fairlead plinth such that
								  the center of the fairlead must be in line with the center of the
								  Winch drum. The fairlead shall be fitted on the stern of the ship.
								  The area between the fairlead and center of the winch drum shall not
								  be obstructed with any metallic objects.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Service Area </h6
  >
							  </para>
							  <para>For maintenance space requirements, see Fig. 2.10 </para
  >
							  <para>
								  A free space at least 2090 mm shall be left on the starboard
								  side for operating MCP and maintenance of winch / removal of Slip
								  Ring from Starboard side. A free space at least 1000 mm each shall
								  be left on the port side and front of the winch for maintenance tasks.
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_10.gif"></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 2.10: Maintenance space requirements – Winch</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Length of cable between Units</h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  For the estimated length of cables to be maintained between
								  the units, <h6>
									  <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Lengthofcable.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;">
										  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
									  </a>
								  </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>
									  Fasteners required
									  for winch mounting
								  </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>See Table 2.5.</para>
							  <para>
								  <h6
  >Table 2.5: Fasteners required for winch mounting</h6>
							  </para>
							  <para
  >
								  <table frame="box" rules="all">
									  <colgroup>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
									  </colgroup>
									  <tbody>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">
												  <h6>Sl. No.</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td>
												  <h6>Item</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td>
												  <h6>Qty.</h6>
											  </td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">1</td>
											  <td>Flange hex bolt M20x2.5x85</td>
											  <td>65</td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">2</td>
											  <td>Flange hex nut M20x2.5</td>
											  <td>65</td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">3</td>
											  <td>Plain Washer</td>
											  <td>130</td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">4</td>
											  <td>Spring Washer</td>
											  <td>65</td>
										  </tr>
									  </tbody>
								  </table>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Connections </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  All deck end
								  connectors (J1, J2, J3 and J4) are provided on plinth, underneath
								  the base structure of the MCP such that the supporting structures
								  shall allow access for connection and correct routing of the cables.
								  The connectors are hermetically sealed and must be protected with
								  vulcanizing tape if they are not connected. All earthing cables should
								  be connected to Prime Earth Points mounted on Winch Plinth as mention
								  in <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/earthterminals.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;">
									  Table 2.6<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  For earthing wire specification and its placement,
								  refer Earthing and Bonding diagram of Winch.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Power supply and consumption</h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  The power supply 380VAC / 415VAC / 440VAC, 50/60Hz, 3 phase
								  for this unit comes from the ship’s mains, which is terminated at
								  connectors provided underneath the base structure of the MCP. The
								  power consumption of the winch motor is 22 kW (full load) with current
								  rating of 45A and for Level Wind Motor power consumption is 0.75 kW
								  with 2A full load current.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Cooling  </h6>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  Main Control Panel (MCP) is provided with heat sink inside
								  to dissipate heat during overheating conditions.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>
									  Installation
									  Procedure-Winch Plinth
								  </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  The pictorial view of Winch
								  is shown in Fig. 2.11. To install the winch, perform the following:
							  </para
  >

							  <para>
								  (a)
								  Lift the Winch Plinth Assembly by attaching Type D-Shackle to
								  two eyebolts (see Fig. 2.11) of M16 size located on the plinth top
								  face and place the assembly at desired location on the deck of the
								  ship. (Lifting Crane Capacity shall be greater than 2 ton)<para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_11.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.11: Location of Winch Plinth Lifting eyebolts</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (b)
								  Check the flatness of Winch Plinth Assembly on the deck using
								  spirit level at all locations. The flatness should be within 0.2 mm
								  and can be achieved by using shims of appropriate sizes at the base
								  of the Plinth.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (c)
								  The Winch vertical support plates are provided with additional
								  material of 22 mm that removed from bottom side to accommodate for
								  uneven deck surfaces. It may be noted that the height of Winch Plinth
								  Assembly should not be less than 178 mm, i.e., maximum of 22 mm material
								  can be removed during the installation from 200 mm. See Fig. 2.12
								  below:<para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_12.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.12: Winch surface requirements</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (d)
								  Ensure that winch plinth bottom side should be painted but welded
								  surface should not be painted (at approximately 50 mm from bottom
								  side)
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (e)
								  The welding of plinth onto the deck surface to be carried out
								  as per AWS D1.1 or as per ship standard procedure by a qualified welder.
								  (Material of Construction: Winch Plinth Assembly - IS 2062 E350; Rib
								  Thickness - 25 mm)
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (f)
								  Post welding Dye Penetration (DP) test to be carried out at all
								  welded joints to detect the defects. If no weld defect found, the
								  surface shall be painted with RAL 7042.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (g)
								  Re-Check that the flatness of Winch Plinth Assembly is within
								  0.2mm, which may be further achieved by scraping-off the Winch Plinth.
							  </para>
							  >
							  <para>
								  <h6>Installation Procedure-Winch</h6>
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  (a)
								  Post completion of Winch Plinth Installation, firmly connect the
								  Spreader Bar to the Winch Equipment (Refer Sl (c) (i)) using Type
								  D Shackle (Use Crane of capacity greater than 08 ton).
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (b)
								  The spreader bar with lifting capacity of 08 ton, is adjustable
								  according to the Centre of Gravity of the equipment. (Distance between
								  two eyebolts:1439 mm) (see Fig. 2.13)<para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_13.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.13: Spreader Bar mounting details</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para><para>
									  <note>
										  <para style="color:red">
											  Note:	Make sure that the spreader bar is strong enough to lift
											  the Winch and is not damaged or cracked. When attaching lifting chain
											  or sling to the winch, make sure it is firmly attached. Make sure
											  the fasteners attaching the lifting chain, or sling, have an adequate
											  strength.
										  </para>
									  </note>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (c)
								  The complete equipment is installed in two subassemblies, namely,
								  Gear-Drum-Brake Assembly and Level Wind Assembly.
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  (i)
								  The Gear-Drum-Brake Assembly comprises Gear Box Assembly, Drum-Flange
								  Assembly, Rotary Encoder Housing Assembly, Band Brake Assembly Support
								  Structures and the Main Control Panel (MCP) assembled on common platform/structure.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (ii)
								  The Level Wind Assembly comprises of Level Wind and Motor with
								  Gear Box.
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  (d)
								  Prior lifting the assembly ensure that the cable assemblies are
								  properly secured using cable tie and tied properly behind MCP. Make
								  sure all the cables from Plinth to MCP (J1) and SRJB (J2, J3 and J4)
								  are properly secured and not left hanging.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (e)
								  Lift the Gear-Drum-Brake Assembly from two lifting eyebolts provided
								  at the top of Gear Box Housing and Encoder Housing. (see Fig. 2.14
								  below)<para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_14.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>
											  Fig. 2.14: Location of Eyebolts on GB Drum Flange and Level
											  Wind Assy
										  </figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (f)
								  Adjust the CG of the equipment by adjusting the length of Spreader
								  Bar so that the assembly is lifted vertically without minor inclination.<para
  >
									  <note>
										  <para style="color:red">
											  Note: 	During the lifting ensure that there is no load on the
											  flange, as 	it may damage the flange.
										  </para>
									  </note>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (g)
								  After lifting, place Gear-Drum-Brake Assembly on the Winch Plinth
								  ensuring holes on the assembly in line with holes on the Plinth.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (h)
								  Fasten the assemblies using Bolts M20x80LG (see Fig. 2.15), Nuts,
								  Plain Washer &amp; Spring Washer (45 No’s). Apply grease to all bolts
								  before fastening.<para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_15.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.15: Fastening Bolts M20x80LG-GB</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (i)
								  The next sub assembly, i.e., Level Wind Assembly is lifted using
								  the crane of same capacity from its Lifting Eye Bolts provided on
								  either side of the Level Wind, as shown in the Fig. 2.14 above.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (j)
								  During lifting, ensure that the equipment is lifted without any
								  inclination with the ground.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (k)
								  Place the assembly at its designated location on the plinth (see
								  Fig. 2.16) and engage with the fasteners of size M20x80LG (20 No’s)
								  with torque value of 303 N-m.<para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_16.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.16: Fastening Bolts M20x80LG-Level Wind</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (l)
								  Based on the location of Winch on the ship and distance from the
								  Fairlead Assembly, adjust the height of the Level Wind Guiding Structure
								  by means of adjusting the height of Upper Sliding C-Structure on the
								  Level Wind using M16 bolts (10 No’s each on sliding structure) with
								  torque of 150 N-m.
							  </para>

						  </content>
						  <section id="2.2.14.4.1 Winch Alignment Procedure" level="6">
							  <title>2.2.14.4.1 Winch Alignment Procedure</title>
							  <content>

								  <para>
									  (a)
									  Loosen the 4 No’s bolts (M20x80LG) of the Encoder Housing Assembly
									  and 16 No’s bolts (M20x80LG) of the Support Structure. See Fig. 2.17.<para
  >
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_17.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>
												  Fig. 2.17: Location of bolts (M20x80LG) on Encoder Housing
												  Assembly
											  </figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  (b)
									  Align the Support Structure with respect to Plinth in horizontal
									  direction as shown in the Fig. 2.18 below. The dimensions shall be
									  62 mm with a deviation of 0.5mm.<para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_18.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.18: Aligning Support Structure with respect to Plinth</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  (c)
									  Tighten the 16 No’s bolts (M20x80LG) of the Support Structure
									  with Torque 303 N-m.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  (d)
									  Rotate the drum manually by one rotation in both the direction so that it allows the Encoder Housing Assembly to be self-adjustment.
									  
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  (e)
									  Open the Encoder Housing cover plate by removing Allen Bolts (M6x1x25
									  - 15 Nos).
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  (f)
									  Check the alignment of Encoder Housing by using Feeler Gauge at
									  Bush-Shaft interface. (The alignment can be achieved by inserting
									  appropriate size of shims at the base of housing for the height and
									  aligning the assembly sideways).
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  (g)
									  Ensure that the shaft is resting on the bottom of the bush. Measure
									  the clearances at 900, 2700, and 00 for reference of alignment and
									  benchmarking. Refer Fig. 2.19.<para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_19.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.19: Shaft &amp; Bush Clearance Check Points</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  (h)
									  Once aligned in all the directions, equally tighten all the bolts
									  on the Encoder Housing Assy with Support structure, sequentially (M20X80lg-4Nos)
									  with Torque of 303 N-m. Apply grease to all bolts before fastening.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  (i)
									  After Tightening the bolts again repeat the procedure as mentioned
									  at Sl (f) above. Ensure that Bottom side Gap should be Zero and gap
									  at 00, 900 and 2700 be recorded for alignment reference.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  (j)
									  If there are any significant changes (eg. No gap available at
									  180 degrees position), then again loosen the bolts and repeat the
									  procedure Sl (f) to Sl (i).
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  (k)
									  Connect the external cables to their corresponding connectors
									  provided underneath the base structure of the MCP considering the
									  correct routing and bending of these cables to the unit.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  (l)
									  Protect the connectors using vulcanizing tape if not connected
									  to the system.
								  </para>
								  <para>(m)Ensure that the unit is properly grounded.</para>

							  </content>
						  </section>
