			  <section id="2.3 Operating Procedure" level="3">
				  <title>2.3 Operating Procedure</title>
				  <section id="2.3.1 Precautions and Safety Measures  " level="4">
					  <title>2.3.1 Precautions and Safety Measures </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The following precautions are to be taken and safety
							  measures ensured before operating NTDS.
						  </para>

						  <para>(a) All units/subunits of the system are grounded properly.</para>
						  <para>(b) Cable connectors are properly tightened.</para>
						  <para>
							  (c)
							  Cable assemblies are not damaged while removing/inserting in the
							  units.
						  </para>
						  <para>(d) Correct tools are used for tightening / loosening screws. </para>
						  <para>(e) Power supply connectors are not touched when the power is “ON”.</para>
						  <para>(f) Connectors are not disconnected / connected when power is “ON”.</para>
						  <para>(g) Only trained personnel are allowed to operate the system.</para>
						  <para>
							  (h)
							  Devices for the protection of the system such as fuses, switches,
							  etc. must never be put out of operation.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (i)
							  Before operating the Launcher ensure all personnel are clear of
							  the EDL. Before operating the Winch ensure all personnel are clear
							  of the cable and moving parts.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (j)
							  Ensure that equipment like fire extinguisher, grease gun, torch
							  and tools are installed and safely stowed.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  (k)
							  Care should be taken not to leave tools or equipment in the winch
							  housings, Drum Junction Box where they could become entangled in the
							  moving machinery or cable.
						  </para>

					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.3.2 Operating Procedure - Launcher" level="4">
					  <title>2.3.2 Operating Procedure - Launcher</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  For Operating Procedure-Launcher,
							  <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V19_operation_procedure.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
								  Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
							  </a>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  The operating procedures of Launcher are broadly divided
							  in to the following groups:
						  </para>

						  <para>(a) Pre-Mission Checks</para>
						  <para>(b) System Operation</para>
						  <para>(c) Post-Mission Checks</para>


					  </content>
					  <section id="2.3.2.1 Pre-Mission Checks  " level="5">
						  <title>2.3.2.1 Pre-Mission Checks  </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  These checks are carried out prior to firing or weekly/bi-weekly,
								  whichever is earlier. In carrying out these checks, the operator is
								  to be guided only by the instructions laid down in this Manual.
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  <h6>(a)	General Guidelines</h6>
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  (i)
								  Carry out visual inspection of all mechanical/electrical systems
								  and their sub-systems.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (ii)
								  Check for marks of rust on metallic surfaces. Clean and paint
								  the affected areas.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (iii)
								  Check tightness of all cable connectors and earthing points and
								  ensure they are in order.
							  </para>
							  <para>(iv) Check tightness of fasteners and tighten, if needed. </para>

							  <para>
								  <h6>(b)	Electrical Interface</h6>
							  </para>

							  <para>(i) Check the power supply availability to the system.</para>
							  <para>
								  (ii)
								  Check that RS-485 data link cable between EDL and LCU/RCU/Cabinet
								  is connected properly.
							  </para>
							  <para>(iii) Check that interface cable between LCU-FVA is connected properly.</para>

							  <para>
								  <h6>(c)	Pneumatic Interface</h6>
							  </para>

							  <para>(i) Ensure that ship’s air supply source is available to the EDL-FVA. </para>
							  <para>
								  (ii)
								  Open that EDL door and lock both the doors in opened position
								  (LCU door may remain locked).
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (iii)
								  Set the 5-way mechanical selector valve ‘SAFE/VENT/CHARGE/ARM’
								  to ‘VENT’ mode to depressurize the reservoir.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (iv)
								  After depressurizing, connect 3-way isolation valve to depressurize
								  line so that air remaining in the manifold will also depressurize.
								  (Refer Fig. 2.21)<para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_21.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.21: Carcass &amp; Plinth of EDL</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (v)
								  Once the manifold is depressurized, set the 5-Way mechanical selector
								  valve ‘SAFE/VENT/CHARGE/ARM’ to ‘SAFE’ mode for all FVAs.
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  <h6>(d)	Electrical and Electro-mechanical Systems</h6
  >
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  (i)
								  Check that 5-way mechanical selector valve ‘SAFE/VENT/CHARGE/ARM’
								  is set to ‘SAFE’ mode.
							  </para>
							  <para>(ii) Check if earthing is connected properly.</para>
							  <para>(iii) Ensure SAFE/ENABLE switch is in SAFE mode on LCU and RCU.</para>
							  <para>
								  (iv)
								  Check that ‘REMOTE/SAFE/LOCAL ARM’ switch is set to ‘SAFE’ mode
								  on LCU.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (v)
								  Check that ‘AUTO ARM/SAFE/REMOTE ARM’ switch is set to ‘SAFE’
								  mode on RCU.
							  </para>

						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.3.2.2 System Operation - EDL " level="5">
						  <title>2.3.2.2 System Operation - EDL </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The system can operate from both RCU and LCU based
								  on the selection made by the operator. Following are the modes of
								  operation of the launcher:
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <ol type="1">
									  <li>Local Mode</li>
									  <li>Remote Mode</li>
									  <li>Auto Mode</li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Local Mode </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  When the operator initiates this mode, the EDL can be operated from the LCU, the EADs can be fired from the LCU. Load the EAD on the Barrel and carryout the following procedure:
							  </para>
							  <para>(a) When power is available to the launcher, the `POWER AVL` indicator  (White) on the LCU glows.</para>
							  <para>(b) Switch the 2 position `Power ON/OFF` switch to `ON`. `Power ON` indicator (White) on the LCU glows.</para>
							  <para>(c) The 2 way key switch, SAFE/ENABLE is by default in SAFE position.</para>
							  <para>(d) The 3-way Key switch, `REMOTE/SAFE/LOCAL ARM` is by default in SAFE position.</para>
							  <para>(e) Set the 2-way key switch, `SAFE/ENABLE`, to ENABLE.</para>
							  <para>(f) While firing switch the 3-way key switch momentarily to LOCAL ARM  with one hand and press the firing button simultaneously with the other hand.</para>
							  <para>(g) Sounder will come on when 3-way key switch is put to LOCAL ARM.</para>
							  <para>
								  (h) Inputs to the LCU are:
								  <para>
									  <ol type="i">
										  <li>Position of 5-way mechanical selector switch on each FVA (SAFE, VENT and ARM proximity sensors).</li>
										  <li>State of Reservoir pressure (Pressure sensor)</li>
										  <li>EAD present indication. </li>
									  </ol>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (i) Output from the LCU are the following: <para>
									  <ol type="i">
										  <li>Firing signal to the solenoid valve.</li>
										  <li>Status of the launcher to RCU and Cabinet.</li>

									  </ol>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>The flowchart corresponding to the operation of EDL in Local mode along with its procedure is given in the figure below:</para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/EDL_Local_Mode.gif"></graphic>
									  <figtitle>EDL Operation-Local Mode</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Remote Mode</h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>While operating the launcher from the RCU, the 3-way key  switch, REMOTE/SAFE/LOCAL ARM  is put to REMOTE. The operation of the launcher from RCU is identical to that of LCU. It may be noted that when operating the system through RCU, ensure that link between RCU &amp; LCU is established.</para>
							  <para>(a) When power is available to the launcher, the `POWER AVL` indicator (White) on the LCU glows.</para>
							  <para>(b) When power is available to the launcher, the `POWER AVL` indicator (White) on the RCU glows.</para>
							  <para>(c) Switch the 2 position `Power ON/OFF` switch to `ON`. `Power ON` indicator (White) on the LCU glows.</para>
							  <para>(d) Switch the 2 position `Power ON/OFF` switch to `ON`. `Power ON` indicator (White) on the RCU glows.</para>
							  <para>(e) The 2 way key switch, SAFE/ENABLE is by default in SAFE position on LCU.</para>
							  <para>(f) The 3-way Key switch, `REMOTE/SAFE/LOCAL ARM` is by default in SAFE position on LCU.</para>
							  <para>(g) The 2 way key switch, AUTO/MANUAL is by default in MANUAL position on RCU.</para>
							  <para>The flowchart corresponding to the operation of EDL in Remote mode along with its procedure is given in the figure below:</para>
							  <para>(h) The 3-way Key switch, `AUTO ARM/SAFE/REMOTE ARM` is by default in SAFE position On RCU</para>
							  <para>(i) The 2-way key switch, `SAFE/ENABLE`, to ENABLE on LCU</para>
							  <para>(j) The 2-way key switch, `AUTO/MANUAL to AUTO on RCU.</para>
							  <para>(k) 3 way key switch REMOTE/SAFE/LOCAL ARM to REMOTE on LCU </para>
							  <para>(l) While firing switch the 3-way key  switch momentarily to REMOTE ARM  with one hand and press the firing button simultaneously with the other hand on RCU</para>
							  <para>(m) Sounder will come on when 3-way key  switch is put to REMOTE ARM .</para>
							  <para>(n) Inputs to the RCU: Status of launcher via RS485 communication link.</para>
							  <para>
								  (o) Output from the RCU are the following: <para>
									  <ol type="i">
										  <li>Firing signal to the solenoid valve</li>
										  <li>Status of RCU to Cabinet</li>

									  </ol>
								  </para>
							  </para>



							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/EDL_Remote_Mode.gif"></graphic>
									  <figtitle>EDL Operation-Remote Mode</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Auto Mode</h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>The operating procedure of the launcher from the Processing Cabinet is as given below:</para>
							  <para>(a) When power is available to the launcher, the `POWER AVL` indicator (White) on the LCU glows.</para>
							  <para>(b) When power is available to the launcher, the `POWER AVL` indicator (White) on the RCU glows.</para>
							  <para>(c) Switch the 2 position `Power ON/OFF` switch to `ON`. `Power ON` indicator (White) on the LCU glows.</para>
							  <para>(d) Switch the 2 position `Power ON/OFF` switch to `ON`. `Power ON` indicator (White) on the RCU glows.</para>
							  <para>(e) The 2 way key switch, SAFE/ENABLE is by default in SAFE position on LCU.</para>
							  <para>(f) The 3-way Key switch, `REMOTE/SAFE/LOCAL ARM` is by default in SAFE position on LCU.</para>
							  <para>(g) The 2 way key switch, AUTO/MANUAL is by default in MANUAL position on RCU.</para>
							  <para>(h) The 3-way Key switch, `AUTO ARM/SAFE/REMOTE ARM` is by default in SAFE position On RCU</para>
							  <para>(i) The 2-way key switch, `SAFE/ENABLE`, to ENABLE on LCU</para>
							  <para>(j) The 2-way key switch, `AUTO/MANUAL to AUTO on RCU.</para>
							  <para>(k) 3 way key switch REMOTE/SAFE/LOCAL ARM to REMOTE on LCU </para>
							  <para>(l) The 3-way Key switch, `AUTO ARM/SAFE/REMOTE ARM` is on AUTO ARM position On RCU.</para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/EDL_Auto_Mode.gif"></graphic>
									  <figtitle>EDL Operation-Auto Mode</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.3.2.3 Post-Mission Checks " level="5">
						  <title>2.3.2.3 Post-Mission Checks </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  On completion of the assigned mission, the Launcher
								  system should be allowed to cool to the ambient temperature, carry
								  out the following:
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  (a)
								  Set the 2-way and 3-way selector switches located on LCU and RCU
								  to SAFE position.
							  </para>
							  <para>(b) Turn-Off the power supply to both RCU and Launcher (LCU).</para>
							  <para>
								  (c)
								  By setting Mechanical Selector Switch to ‘VENT’ position vent
								  all the FVA’s.
							  </para>
							  <para>(d) Thorough cleaning of the barrel and components.</para>
							  <para>(e) Check the health of gaskets located on LCU door and EDL door.</para>

						  </content>
					  </section>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.3.3 Operating Procedure - Winch " level="4">
					  <title>2.3.3 Operating Procedure - Winch </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>The operating procedure of the winch is as follows:</para
  >
					  </content>
					  <section id="2.3.3.1 Pre-mission checks   " level="5">
						  <title>2.3.3.1 Pre-mission checks</title>
						  <content>

							  <para>(a) All guards must be in place.</para>
							  <para>(b) All personnel must be clear of the winch.</para>
							  <para>
								  (c)
								  Manual release of the electric brake should not be in the Release
								  position.
							  </para>

						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.3.3.2 Actions to be taken after switching ON the Winch"
					  level="5">
						  <title>2.3.3.2 Actions to be taken after switching ON the Winch</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The following actions are to be taken on switching
								  ON the winch.
							  </para>

							  <para>(a) Make sure upon switching ON, the SUPPLY AVAILABLE lamp is illuminated</para>
							  <para>
								  (b)
								  If ‘Emergency Pressed’ lamp is ON, release EMERGENCY and press
								  ‘EMERGENCY RESET’ push button. This will turn off the emergency lamp.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (c)
								  Ensure communication link between the cabinet and the winch has
								  been established. This is indicated by the blinking of “Communication
								  Link Indicator” on the Length and Depth display.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (d)
								  Ensure actual length and depth of Tow agrees with the displayed
								  length and depth on the MCP panel.
							  </para>
							  <para>(e) Over temperature indicator should be OFF.</para>
							  <para>
								  (f)
								  Drive Reset Indicator should be in OFF position, if not press
								  “Drive Reset Switch”
							  </para>
							  <para>(g) Make sure that the manual break (Band Brake) is released.</para>

						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.3.3.3 Operating Procedure  " level="5">
						  <title>2.3.3.3 Operating Procedure </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>Following is the Operating Procedure of the Winch.</para
  >

							  <para>
								  (a)
								  Change the position of the “Standby/Operation Switch” to Operation.
								  Ensure that “Supply Available Indicator” and “System Ready Indicator”
								  are ON.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (b)
								  To rotate drum use “forward most control (joystick) with Dead-man
								  Switch”
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (c)
								  For Deployment move joystick towards PAY-OUT (i.e., towards left-hand
								  side of the operator) and for Recovery towards HAUL-IN (i.e., towards
								  right-hand side of the operator)
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (d)
								  Ensure that the during winch operation the Tow carefully guided
								  through Fairlead and the activity is carried out under the supervision
								  of Ship Safety Personnel.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (e)
								  Prior recovery of the tow ensure that the flaps of the Level Wind
								  Assembly are in vertical direction and the tow is present in-between
								  the flaps. (This can be achieved by positioning the Level Wind at
								  the location of Tow cable)
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (f)
								  During recovery systematically wind the tow layer-by-layer by
								  guiding the tow through the level wind. The level wind is operated
								  in synchronization with the rotation of the drum and tow by operating
								  the Level Wind Joystick.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (g)
								  Turn ON the water tap provided on the Fairlead to wash out the
								  incoming tow from foreign particles.
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  <h6>
									  For Deployment of FOTC,  <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Deployment_FOTC.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="user">
										  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
									  </a>
								  </h6>
							  </para
  >

							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_22.gif"></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 2.22: Deployment of FOTC </figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>
									  For Recovery of FOTC,  <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Recovery_FOTC.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="user">
										  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
									  </a>
								  </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/fig_2_23.gif"></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 2.23: Recovery of FOTC</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.3.3.4 Operating Procedure-Level Wind Assembly" level="5">
						  <title>2.3.3.4 Operating Procedure-Level Wind Assembly</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The mechanism is operated by a single operator, using
								  a joystick mounted on the MCP. The MCP is mounted on the winch and
								  can be operated in Local/Remote modes. Change the position of the
								  “Standby/Operation Switch” to Operation. Ensure that “Supply Available
								  Indicator” and “System Ready Indicator” are ON. Local/Remote operation
								  can be selected through the Local/Remote switch on the panel. Two
								  Joysticks to operate the Winch Drum and Level Wind Assembly are provided
								  on the MCP. The Aft joystick (Left of operator) controls the Level
								  Wind Assembly. The joystick is moved to port side to move the Level
								  Wind Assembly away from the operator and to starboard side to move
								  the Level Wind Assembly towards the operator.
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.3.4 Operating Procedure-NTDS Console " level="4">
					  <title>2.3.4 Operating Procedure-NTDS Console </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The operating procedures of NTDS Console are broadly
							  divided into the following groups:
						  </para>

						  <para>(a) Pre-Mission Checks</para>
						  <para>(b) System Operation</para>
						  <para>(c) Post-Mission Checks</para>

					  </content>
					  <section id="2.3.4.1 Pre-Mission Checks " level="5">
						  <title> 2.3.4.1 Pre-Mission Checks </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  These checks are carried out prior to firing or weekly/bi-weekly,
								  whichever is earlier. In carrying out these checks, the operator is
								  to be guided only by the instructions laid down in the Manual.
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  <h6>(a)	General Guidelines</h6>
							  </para>

							  <para>
								  (i)
								  Carry out visual inspection of all mechanical/electrical systems
								  and their sub-systems.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (ii)
								  Check for marks of rust on metallic surfaces. Clean and paint
								  the affected areas.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (iii)
								  Check tightness of all cable connectors and earthing points and
								  ensure they are in order.
							  </para>
							  <para>(iv) Check tightness of fasteners and tighten, if needed. </para>

							  <para>
								  <h6>(b)	Electrical Interface</h6>
							  </para>

							  <para>(i) Check the power supply availability to the system.</para>
							  <para>(ii) Check that NTDS Console Power cable is connected properly. </para>
							  <para>
								  (iii)
								  Check that interface cable between Fiber cable is connected properly
								  for Communication.
							  </para>
							  <para>(iv) Check that Audio Jack/Headphone is connected properly.</para>

						  </content>

					  </section>
					  <section id="2.3.4.2 Operating Procedure-Console   " level="5">
						  <title>2.3.4.2 Operating Procedure-Console   </title>
						  <content>

							  <para>(a) Switch ON the ships main power supply to the Console.</para>
							  <para>
								  (b)
								  Set the Power Selector Switch located at bottom of the console
								  to ‘2’ position and check that its Power ON indicator is glowing. <para
  >
									  <note>
										  <para style="color:red">
											  Note:	The power ON indicators will glow either GREEN or AMBER
											  based on the power supply configuration made to the system.
										  </para>
									  </note>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (c)
								  Switch ON the Display (Monitor) by means of pressing a push button
								  switch located on its front panel and check that its indicator is
								  glowing. Check the image is displayed clearly.
							  </para>
							  <para>(d) Run the desired application.</para>

						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.3.4.3 Post Mission Checks" level="5">
						  <title>2.3.4.3 Post Mission Checks</title>
						  <content>

							  <para>(a) Close all the applications</para>
							  <para>(b) Switch OFF the console</para>

						  </content>
					  </section>
				  </section>
			  </section>
			  <section id="2.4 Preventive Maintenance Procedures" level="3">
				  <title id="2.4 Preventive Maintenance Procedures">
					  2.4	Preventive Maintenance Procedures
				  </title>
				  <content>
					  <para>
						  This section describes the preventive and corrective
						  maintenance procedures of the New Torpedo Defence System (NTDS). The
						  NTDS is in a good state of preservation, when the equipment is clean,
						  free from corrosion and damage. In order to maintain the system to
						  be in good condition, the general maintenance routines should be carried
						  out periodically and strictly adhered to avoid costly failures. The
						  maintenance procedures are categorized by the periodic interval at
						  which they need to be performed. <ol type="a">
							  <li>Preventive Maintenance</li>
							  <li>Corrective Maintenance – Fault Finding and Rectification</li>
						  </ol>
					  </para>
				  </content>
				  <section id="2.4.1 Preventive Maintenance" level="4">
					  <title id="2.4.1 Preventive Maintenance">2.4.1 Preventive Maintenance</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The aim of preventive maintenance is to ensure that
							  the performance of the equipment remains optimum and also to ensure
							  that it is in good physical state. The preventive maintenance routines
							  pertaining to the NTDS should be performed at regular intervals based
							  on the nature of maintenance. The preventive maintenance routines
							  consists of:<ol type="1">
								  <li>Inspection &amp; checking</li>
								  <li>Adjustment</li>
								  <li>Cleaning</li>
								  <li>Lubrication</li>
								  <li>Preservation</li>
								  <li>Sealing </li>
								  <li>Keep Alive Procedure</li>
								  <li>Testing</li>
								  <li>Servicing </li>
							  </ol>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <h4>Inspection &amp; Checking</h4>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  This
							  procedure consists of the following steps:<ol type="1">
								  <li>Inspect the equipment for dust, dirt and corrosion.</li>
								  <li>
									  Before and after EDL/Winch/RCU/Console use, always inspect to
									  make sure there is no damage to the units.  Also check the tightness
									  of the mounting bolts and verify there are no loose components or
									  fasteners.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  Check that all pneumatic fittings located on EDL &amp; FVA are
									  well secured and check for any leakages.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  Check draining holes located at bottom structure of EDL for any
									  blockage.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  Check pneumatic tubes that have been connected to Vent, Charge
									  &amp; Arm ports for any damage and ensure connected properly.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  The winch is bolted down to the plinth with M20x2.5x85. The nuts
									  should be checked for tightness to a torque of 580 Nm (430 ft/lb)
									  once a month.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  Paint damage should be touched-up to prevent corrosion. The type of paint
									  used is RAL7040.
								  </li>
							  </ol>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <h4>Adjustment</h4>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							 The FVA does not need any adjustments under 5 years of normal use conditions.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <h4>Cleaning</h4>
							  <ol type="a">
								  <li>Ensure that the power supply to the system is Switched OFF.</li>
								  <li>
									  Carefully wipe the external surface of the subsystems and remove
									  dust and dirt.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  If dust or corrosion spots are detected, they should be removed
									  immediately.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  The corrosion must be removed with fine emery paper, preventing
									  the deposit of abrasive material on the surrounding components. Cover
									  such components with a clean cloth.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  If contamination with soot is observed then clean with water and
									  soap.
								  </li>
							  </ol>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <h4>Lubrication</h4>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  Rotating parts
							  like Level wind lead screw and Support shaft, located in Winch must
							  be greased periodically, according to the maintenance instructions
							  given in this section. Correct lubrication is essential for the safe
							  operation and long service life of the Winch.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <h4>Preservation</h4>
						  </para
  >
						  <para>
							  The preservation state of the equipment must be carefully and
							  regularly checked. The frequency of these checks depends on the usage
							  or storage condition.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <h4>Sealing</h4>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  Sealing
							  is intended to avoid:<ol type="a">
								  <li>Penetration of moisture in to the equipment.</li>
								  <li>
									  Crevice corrosion or frost damage due to moisture in seams, splits
									  and fissures, leakage and bimetallic contacts.
								  </li>
							  </ol>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <h4>Keep Alive Procedure</h4>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							 Only Dry Air to be supplied when FVA needs to be pressurised.

						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <h4>Testing</h4>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  Test front panel indicator
							  lamps located on LCU/RCU and MCP located on Winch by pressing the
							  LAMP TEST switch. Replace faulty lamps. Report all failures to maintenance
							  personnel.
						  </para>
					  </content>
				  </section>
