				  <section id="2.4.3 Maintenance Requirement Periodicity" level="4">
					  <title id="2.4.3 Maintenance Requirement Periodicity">
						  2.4.3 Maintenance
						  Requirement / Periodicity
					  </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The Maintenance Requirement / Periodicity give the
							  interval at which the maintenance must be performed. The preventive
							  maintenance procedures pertaining to various subsystems are broadly
							  grouped as daily, weekly, monthly, quarterly, half-yearly, yearly
							  and two early.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  The maintenance of the NTDS system components
							  can be performed mostly without changing its current operating status.
							  The maintenance of the system does not require any special tools or
							  measuring devices.
						  </para>
					  </content>
					  <section id="2.4.3.1 Daily maintenance " level="5">
						  <title id="2.4.3.1	Daily maintenance ">2.4.3.1	Daily maintenance </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>(Periodicity code -D)</para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>
									  External Visual
									  Inspection-EDL/RCU/Console
								  </h4>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Perform the following:<ol
  type="a">
									  <li>Ensure that the power supply to the system is Switched OFF.</li>
									  <li>
										  Inspect the equipment for dust, dirt and corrosion; check the
										  presence of any cracks, bends, dents or any other external damages
										  / abnormalities.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check that all cabinets are well secured to the ships bulkhead
										  and deck.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check the tightness of the electrical connectors connected to
										  the units.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check all mechanical assemblies / parts and ensure that no parts
										  are loose.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check the nuts that fix the EDL to the plinth for tightness and
										  ensure that it is well secured.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check draining holes located at bottom structure of EDL for any
										  blockage.
									  </li>
									  <li>Ensure EDL is properly covered when not in use.</li>
									  <li>
										  Ensure that Lock/key located on LCU/RCU is in OFF position (vertical
										  position)
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check that all pneumatic fittings between EDL &amp; FVA are well
										  secured and check for any leakages.
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>External Cleaning</h4>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Perform the
								  following:<ol type="a">
									  <li>Ensure that the power supply to the system is Switched OFF.</li>
									  <li>
										  Carefully wipe the external surface of the subsystems and remove
										  dust and dirt.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  If dust or corrosion spots are detected, they should be removed
										  immediately.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  The corrosion must be removed with fine emery paper, preventing
										  the deposit of abrasive material on the surrounding components. Cover
										  such components with a clean cloth.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  If contamination with soot is observed then clean with water and
										  soap.
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>External Visual Inspection-Winch</h4>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  Perform the following:<ol type="a">
									  <li>Ensure that the power supply to the system is Switched OFF.</li>
									  <li>
										  Inspect the equipment for dust, dirt and corrosion; check the
										  presence of any cracks, bends, dents or any other external damages
										  / abnormalities.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check the nuts that fix the units to the plinth for tightness
										  and ensure that they are well secured.  d)	Carry out a full cable
										  inspection including cable termination trips located in slip ring
										  assembly for deformation, crushing and loose or broken wire strands.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check the tightness of the electrical connectors connected to
										  the units i.e. Deck end connectors (J1, J2, J3 &amp; J4), MCP, Slip
										  ring assembly, Winch drum junction box.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check the TOW cable wraps on the drum are bedded correctly in
										  the grooves and are not covered in grit or dirt. Brush with a stiff
										  brush to remove dirt.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check drum brake surface is clean and not contaminated with oil
										  or grease.
									  </li>
									  <li>Check brake is applied manually.</li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>External Cleaning</h4>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Perform the
								  following:<ol type="a">
									  <li>Ensure that the power supply to the system is Switched OFF. </li>
									  <li>
										  Carefully wipe the external surface of the subsystems and remove
										  dust and dirt.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  If dust or corrosion spots are detected, they should be removed
										  immediately.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  The corrosion must be removed with fine emery paper, preventing
										  the deposit of abrasive material on the surrounding components. Cover
										  such components with a clean cloth. Finally apply a thin layer of
										  grease on the cleaned part or paint the area.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  If contamination with soot is observed then clean with water and
										  soap
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.4.3.2 Weekly maintenance " level="5">
						  <title id="2.4.3.2 Weekly maintenance ">2.4.3.2	Weekly maintenance</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>(Periodicity code -W)</para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>
									  Tightness of
									  Fasteners
								  </h4>
								  <?Pub Caret 0?>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Perform the following procedure
								  to check Fasteners securing the unit:
							  </para>
							  <para>(a)	Ensure that power supply to the system is Switched OFF. </para>
							  <para>
								  (b)	Locate the positions where the units like EDL, Winch, RCU
								  &amp; Console are secured to the ship’s deck/bulkhead.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (c)	Using the appropriate tool, tighten the fastening mechanisms
								  and make sure that the units are well secured to the designated torque
								  value where appropriate.See the table below.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_4_3_2_table.gif"></graphic>

								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (d)	Ensure that the tools used
								  are in good condition. Defective tools can cause damage to the equipment.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <note>
									  <para style="color:red">
										  Note:	Do not apply excess force during tightening/loosening.
									  </para>
								  </note>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>Earthing checks</h4>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Perform the
								  following:
							  </para>
							  <para>(a) Ensure the power supply to the system is switched OFF.</para>
							  <para>(b) Disconnect the earthing strip from the unit.</para>
							  <para>
								  (c) Clean the earthing strip using emery paper and soft cloth.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (d) Check
								  the earthing and ensure that value lies in 0-2 ohms.
							  </para>
							  <para>(e) Connect the earthing strip back to the unit.</para>


							  <para>
								  <h4>Cables and connections checks-Winch</h4>
							  </para  >
							  <para>Perform the following:</para>

							  <para>(a) Check fibre optic cables for damage.</para>
							  <para>
								  (b) Check terminal strips inside slip ring junction box for any loose
								  contacts or poor connection.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (c) Check operation of all limit switches by means of rotating winch
								  drum manually. These switches can be activated by hand and their operation
								  checked from the MCP.
							  </para>



							  <para>
								  <h4>Gear box oil level checks</h4>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  For Gear box oil level checks,
								  <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V26_GearBoxOilLevelChecks.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
									  Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Perform
								  the following:
							  </para>
							  <para>(a) Visually see the oil level indicator.</para>
							  <para>
								  (b) Check if oil levels in gearbox is adequate else top up to the
								  desired level.
							  </para>
							  <para>(c) Ensure that the oil used is correct. Do not mix oils.</para>


							  <para>
								  <note>
									  <para style="color:red">
										  Note: Oil specification: MAK 320
									  </para>
								  </note>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>Lubrication</h4>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  For Winch Lubrication,
								  <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V18_Winch_Lubrication.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
									  Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <para>
									  Perform
									  the following:
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <note>
									  <para style="color:red">
										  Note: Grease specification - NLGI3 (HP)
									  </para>
								  </note>
							  </para>


							  <para>(a) Clean and grease nuts &amp; bolts that have been fastened to plinth.</para>
							  <para>(b) Clean and apply a thin layer of grease over level wind lead screw.</para>
							  <para>(c) Clean and apply a thin layer of grease over support shaft.</para>
							  <para>
								  (d) Clean and apply a thin layer of grease over lead screw of band
								  brake.
							  </para>
							  <para>(e) Clean and grease the locking pin of band brakes.</para>



							  <para>
								  <h4>Greasing to Encoder Assembly-Winch</h4>
							  </para>
							  <para
  >
								  Perform the following:
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  (a) Using grease gun (12mm) lubricate the Encoder assembly at the nipples
								  provided on the housing.
							  </para>



							  <para>
								  <note>
									  <para style="color:red">
										  Note: Avoid excess greasing. Grease specification: Gulf Crown MP Grease (NLGI3).

									  </para>
								  </note>
							  </para>

						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.4.3.3 Quarterly Maintenance Routines" level="5">
						  <title id="2.4.3.3 Quarterly Maintenance Routines">
							  2.4.3.3 Quarterly
							  Maintenance Routines
						  </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>(Periodicity code -Q)</para>
							  <para>
								  Power/Signal/FOTC
								  cable connector checks
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Perform the following:<ol type="a">
									  <li>Ensure that the power supply to the system is switched OFF.</li>
									  <li>
										  Check all power and signal/data/FOTC cables terminating from their
										  respective units / cabinets are properly connected.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check for any physical damage on the cables and connectors, take
										  corrective action.
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>Inspection of fan for operation-Console/Winch-MCP </h4
  >
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  The console is fitted with one fan and MCP is equipped
								  with 4 fans. For inspection of fan for operation, perform the following:	<ol
  type="a">
									  <li>Switch ON the system/unit.</li>
									  <li>Check that the air flow is adequate to cooling the unit.</li>
									  <li>
										  Check for excessive noise or friction during startup or during
										  operation.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Switch OFF the system and listen to the bearing noise of the fan
										  when the RPM (revolutions per minute) comes down. A rumbling or grinding
										  noise indicates a worn out or fouled bearings. Contact the OEM for replacement.
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.4.3.4 Half Yearly Maintenance Routines" level="5">
						  <title id="2.4.3.4 Half Yearly Maintenance Routines">
							  2.4.3.4	Half-Yearly
							  Maintenance Routines
						  </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>(Periodicity code -S)</para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>
									  Cleaning of plugs
									  and connectors
								  </h4>
							  </para>
							  <para>Perform the following:</para>
							  <para
  >Ensure that the power supply to the system is switched OFF.</para
  >
							  <para>
								  Disconnect all connectors. Clean the plugs and sockets thoroughly
								  using alcohol. Visually inspect the internal pins of the connector
								  and plug for dirt, corrosion and any loose connection.
							  </para>
							  <para
  >Put back all connectors to their respective plugs.</para>
							  <para>
								  <h4
  >Internal Inspection (EDL)</h4>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  For Maintenance EDL,
								  <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V17_Maintenance_EDL.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
									  Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>
							  </para>
							  <para>Carry out the following:</para
  >
							  <para>
								  <note>
									  <para style="color:red">

										  Note:	Extreme care is to be taken while performing internal
										  inspection of EDL.

									  </para>
								  </note>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <ol type="a">
									  <li>Ensure that the power supply to the system is switched OFF.</li>
									  <li>Remove the cover from EDL.</li>
									  <li>
										  Visually inspect inside of the EDL for dirt, corrosion, loose
										  particles and blockage of draining holes located at bottom structure
										  of the EDL. Clean and preserve if required.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check for air leaks and tightness of pneumatic fittings between
										  reservoir &amp; pressure gauge and EDL &amp; FVA.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check all electrical cables end terminations for defective wiring
										  and poor/loose connection and mechanical damage or corrosion. Take
										  corrective action.
									  </li>
									  <li>Check all the fastener screws/bolts.</li>
									  <li>Check state of gaskets and replace if perished.</li>
									  <li>
										  Check outside of the barrels for damage or signs of corrosion
										  and take corrective measures if necessary.
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>Internal Inspection (LCU/RCU)</h4>
							  </para>
							  <para
  >
								  Perform the following:<ol type="a">
									  <li>Ensure that the power supply to the system is switched OFF.</li>
									  <li>Loosen all screws on the front/top panel of LCU and open it.</li>
									  <li>
										  Visually inspect inside of the LCU for dirt, corrosion, loose
										  particles and overheated components. Clean and preserve if required.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check all electrical/data/signal cables end terminations for defective
										  wiring and poor/loose connection and mechanical damage or corrosion.
										  Take corrective action.
									  </li>
									  <li>Check all the fastener screws/bolts.</li>
									  <li>
										  Check outside of the cabinet for damage or signs of corrosion
										  and chipped of paint, take corrective measures if necessary.
									  </li>
									  <li>Clean the exterior of the cabinet with a damp cloth and wipe dry.</li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>Oil replacement in Gear box </h4>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  For Oil replacement in Gear box,
								  <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V27_Gboilreplacement.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
									  Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>
							  </para>
							  <para
  >
								  Perform the following:<ol type="a">
									  <li>Remove the oil by means of removing the drain plug.</li>
									  <li>Put back the drain plug.</li>
									  <li>
										  Sieving oil through inlet of gear box and check the oil level
										  in its indicator.
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <note>
									  <para style="color:red">
										  Note: Oil Specification: MAK AMOCAM 320
									  </para>
								  </note>
							  </para>

						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.4.3.5 Yearly Maintenance Routines" level="5">
						  <title id="2.4.3.5 Yearly Maintenance Routines">
							  2.4.3.5 Yearly Maintenance
							  Routines
						  </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>(Periodicity code -A)</para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>Internal Inspection-Console </h4
  >
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Perform the following:<ol type="a">
									  <li>Remove the top cover by unscrewing captive screws on the top plate.</li>
									  <li>
										  Remove dust, dirt by using a vacuum cleaner and then clean the
										  PCBs with anti static ESD cleaning brush.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check all sub-assemblies, PCBs and other components for any damage
										  and verify that these are secured in their respective slots/positions
										  firmly.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check all electrical/data cables end terminations for defective
										  wiring and poor/loose connection and mechanical damage or corrosion.
										  Take corrective action.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Wipe the LCD panel swiftly with cotton or other soft cloth. Do
										  not apply CCl4 (Carbon Tetrachloride) to the LCD Display or components
										  as it may damage polarizer.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check the condition of the MOV (Metal Oxide Varistor) mounted
										  on the RFI Line Filter on 230 VAC power lines and check if they are
										  deteriorated and replace if required.
									  </li>
									  <li>Close and tighten the screws of the top plate.</li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>Internal Inspection (Winch- MCP)   </h4>
							  </para
  >
							  <para>
								  Perform the following:<ol type="a">
									  <li>Ensure that the power supply to the system is switched OFF.</li>
									  <li>Loosen all screws on the front/top panel of MCP and open it.</li>
									  <li>
										  Visually inspect inside of the MCP for dirt, corrosion, loose
										  particles and overheated components. Clean and preserve if required.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Check all electrical/data cables end terminations for defective
										  wiring and poor/loose connection and mechanical damage or corrosion.
										  Take corrective action.
									  </li>
									  <li>Check all the fastener screws/bolts.</li>
									  <li>
										  Check outside of the cabinet for damage or signs of corrosion
										  and chipped of paint, take corrective measures if necessary.
									  </li>
									  <li>Clean the exterior of the cabinet with a damp cloth and wipe dry.</li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>Continuity checks	</h4>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Perform
								  the following:<ol type="a">
									  <li>Ensure that the power supply to the system is switched OFF.</li>
									  <li>Disengage all connectors.</li>
									  <li>
										  Check the continuity of all cables and ensure that it lies in
										  approximately  0 - 0.02 ohms.
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>Gasket checks (EDL/LCU-Door)   </h4>
							  </para>
							  <para
  >
								  Perform the following:<ol type="a">
									  <li>Ensure that the power supply to the system is switched OFF.</li>
									  <li>
										  Open the EDL/LCU door and check the state of the gaskets and replace
										  them if necessary.
									  </li>
									  <li>Close the both the door and lock it properly.</li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h4>Gasket checks (Winch-MCP Door) </h4>
							  </para>
							  <para
  >
								  Perform the following:<ol type="a">
									  <li>Ensure that the power supply to the system is switched OFF.</li>
									  <li>
										  Open the MCP door and check the state of the gaskets and replace
										  them if necessary.
									  </li>
									  <li>Close the both the door and lock it properly.</li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.4.3.6 Two Yearly Maintenance Routines" level="5">
						  <title id="2.4.3.6 Two Yearly Maintenance Routines">
							  2.4.3.6 Two Yearly
							  Maintenance Routines
						  </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>(Periodicity code -2A)</para>
							  <para>
								  Overhauling and
								  reconditioning of the equipment to be carried out as per the test
								  procedures.
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.4.4 Corrective Maintenance" level="4">
					  <title id="2.4.4 Corrective Maintenance">2.4.4 Corrective Maintenance</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  Corrective maintenance deals with procedures for replacement
							  of various subunits/modules/components. However, the corrective maintenance
							  for this system onboard ship is limited to the LRU/Unit level. This
							  maintenance is performed after:<ol type="a">
								  <li>A failure has occurred. </li>
								  <li>
									  When the specifications can no longer be met even after tests
									  and adjustments.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  A preventive maintenance action has indicated degradation in performance
									  necessitating corrective action.
								  </li>
							  </ol>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  Before carrying out the maintenance or repair operations
							  of the NTDS system the safety regulations mentioned below must be
							  strictly adhered:<ol type="a">
								  <li>
									  Only trained personnel are allowed to operate/repair the NTDS
									  system.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  Facilities for the protection of the system, such as fuses, switches,
									  etc., must never be put out of operation.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  High voltage may present in electrical devices. Contact with live
									  parts or with parts which have damaged insulation, may result in severe
									  personal injuries.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  Maintenance and repair works must be carried out by personnel
									  who have undergone appropriate specialized training. Before carrying
									  out work on electrical systems, those systems have to be de-energized.
									  This applies even for minor operations.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  Place a warning notice close to the units that have been disconnected
									  with the following text:
								  </li>
							  </ol>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <table frame="box" rules="none" width="535">
								  <colgroup align="center">
									  <col/>
								  </colgroup>
								  <tbody>
									  <tr>
										  <td>
											  <h4>DO NOT OPERATE - WORK IN PROGRESS</h4>
										  </td>
									  </tr>
									  <tr>
										  <td>Sign may be removed only by Departmental Head</td>
									  </tr>
								  </tbody>
							  </table>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <caution>
								  <para>
									  <table frame="box" rules="none" width="584">
										  <colgroup align="center">
											  <col/>
										  </colgroup>
										  <tbody>
											  <tr>
												  <td>
													  <h4>CAUTION</h4>
												  </td>
											  </tr>
											  <tr>
												  <td>
													  Switching ON or OFF has to be performed by order of the ship`s
													  command only
												  </td>
											  </tr>
										  </tbody>
									  </table>
								  </para>
							  </caution>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <para>
								  <table frame="box" rules="none" width="615">
									  <colgroup align="center">
										  <col/>
									  </colgroup>
									  <tbody>
										  <tr>
											  <td>
												  <h4>ATTENTION</h4>
											  </td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td>
												  Avoid touching areas of integrated circuits; static discharge
												  can damage these circuits
											  </td>
										  </tr>
									  </tbody>
								  </table>
							  </para>
						  </para>
					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.4.5 Logging of Maintenance Record" level="4">
					  <title id="2.4.5 Logging of Maintenance Record">
						  2.4.5	 Logging of
						  Maintenance Record
					  </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The details of failures of both electrical and mechanical
							  should be noted and maintained in a log-book for future references.
							  These are useful for ascertaining the reliability and maintainability
							  of the system.
						  </para>
					  </content>
				  </section>
			  </section>
			  <section id="2.5 Dismantling and Re-Assembly " level="3">
				  <title>2.5 Dismantling and Re-Assembly </title>
				  <content>
					  <para>
						  The New Torpedo Defence System (NTDS) is a ship borne
						  system consists of two Expendable Device Launchers (EDL), two LCUs,
						  one RCU, two Consoles, a Processing Cabinet and a Winch. This section
						  describes about the dismantling and reassembly procedures of various
						  units of the system.
					  </para>
				  </content>
				  <section id="2.5.1 Precautions " level="4">
					  <title>2.5.1 Precautions </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>The following precautions have to be taken while dismantling/re-assembly:</para
  >
						  <para>
							  <ol type="a">
								  <li>Ensure that the main power supply to the system is switched OFF.</li>
								  <li>
									  Take necessary precautions to prevent ESD (Electro Static Discharge)
									  damage. For details, <a onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Attachment_ESD.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;">
										  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
									  </a>
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  Equipment should be electrically insulated before any work is
									  commenced.
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  Personnel should not work unaccompanied on electrical equipment.
									  They should always work in pairs.
								  </li>
								  <li>Ensure all high voltage electrical capacitors are discharged.</li>
								  <li>Remove all electrical connections before dismantling any unit/subunit.</li>
							  </ol>
						  </para>
					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.5.2 Tools required  " level="4">
					  <title>2.5.2 Tools required  </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  The tools required for dismantling &amp; reassembly
							  are given in the Table 1.1 below:
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <h6>
								  Table 1.1: Tools
								  required
							  </h6>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <table frame="box" rules="all" width="767">
								  <colgroup>
									  <col width="28*"/>
									  <col width="69*"/>
								  </colgroup>
								  <tbody>
									  <tr>
										  <td>
											  <h6>Sl. No.</h6>
										  </td>
										  <td>
											  <h6>Description</h6>
										  </td>
									  </tr>
									  <tr>
										  <td>1</td>
										  <td>Hydraulic Crane (5T: Launcher; 15T: Winch)</td>
									  </tr>
									  <tr>
										  <td>2</td>
										  <td>Sling &amp; Anchor Shackle Type D (5T: Launcher; 10T: Winch)</td>
									  </tr>
									  <tr>
										  <td>3</td>
										  <td>Screw driver set</td>
									  </tr>
									  <tr>
										  <td>4</td>
										  <td>Allen key set</td>
									  </tr>
									  <tr>
										  <td>5</td>
										  <td>Box spanner Set</td>
									  </tr>
								  </tbody>
							  </table>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <h6>Precautions: </h6>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <ol type="a">
								  <li>
									  <h6>
										  Anchor Shackle &amp; Crane slings should be in good condition
										  and must be visually checked for any damage prior usage.
									  </h6>
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  <h6>
										  The equipment should be well balanced (referring to its CG)
										  during lifting, prior its movement.
									  </h6>
								  </li>
								  <li>
									  <h6>
										  Crane should be operated in presence of safety officer by
										  qualified personnel.
									  </h6>
								  </li>
							  </ol>
						  </para>
					  </content>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.5.3 Dismantling and Re-assembly" level="4">
					  <title>2.5.3 Dismantling and Re-assembly</title>
					  <section id="2.5.3.1 Expendable Device Launcher EDL" level="5">
						  <title>2.5.3.1 Expendable Device Launcher (EDL)</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  <ol type="a">
									  <li>
										  To remove the EDL from the plinth, the following procedure has
										  to be followed:<para></para><para>
											  Step 1:	Disconnect all the connectors (J1, J2
											  &amp; J3) that have been connected to the electrical connector box
											  located inside (see Fig. 2.1), at bottom of the EDL carcass.
										  </para
  ><para>
											  Step 2:	Fix the Anchor Shackle (Type D) to the lifting hooks
											  provided on the top of the EDL and firmly fasten the crane slings
											  to it.
										  </para><para>
											  Step 3:	Remove 20 No’s M20x2.5 nuts &amp; bolts
											  (using Box Spanner Size 24, with joint extension) that fix the EDL
											  structure to the plinth (it is advisable dismantle the bolts in diagonal
											  order starting from outer end to FVA end). (see Fig. 2.1(a))
										  </para
  ><para>
											  Step 4:	Using crane, lift the EDL and separate it from its
											  plinth.
										  </para>
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  For re-assembling the EDL, the following procedure has to
										  be followed:<para></para><para>
											  Step 1:	Firmly fasten and secure the Anchor Shackle
											  (Type D) with the lifting hooks on the EDL, to the crane with slings.
										  </para
  ><para>
											  Step 2:	Lift the EDL and take it to its position (on to the
											  plinth).
										  </para><para>
											  Step 3:	Place the EDL in its position ensuring
											  apertures of base of EDL and plinth in line and the launcher barrel
											  pointing towards the outside of the ship.
										  </para><para>
											  <figure>
												  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_1.gif"></graphic>
												  <figtitle>Fig. 2.1: View of EDL with plinth connectors</figtitle>
											  </figure>
										  </para><para>
											  <figure>
												  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_2.gif"></graphic>
												  <figtitle>Fig. 2.1(a): View of EDL with plinth bolts</figtitle>
											  </figure>
										  </para><para>
											  Step 4:	Secure the EDL in its position and tighten
											  the nuts &amp; bolts that join it to its support, plinth (it is advisable
											  fasten the bolts in diagonal order starting from FVA end then moving
											  towards outside). Remove the slings once it is well-fastened (tightening
											  torque: 161 Nm).
										  </para><para>
											  Step 5:	Remove the Anchor Shackle (Type
											  D) from the EDL lifting hooks.
										  </para><para>
											  Step 6:	Re-fit all the
											  connectors (J1, J2 &amp; J3) to the electrical connector box located
											  inside (see Fig. 2.1), at bottom of the EDL carcass. (Ring marks to
											  ensure proper fitment)
										  </para><para>
											  Step 7:	Check the unit is properly
											  grounded. (Using Earth Resistance Meter, measure the resistance between
											  the prime earth &amp; launcher earth points and between the prime
											  earth &amp; EDL power connector earth. The resistance measured stud
											  shall be &lt; 0.1 Ohms.)
										  </para><para>
											  <note>
												  <para style="color:red">
													  Note: 	The removal and re-assembly procedure for the EDL (Stbd)
													  is identical to that of the EDL (Port).
												  </para>
											  </note>
										  </para>
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  For Installation of EDL,
								  <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V11_Installation_EDL.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
									  Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  For Uninstallation of EDL,
								  <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V20_UninstallationEDL.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
									  Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.5.3.2 Firing Valve Assembly FVA" level="5">
						  <title>2.5.3.2 Firing Valve Assembly (FVA)</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The FVA is bolted on to the EDL and can be removed
								  from the front of the EDL for maintenance. The FVA weighs less than
								  20kgs. See Fig. 2.2.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <ol type="a">
									  <li>
										  To remove the FVA, the following procedure has to be followed:<para></para><para
  >
											  Step 1:	Disengage the Solenoid cable connector that has been connected
											  at electrical connector (Fire Pulse Connector) and the Feedback Connector
											  (12-pin connector) provided on valve body (see Fig. 2.2).
										  </para><para
  >
											  Step 2:	Disconnect the earthing strip that has been bolted on valve
											  body.
										  </para><para>
											  Step 3:	Remove the inlet and vent flexible pipe
											  that has been connected to the FVA.
										  </para><para>
											  Step 4:	Using box
											  spanner (of socket size 19), remove the Hex bolt M12x1.75xL50 with
											  plain washer and lock washer. (See Fig. 2.2 (a))
										  </para><para>
											  Step
											  5:	Take out the FVA and keep it safe by stacking them in wooden box
										  </para
  >
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  For re-assembling the FVA, the following procedure has to be followed:<para></para><para
  >
											  Step 1:	Place the FVA on its position ensuring holes provided on
											  the valve body and the EDL structure in line (See Fig. 2.2(a))
										  </para
  ><para>
											  <figure>
												  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_3.gif"></graphic>
												  <figtitle>Fig. 2.2: View of FVA with Nomenclature</figtitle>
											  </figure>
										  </para><para>
											  <figure>
												  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_4.gif"></graphic>
												  <figtitle>Fig. 2.2(a): View of FVA fitment on EDL Structure </figtitle>
											  </figure>
										  </para><para>
											  Step 2:	Fix the FVA using box spanner (of socket
											  size 19), Hex bolt M12x1.75xL50 with plain washer and lock washer
											  and tighten (tightening torque: 67 Nm) them using appropriate spanner
											  (See Fig. 2.2(a)).
										  </para><para>
											  <note>
												  <para style="color:red">
													  Note: 	Use Loctite-574 between Interface Sleeve Flange of FVA
													  and Front plate of EDL Assembly. Make sure there is no paint, dust,
													  rust or other foreign particles before applying Loctite between Interface
													  Sleeve flange of FVA and front plate of EDL. Use Loctite-243 between
													  threads of M12 Bolts and Nuts.
												  </para>
											  </note>
										  </para><para>
											  Step 3:	Connect electrical connector (Fire Pulse
											  Connector (3 pin)) and the Feedback Connector (12-pin connector) (see
											  Fig. 2.2).
										  </para><para>
											  Step 4:	Connect the earthing strip (i.e.,
											  ring lug which is crimped onto earthing cable) to its stud provided
											  on the valve body and secure using hexagonal bolt.
										  </para><para>
											  Step
											  5:	Connect the inlet and vent flexible pipes that has been removed
											  from the FVA (see Fig. 2.2).
										  </para>
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  For FVA Dismantling,
								  <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V10_FVA_Dismantling.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
									  Click here for video<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.5.3.3 Local Control Unit LCU " level="5">
						  <title>2.5.3.3 Local Control Unit (LCU) </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The LCU is mounted on the side of the EDL. The electrical
								  connector box located at the bottom of the carcass.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <figure>
									  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_5.gif"></graphic>
									  <figtitle>Fig. 2.3: View of LCU on EDL structure</figtitle>
								  </figure>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <ol type="a">
									  <li>
										  For dismantling LCU from the EDL structure, the following procedure
										  has to be followed:<para>
											  <para></para>Step 1:	Open the LCU door.
										  </para><para>
											  Step
											  2:	Remove 12 No’s M3x10 screws that fix the LCU to the EDL structure
											  using appropriate spanner.
										  </para><para>
											  Step 3: 	Lift the LCU up (45
											  degrees from the vertical), hold it and disconnect all the cables
											  that have been connected to the LCU connector plate assembly.
										  </para
  ><para>
											  <note>
												  <para style="color:red">
													  Note:	Two persons are required, one for holding the LCU and
													  the other for removing cable connectors.
												  </para>
											  </note>
										  </para><para>
											  Step 4:	Remove earthing cable and take out the
											  unit.
										  </para>
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  For re-assembling the LCU, the following procedure has to be followed:<para></para><para
  >
											  Step 1:	Place the LCU in its position and connect the cables as per
											  connector designation.
										  </para><para>
											  Step 2:	 Connect the earthing cable
											  to the unit.
										  </para><para>
											  Step 3:	 Fasten 12 No’s M3x10 screws that
											  fix the LCU to the EDL structure.
										  </para><para>
											  Step 4:	Close the LCU
											  door.
										  </para>
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  For Installation of LCU,
								  <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V12_Installation_LCU.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
									  Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  For Uninstallation of LCU,
								  <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V21_UninstallationLCU.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
									  Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.5.3.4 Remote Control Unit RCU" level="5">
						  <title>2.5.3.4 Remote Control Unit (RCU)</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>The RCU is a bulkhead mounted and it weighs 20 kgs.</para
  >
							  <para>
								  <ol type="a">
									  <li>
										  For removing RCU, the following procedure has to be followed:<para></para><para
  >
											  Step 1:	Disconnect all the cables that have been connected to the
											  RCU.
										  </para><para>Step 2: 	Remove earthing strip from the RCU.</para
  ><para>
											  Step 3: 	Remove 4 No’s M3x10 screws that fix the RCU to the
											  ships bulkhead structure/mounting plate and take out.
										  </para><para
  >
											  <note>
												  <para style="color:red">
													  Note:	Two persons are required, one for holding the RCU and
													  the other for removing screws.
												  </para>
											  </note>
										  </para>
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  For re-assembling the RCU, the following procedure has to be followed:<para></para><para
  >
											  Step 1: 	Place the unit on the mounting plate / base on the bulkhead.
										  </para><para>
											  Step 2: 	Secure the unit by using 4 No’s M3x10 screws
											  along with plain and spring washers.
										  </para><para>
											  Step 3: 	Connect
											  all the external cables to the unit as per connector’s designation.
										  </para
  ><para>Step 4:	Connect the earthing cable to the unit</para>
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>

					  <section id="2.5.3.6 Winch  " level="5">
						  <title>2.5.3.6 Winch</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The assembling procedure of winch is carried out in
								  two main assemblies as explained below:
							  </para>
						  </content>
						  <section id="2.5.3.6.1 Gear Drum Brake Assembly   " level="6">
							  <title>2.5.3.6.1 Gear Drum Brake Assembly</title>
							  <content>
								  <para>
									  The Gear drum brake assembly can be assembled sub assembly
									  wise as follows:
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <ol type="a">
										  <li>
											  <h6>Drum Weldment Assembly:</h6> It comprises Flanges, Drum, Port
											  side shaft, Starboard side shaft, Brake flange and Winch drum junction
											  box. These are assembled to guide sleeves and guide sleeve strip using
											  M8X20 hexagon socket countersunk head.
										  </li>
										  <li>
											  <h6>Brake drum assembly:</h6> It comprises Brake C Channel assembly,
											  Brake angle assembly, Brake belt shoe assembly, Brake support bush,
											  Brass bush, Brake threaded bush, Support brake threaded bush, Brake
											  shaft, C link, Fulcrum lever, Brake handle and Spacer. These are assembled
											  using joint pins, split pins and hexagonal flanged head bolt.
										  </li>
										  <li>
											  <h6>MCP:</h6> It consists of MCP box, Joystick mounting plate,
											  MCP cover, insulation box and electronic components. These are assembled
											  using hexagonal socket countersunk, Allen screw and seal.
										  </li>
										  <li>
											  <h6>MCP with shock mounts:</h6> Shock mounts (2 no’s at the bottom
											  of Winch and 1 no. at rear side of the MCP) are bolted to the MCP
											  assembly is fitted.
										  </li>
										  <li>
											  Worm and worm gear box assembly without worm gear, spacer, gear
											  handle, cover and shaft cap. These parts are assembled as Gearbox
											  housing assembly, worm shaft, bevel gear on worm shaft, shaft for
											  bevel gear, bevel gear on handle shaft, bevel gear shaft mounting
											  assembly, bearing locking block, worm shaft side cover, taper bearing,
											  eye-bolt, Allen screw.
										  </li>
										  <li>
											  Encoder Housing Assembly without closing plate, pulleys, gasket
											  and timing belt. These parts are assembled as Encoder housing, encoder
											  rotary cam mounting plate, support block, belt tensioner assembly,
											  encoder, rotary cam, eye-bolt, Allen head bolt.
										  </li>
									  </ol>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  When the above sub-assemblies are ready, the STBD
									  and PORT side support structures are taken for assembly.
								  </para>
								  <para
  >
									  For assembling Gear drum brake assembly, the following procedure
									  has to be followed:
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 1: 	Place the assembled worm
									  and worm gear box assembly on the support structure and fasten the
									  bolts to it. Place the Encoder Housing Assembly on PORT side support
									  structure and fasten the bolts to it.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 2: 	Assemble
									  Drum assembly with the Worm and worm gear box assembly and Encoder
									  housing assembly on STBD and PORT side respectively.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step
									  3:	Assemble Worm gear, spacer, gear handle, cover and shaft cap to
									  the worm and worm gear box assembly.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 4:	Insert the
									  slip ring into the hollow shaft on STBD side.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 5:	Assemble
									  closing plate, pulleys, gasket and timing belt to the encoder housing
									  assembly on the PORT side.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 6:	Two Transportation
									  bars bolted between both the support structures hold the Gear Box-Drum-Brake-MCP
									  assembly intact during transport &amp; installation on a fit-to-receive
									  winch plinth.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 7:	Assemble the brake drum assembly
									  to the support structure on the STBD side and flange.
								  </para>
								  <para
  >
									  Step 8: 	Assemble the motor to the worm shaft using the Rotex coupling
									  on the STBD side and then bolt it to the support structure.
								  </para
  >
								  <para>
									  Step 9:	Assemble the MCP panel with shock mounts to the support
									  structure on the STBD side.
								  </para>
							  </content>
							  <section id="Installation of Fibre Optic Tow Cable FOTC" level="7">
								  <title>Installation of Fibre Optic Tow Cable (FOTC)</title>
								  <content>
									  <para>
										  <h6>Pre installation checks:</h6>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  (1).Once the FOTC entry slots on the drum are positioned
										  at desired locations, ensure that
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <ol type="a">
											  <li>The system is disconnected from main power supply to the Winch</li>
											  <li>
												  Rotation of drum is locked by engaging the manual brake (band
												  brake)
											  </li>
										  </ol>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 1:	Position the drum with Winch Drum Junction
										  Box (WDJB) at an angle of 45°(approx.) with vertical, as depicted
										  in Fig. 2.13 below:
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_15.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.13: Positioning WDJB</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_16.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.14: FOTC Entry Slot on WDJB</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 2:	Switch ON the system and move the Level
										  Wind from its parked position to facilitate the winding of the Tow
										  (see Fig. 2.15 below).
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_17.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.15: Positioning Level Wind</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 3:	Switch OFF the mains supply and insert
										  the Tow through the slot and connect it with its FOTC mating half
										  flanged to the WDJB plate.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_18.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.16: Connecting FOTC cable</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 4:	Release the mechanical brake and Power
										  ON the system.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 5:	Slowly rotate the drum in ‘Recovery’
										  direction while directing the tow to wind on the first grove. Reposition
										  the drum with WDJB at an angle of 45° (approx.) with vertical, as
										  shown in Fig. 2.17 below.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_19.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.17: Reposition the drum with WDJB</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 6:	Disconnect Winch from the mains supply
										  and lock in this position with Manual Brake.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 7:	Insert
										  the clamp on to the cable at the entry point and clamp it to the drum
										  by fastening 2 No’s Allen bolts of Size M5 (3 pair of holes helps
										  to fasten the clamp at desired positions)
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_20.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.18: Clamping cable to the Drum</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 8:	Switch ON the system and release the
										  manual brake.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 9:	Wind the Tow on the drum by simultaneously
										  guiding it through Level Wind.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_21.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.19: Winding Tow on the Drum</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 10:	Once the complete Tow is wound on the
										  drum, lock the drum by engaging the manual brake. The end of the tow
										  should be aligned to the reference position (i.e., Level Wind)
									  </para
  >
									  <para>
										  <note>
											  <para style="color:red">
												  Note:	Refer to the ‘Rotary Cam Limit Switch calibration/setting
												  procedure’ for setting 	up the tow position, rotary cam limit switch
												  and cable length display.
											  </para>
										  </note>
									  </para>
								  </content>
							  </section>
							  <section id="Drum Motor Installation and Alignment Procedure " level="7">
								  <title>Drum Motor Installation and Alignment Procedure </title>
								  <content>
									  <para>
										  Note:	Ensure that rotation of drum is locked by engaging the
										  manual brake (band brake)
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 1:	Mount both the Flexible Coupling halves
										  on the shaft of Gear Box and Electric Motor Shaft, by fastening the
										  grub Screws.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 2:	Lift the motor with Crane (Capacity:
										  05 ton) and place it at its location on the STBD Side Support Structure
										  and slide into the coupling half on GB shaft.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_22.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.20: Fixing Motor</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 3:	Align the mounting holes on Electric
										  Motor with holes on Support Structure and loosely fasten with 4 No’s
										  bolts of size M16x80.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 4:	Disengage the Electric Motor
										  from the Crane.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 5:	Measure the height of both couplings
										  at locations on both the coupling halves as shown in the images below.
										  (Machined surface of the STBD Support Structure is used as datum reference
										  and the height is measured using Height Gauge.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 6:	Adjust
										  the height difference by inserting appropriate sizes of shims at the
										  base of Electric Motor. (The height difference should not be more
										  than 0.2mm)
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_23.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.21: Adjusting motor height</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 6:	Post height adjustments, gaps between
										  both the couplings is measured using Filler Gauges at four locations
										  as shown in the image below:
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_24.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.22: Measuring couplings using Filler Gauges</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_25.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.22(a): Measuring couplings using Filler Gauges</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 7:	Record the readings and determine the
										  summation of Vertical and Horizontal readings and calculate the difference
										  between them as given below:
									  </para>
									  <para>Vertical: a+b = 2.30 mm</para
  >
									  <para>Horizontal: c+d = 2.15 mm</para>
									  <para>
										  Difference = 2.30-2.15
										  = 0.15 mm
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 8:	The assembly is considered to be properly
										  aligned if the difference value is less than 15% of the higher values
										  among measured readings. (that is, 0.15 mm is less than 15%  i.e.
										  0.345 mm of 2.30 mm)
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  For Drum Motor Installation,                     <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V8_drum_installatio.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
											  Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
										  </a>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  For Drum Motor Uninstallation,
										  <a onclick="javascript:parent.VideoFrame(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Video/videos/V9_drum_uninstallatio.mp4&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;" actuate="uSer">
											  Click here <img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/video.gif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
										  </a>
									  </para>
								  </content>
							  </section>
							  <section id="Electric Brake Manual Release and Engage" level="7">
								  <title>Electric Brake Manual Release and Engage</title>
								  <content>
									  <para>
										  Note: Ensure that the Manual Brake is applied before releasing
										  the Electric Brake.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 1:	Remove the M20 (A/F 24) Hexagonal Bolts
										  (2 No’s) of the Brake Housing Cover.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_43.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.40: Removal of Brake Housing Cover</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 2:	Using 6 mm Allen Key, tighten the M8
										  Allen Screw fully to release the Brake.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_44.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.41: Tightening screws for releasing Brake</figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 3:	Using 6 mm Allen Key, loosen the Allen
										  Screw (M8) by rotating two turns to engage the Brake.
									  </para>
								  </content>
							  </section>
						  </section>
						  <section id="2.5.3.6.2 Level Wind Assembly " level="6">
							  <title>2.5.3.6.2 Level Wind Assembly </title>
							  <content>
								  <para>
									  The level wind assembly can be assembled sub assembly
									  wise as follows:
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <ol type="a">
										  <li>
											  <h6>Base C-section assembly:</h6>  The C-clock and C-block mounting
											  plate is welded to form the Base C-section assembly.
										  </li>
										  <li>
											  <h6>Sliding C-Section assembly:</h6> Sliding C section, Angle
											  section, Wheel mounting rod, Hook block are welded to for this assembly
										  </li>
										  <li>
											  <h6>Guide structure flap assembly:</h6> Side flaps are welded
											  to the base plate. Then the Nylon plate is bolted to it.
										  </li>
										  <li>
											  <h6>Guide structure assembly:</h6> Firstly the guide structure
											  sub assembly comprising of leveler support plate, plate, support plate,
											  pin holding, sensor rod, holding cap L-section, metal bush is created.
											  Then the bush is press fitted. Then the guide structure flap assemblies
											  are connected to the guide structure assembly using the flap pins.
											  Then the support shafts are assembled.  Then the nylon block is bolted
											  to the guide structure. Then the support shaft mounting block is press
											  fitted to the ends of support shaft.
										  </li>
									  </ol>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  For assembling level wind assembly, the following
									  procedure has to be followed:
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 1: 	Assemble Base C-section
									  assembly to the sliding C-section assembly.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 2: 	Bolt
									  the guide structure assembly to the Sliding C-section assembly along
									  with the lead screw.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 3: 	Assemble the bearing hub
									  on both ends of the lead screw and then insert taper bearing both
									  ends.
								  </para>
								  <para>Step 4: 	Assemble the bearing lock nut.</para>
								  <para
  >Step 5: 	Assemble the level wind cap.</para>
								  <para>
									  Step 6: 	Assemble
									  the motor coupling.
								  </para>
								  <para>Step 7: 	Bolt the Motor mounting bracket.</para
  >
								  <para>
									  Step 8: 	Mount the motor on the mounting bracket with the motor
									  coupling
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 9: 	Connect the level wind handle and T-level
									  wind handle to the sliding C-section assembly
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 10:
									  Assemble the I-bolts on both sides.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 11: 	Use support
									  strip to connect both sides of the base C-section assembly.
								  </para
  >
							  </content>

							  <section id="Disassembly-Proximity Sensor  " level="7">
								  <title>Disassembly-Proximity Sensor  </title>
								  <content>
									  <para>
										  The faulty proximity sensor of Starboard side or Port
										  side shall be replaced as per the procedure given below:
									  </para>
									  <para
  >
										  Step 1:	Remove the cable clamp (M5x40) (2 No’s) that secure the Proximity
										  Sensor cable leading to the MCP.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 2: 	Using Allen
										  Key, remove the Allen Bolts of M5 (2 No’s) so as to remove the proximity
										  sensor along with its guard cover.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  <figure>
											  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_5_48.gif"></graphic>
											  <figtitle>Fig. 2.45: Disassembly-Proximity Sensor </figtitle>
										  </figure>
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 3: 	Disconnect the rotary connector at
										  MCP.
									  </para>
								  </content>
							  </section>
							  <section id="Assembly - Proximity Sensor" level="7">
								  <title>Assembly - Proximity Sensor</title>
								  <content>
									  <para>
										  Step 1:	Mount the proximity sensor along with its guard
										  cover to the Level Wind Structure by fastening Allen Bolts of size
										  M5 (2 No’s).
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 2:	Connect the rotary connector of Proximity
										  Sensor to the MCP.
									  </para>
									  <para>
										  Step 3:	Clamp the cable leading to
										  the MCP using (M5x40) (2 No’s) for the Proximity Sensor.
									  </para>
								  </content>
							  </section>

						  </section>
						  <section id="2.5.3.6.3 Fairlead Assembly " level="6">
							  <title>2.5.3.6.3 Fairlead Assembly </title>
							  <content>
								  <para>
									  The Fairlead assembly can be assembled on its plinth
									  which has been welded onto deck, as follows:
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 1:
									  Ensure the Fairlead and its plinth are aligned to the center of the
									  drum and the assembly is located at the stern of the ship
								  </para>
								  <para
  >
									  Step 2: 	Assemble the Fairlead by bolting it with M20X10 no’s to
									  the plinth structure (also ensure that shower arrangement pipe is
									  facing towards FWD side of the ship)
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 3: 	Post installation,
									  connect the fresh water supply source to the shower inlet pipe during
									  recovery of the tow, to wash the tow.
								  </para>
							  </content>
						  </section>
					  </section>
				  </section>
			  </section>
			  <section id="2.6 Test Procedures" level="3">
				  <title>	Test Procedures</title>
				  <content>
					  <para>
						  <h6>2.6	Introduction </h6>
					  </para>
					  <para>
						  Test procedures are designed to monitor the performance
						  levels of systems and subsystems. These levels can be monitored and
						  measured at various points in the equipment. The following are the
						  list of units whose test procedures/overhauling specifications are
						  provided:
					  </para>
					  <para>
						  <ol type="1">
							  <li>Firing Valve Assembly (FVA)</li>
							  <li>Expendable Device Launcher (EDL) </li>
							  <li>Local Control Unit (LCU)</li>
							  <li>Remote Control Unit (RCU)</li>
							  <li>Winch</li>
							  <li>Main Control Panel (MCP)</li>
							  <li>Fairlead</li>
							  <li>Console</li>
						  </ol>
					  </para>
				  </content>
				  <section id="2.6.1 Firing Valve Assembly MDNS-62-02-02-00-000" level="4">
					  <title>2.6.1 Firing Valve Assembly (MDNS-62-02-02-00-000)  </title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  FVA is used to propel the EAD at a minimum firing velocity
							  of 25m/s. The FVA receives air supply and electrical signals from
							  the Air Supply Inlet and Electrical Cable Inlet of the EDL plinth
							  at the bottom of the EDL. The following tests shall be performed on
							  all FVAs, (reinstalled FVAs and repaired FVAs) prior to initial use,
							  to verify functional compliance:
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <ol type="1">
								  <li>Solenoid operational test</li>
								  <li>Proximity sensor test</li>
								  <li>Pressure sensor test</li>
								  <li>Pneumatic assembly leakage test</li>
							  </ol>
						  </para>
