					  <section id="2.6.1.1 Solenoid Operational Test " level="5">
						  <title>2.6.1.1 Solenoid Operational Test </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The purpose of this test is to verify whether the solenoid
								  being tested is functioning correctly. To perform this test, the FVA
								  under test must be discharged completely.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Test Procedure</h6
  >
								  <para>Carry out the following:</para>
								  <para>
									  <ol type="a">
										  <li>
											  Connect the 24VDC external power supply cable to the terminal
											  of solenoid valve
										  </li>
										  <li>
											  Switch ON the power supply, noise due to solenoid activation should
											  be heard when 24VDC is given to the solenoid valve.
										  </li>
									  </ol>
								  </para>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.6.1.2 Proximity Sensor Test" level="5">
						  <title>2.6.1.2 Proximity Sensor Test</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The purpose of this test is to determine if the proximity
								  sensor being tested is functioning correctly
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>
									  Test
									  equipment and accessories required
								  </h6>
								  <para>
									  Following are the test
									  equipment and accessories required:
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <ol type="a">
										  <li>Power supply unit, 24VDC 	-	1 No.</li>
										  <li>Multimeter			-	1 No</li>
										  <li>Power supply terminals 	-	As required</li>
									  </ol>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Test Setup</h6>
								  <para>
									  The test setup is
									  shown in the figure below:
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_6_1_2.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Test Setup - Proximity Sensor Test</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Test Procedure</h6>
								  <para>
									  Carry out
									  the following:
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <ol type="a">
										  <li>
											  Connect the positive terminal of the Proximity sensor to power
											  supply unit (24VDC) and negative terminal to the positive of the Multimeter.
										  </li>
										  <li>
											  Connect the negative terminal of the power supply unit to the
											  negative terminal of the Multimeter.
										  </li>
										  <li>Switch ON the power supply unit.</li>
										  <li>Place a magnet on top of the proximity sensor</li>
										  <li>
											  Observe the current reading on the Multimeter. Current should
											  be between 14.5mA to 19.5mA.
										  </li>
									  </ol>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <note>
										  <para style="color:red">
											  The sensor must detect the magnet when it is placed on top of
											  it and 	subsequently current is recorded on the multimeter.
										  </para>
									  </note>
								  </para>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.6.1.3 Pressure Sensor Test " level="5">
						  <title>2.6.1.3 Pressure Sensor Test </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The purpose of this test is to verify whether the pressure
								  sensor being tested is functioning correctly.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>
									  Test
									  equipment and accessories required
								  </h6>
								  <para>
									  Following are the test
									  equipment and accessories required:
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <ol type="a">
										  <li>Power supply unit, 24VDC 	-	1 No.</li>
										  <li>Multimeter			-	1 No.</li>
										  <li>Power supply terminals 	-	As required</li>
									  </ol>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Test Setup  </h6>
								  <para>
									  The test setup
									  is shown in the figure below:
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_6_1_3.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Test Setup - Pressure Sensor Test</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Test Procedure: </h6>
								  <para>
									  Carry
									  out the following:
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <ol type="a">
										  <li>
											  Connect the positive terminal of the pressure sensor to positive
											  terminal of power supply unit (24VDC) and negative terminal to positive
											  of Multimeter
										  </li>
										  <li>
											  Connect negative terminal of Multimeter to negative terminal of
											  power supply unit.
										  </li>
										  <li>Switch ON the power supply unit</li>
										  <li>Pressurize the reservoir with the air source.</li>
										  <li>
											  Observe the current reading on the Multimeter after the reservoir
											  is pressurized. Current should be between 8.5mA to 20mA.
										  </li>
									  </ol>
								  </para>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.6.1.4 Pneumatic assembly leakage test  " level="5">
						  <title>2.6.1.4 Pneumatic assembly leakage test  </title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  The purpose of this test is to make sure that the pneumatic
								  connections are airtight. Leaks are likely to occur at pipe connectors,
								  plugs, pneumatic joints, the main seal or wherever o-rings or gaskets
								  are located. The exact location of a leak can be detected by spraying
								  a soap water solution around the pipe connectors, plugs/joints and
								  then checking for air bubbles. This test is carried out post installation/assembly
								  of individual FVA
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <ol type="a">
									  <li>
										  Set the 5-way mechanical selector valve ‘SAFE/VENT/CHARGE/ARM’
										  to ‘CHARGE’
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Charge the FVA assembly to 20 bar (test pressure) (for tests in
										  controlled environment)
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Set the 5-way mechanical selector valve ‘SAFE/VENT/CHARGE/ARM’
										  to ‘SAFE’
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Spray soap water solution around the pneumatic plugs/joints and
										  check for any leakage. If a leak is detected, discharge the FVA completely
										  by setting the 5-way mechanical selector valve ‘SAFE/VENT/CHARGE/ARM’
										  to ‘VENT’.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Post discharge, retighten the joint/part and apply Loctite 577
										  and then recheck the unit as per the procedure explained in above
										  steps
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
				  </section>
				  <section id="2.6.2 Expendable Device Launcher EDL" level="4">
					  <title>2.6.2 Expendable Device Launcher (EDL)</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  <table frame="box" rules="all">
								  <colgroup>
									  <col/>
									  <col/>
									  <col/>
									  <col/>
									  <col/>
									  <col/>
									  <col/>
								  </colgroup>
								  <tbody>
									  <tr>
										  <td rowspan="2">
											  <h6>Sl. No.</h6>
										  </td>
										  <td rowspan="2">
											  <h6>Description</h6>
										  </td>
										  <td rowspan="2">
											  <h6>Part No.</h6>
										  </td>
										  <td colspan="3">
											  <h6>Related documents</h6>
										  </td>
									  </tr>
									  <tr>
										  <td>
											  <h6>
												  SD
											  </h6>
										  </td>
										  <td>
											  <h6>GA</h6>
										  </td>
										  <td>
											  <h6>PL</h6>
										  </td>

									  </tr>
									  <tr>
										  <td>1	</td>
										  <td>EDL</td>
										  <td>MDNS-62-02-00-00-000</td>
										  <td>
											  <a
							onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_1_1.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
							actuate="user">SD</a>
										  </td>
										  <td>
											  <a
							onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/1_1_EDL_ASSEMBLY.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
							actuate="user">GA</a>
										  </td>
										  <td>
											  <a
							onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/EDL_PL.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
							actuate="user">PL</a>
										  </td>

									  </tr>
								  </tbody>
							  </table>
						  </para>

						  <para>
							  The launcher is used to launch Expendable Acoustic
							  Devices (EADs). Each EDL has a capacity to launch 10 EADs simultaneously
							  through extended launch barrel assemblies; each barrel can be independently
							  operated.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <h6>EDL Configuration</h6>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  The EDL
							  will be configured in the normal operating condition to enable the
							  unit to be powered up and the required operating measurements to be
							  taken. The test will be carried out in an environment where the ambient
							  temperature will be maintained at +30°C ±5°C. The EDL and RCU is designed
							  to operate over the following input:
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <ol type="a">
								  <li>115VAC, 50/60Hz, Single Phase or</li>
								  <li>380VAC, 50/60Hz, 3 Phase or</li>
								  <li>415VAC, 50/60Hz, 3 Phase or</li>
								  <li>450VAC, 50/60Hz, 3 Phase </li>
							  </ol>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  Unless stated otherwise, the primary power to the
							  EDL during testing shall be 415VAC, 50Hz, 3 Phase (Delta configuration).
						  </para
  >
						  <para>
							  <h6>Pre-requisites</h6>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  The prerequisites that
							  should be met prior to performing the tests are given below.
						  </para
  >
						  <para>
							  <ol type="a">
								  <li>All FVAs are in SAFE position.</li>
								  <li>Local Control Unit and Remote Control Unit are powered OFF.</li>
								  <li>Power supply cable assembly is disconnected from the power source.</li>
								  <li>Main air supply is disconnected from the launcher.</li>
							  </ol>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <h6>Test Equipment</h6>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  The following
							  are the test equipments required:
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <table frame="box"
					rules="all">
								  <colgroup>
									  <col/>
									  <col/>
								  </colgroup>
								  <tbody>
									  <tr>
										  <td>
											  <h6>Sl. No.</h6>
										  </td>
										  <td>
											  <h6>Test Equipment Description</h6>
										  </td>
									  </tr>
									  <tr>
										  <td>1</td>
