									  <li>Laptop loaded with Status Software Version_1.4.</li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Test Procedure</h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Perform the
								  following:
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <ol type="a">
									  <li>
										  Connect Valve Simulator to LCU. EDL Simulator has five selector
										  switches, one each for Pressure feedback, Resistance value, Vent position
										  feedback, ARM position feedback and SAFE position feedback. Each position
										  of the selector switch provides a certain feedback, as explained below:
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Proximity Sensors: There are 4 positions (SAFE, ARM and VENT).
										  The state of current generating for each position is as given below:<ol
  type="i">
											  <li>
												  Position-1 (2.5 mA): It is considered to be a Fault condition
												  when current lies from 0 mA – 3 mA,
											  </li>
											  <li>
												  Position-2 (6 mA):  It is considered to be a Low condition when
												  current lies from 3 mA – 8 mA (Logic 0)
											  </li>
											  <li>
												  Position-3 (9.5mA): It is considered to be a Fault condition when
												  current lies from 8 mA – 11 mA
											  </li>
											  <li>
												  Position-4 (16 mA): It is considered to be a High condition when
												  current lies from 11 mA – 20 mA (Logic 1)
											  </li>
										  </ol>
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Fault Identification for Pressure Sensors:<ol type="i">
											  <li>
												  Position-1 (2.5 mA): It is considered to be a Fault condition
												  when current lies from 0 mA – 3 mA
											  </li>
											  <li>
												  Position-2 (5.5 mA): It is considered to be a Low condition when
												  current lies from 3 mA – 7 mA (Logic 0)
											  </li>
											  <li>
												  Position-3 (8 mA): It is considered to be a High condition when
												  current lies from 7 mA – 20 mA (Logic 1)
											  </li>
										  </ol>
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Start conditions for available indicator to glow is as follows:<ol
  type="i">
											  <li>Pressure Switch – Position 3, it is High condition (Logic 1)</li>
											  <li>Resistance </li>
											  <li>Safe Position – Position 2, it is Low condition (Logic 0)</li>
											  <li>ARM Position – Position 4, it is High condition (Logic 1)</li>
											  <li>VENT Position – Position 2, it is Low condition (Logic 0) </li>
										  </ol>
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Test Procedure for Valve Simulation<ol type="a">
											  <li>Ensure that power supply to the LCU is OFF.</li>
											  <li>
												  Connect the Valve Simulation Test Jig to the LCU for any one firing
												  valve of choice.
											  </li>
											  <li>Switch ON the LCU and put SAFE/ENABLE switch to ENABLE position.</li>
											  <li>
												  Verify the function of the FVA that has been connected to the
												  Valve Simulation Test Jig by means of selector switches in accordance
												  with procedure mentioned below. Record the results obtained in the
												  TDR-2.13. <ol type="i">
													  <li>
														  Select selector switch on Valve Simulation Test Jig for Proximity
														  sensor (SAFE, ARM, VENT) Positions viz., Position 1- Fault, Position
														  2- LOW, Position 3- Fault, Position 4- HIGH and record the reading
														  in TDR-2.13 for each position.
													  </li>
													  <li>
														  Select selector switch on Valve Simulation Test Jig for simulation
														  of pressure sensor viz., Position 1- Fault, Position 2- LOW, Position
														  3-HIGH and record the readings in TDR-2.13
													  </li>
													  <li>Verify only EAD type value on the Simulation EDL Status Software.</li>
												  </ol>
											  </li>
										  </ol>
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
