				  <section id="2.6.5 Winch MDNS 62 01 00 00 000 R0" level="4">
					  <title>2.6.5 Winch (MDNS-62-01-00-00-000 R0)</title>
					  <content>
						  <para>
							  <table frame="box" rules="all">
								  <colgroup>
									  <col/>
									  <col/>
									  <col/>
									  <col/>
									  <col/>
									  <col/>
								  </colgroup>
								  <tbody>
									  <tr>
										  <td align="center">
											  <h6>Sl. No.</h6>
										  </td>
										  <td align="center">
											  <h6>Description</h6>
										  </td>
										  <td align="center">
											  <h6>Part No.</h6>
										  </td>
										  <td align="center" colspan="3">
											  <h6>Related documents</h6>
										  </td>
									  </tr>
									  <tr>
										  <td>1</td>
										  <td>Winch</td>
										  <td>MDNS-62-01-00-00-000 R0</td>
										  <td>
											  (<a
									   onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_3_10.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
									   actuate="user">Wiring Diagram</a>)
										  </td>
										  <td>
											  (<a
									   onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Fig_5_1_Winch.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
									   actuate="user">GA</a>)
										  </td>
										  <td>
											  (<a
									   onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Winch_PL.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
									   actuate="user">PL</a>)
										  </td>
									  </tr>
								  </tbody>
							  </table>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  The Winch is used to deploy and recover the Fiber
							  Optic Tow Cable. It consists of a single drum with shaft mounted on
							  a support structure, Level Wind Assembly, Rotary Housing, Main Control
							  Panel (MCP), Slip Ring assembly, Motors (for Level Wind &amp; Drum)
							  and Junction Boxes (SRJB and WDJB). The winch drum is driven by an
							  electric motor coupled through a gear box, it can also be operated
							  manually. A Main Control Panel (MCP) is provided for electric operation
							  of the winch, manual operation of the winch drum, level wind and band
							  brake are through a hand wheel. A level wind assembly is provided
							  on the backward side of the winch drum as a cable guide controlling
							  the lateral movement of the cable to be wound on the drum of the winch.
							  A band of drum brake covering the drum flange is provided for locking
							  the winch during maintenance. The above structure is mounted on a
							  winch plinth which is welded on the ship
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <figure>
								  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/2_6_5_1.gif"></graphic>
							  </figure>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <figure>
								  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/2_6_5_2.gif"></graphic>
							  </figure>
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  The overhauling of the winch is carried out
							  for the following assemblies.
						  </para>
						  <para>
							  <ol type="a">
								  <li>Gear Box Assembly</li>
								  <li>Level Wind Assembly</li>
								  <li>
									  Encoder Assembly<ol type="i">
										  <li>Belt Tension Setting Procedure</li>
										  <li>Timing Pulley Installation</li>
										  <li>Rotary Cam Limit Switch setting procedure</li>
									  </ol>
								  </li>
								  <li>Band Brake Assembly</li>
								  <li>Main Control Panel (MCP)</li>
							  </ol>
						  </para>
					  </content>
					  <section id="2.6.5.1 Gear Box Assembly" level="5">
						  <title>2.6.5.1 Gear Box Assembly</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  For the wiring details from Drum Motor and Motor Junction
								  Box to MCP,(<a
				onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_3_12.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
				actuate="user">
									  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>)
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  For the wiring
								  details of Slip Ring Assembly with SRJB and WDJB,(<a
onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_3_14.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
actuate="user">
									  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>)
							  </para
>
							  <para>
								  For the wiring diagram of SRJB to Plinth and MCP,(<a
onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_3_15.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
actuate="user">
									  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>)
							  </para
>
							  <para>
								  For wiring diagram from WDJB to Slip Ring Assembly and Connection
								  Details of WDJB to SRA,(<a
onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_3_16.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
actuate="user">
									  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
								  </a>)
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Carryout the
								  following:
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 1:	Ensure that power supply to the system
								  is switched OFF.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 2:	Remove all electrical connections
								  that are connected to the Motor and also disconnect its associated
								  cables that are connected in the Motor terminal box.
							  </para>
							  <para
>
								  Step 3:	Remove 4 in no’s M16 bolts that fix the motor to the support
								  structure using appropriate spanner.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 4:	Disengage
								  the motor from the coupling by sliding it out manually and keep it
								  a side
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 5:	Remove 14 no’s M6 screws that fix the front
								  over to the slip ring junction box assembly.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 6:	Disengage
								  32 no’s (28 electrical lines + 4 optical lines) slip ring pigtails.On
								  the port side, dismantle the following:
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 7:	Remove
								  the winch drum junction box cover that has been fixed to the winch
								  drum assembly by unscrewing 16 no’s M6 screws.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 8:	Disengage
								  FOTC connectors that have been connected to its connector plate. Remove
								  optical repeater by unscrewing 4 mounting screws.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step
								  9:	Disengage high voltage/low voltage connectors that have been connected
								  inner side of the WDJB.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 10:	Remove 6 in no’s M10
								  screws that have been fastened to the Starboard shaft of the slip
								  ring assembly.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 11:	Hold the slip ring assembly
								  and slide out it from the Starboard shaft.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <note>
									  <para style="color:red">
										  At least 2 personnel are required when slip ring assembly is
										  being removed.
									  </para>
								  </note>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 12:	Set the Two-way ball valve to ‘open’
								  position and drain the oil from the gear box assembly. Step 13:	Remove
								  seal plate fro
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 13:	Remove seal plate front side by
								  unscrewing 4 in no’s M12 screws.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 14:	Remove gear
								  box cover plate by unscrewing 20 in no’s M10 Allen bolts.
							  </para>
							  <para
>Step 15:	Clean/dry the oil from the gear box.</para>
							  <para>
								  Step 16:	Remove
								  bearing hub locking plate from both sides by means of spanner.
							  </para
>
							  <para>Step 17:	Remove tapper bearing from worm shaft.</para>
							  <para
>
								  Step 18:	Slide out the worm shaft towards the motor side by rotating
								  counter clockwise.
							  </para>
							  <para>Step 19:	Remove worm shaft.</para>
							  <para
>
								  Step 20:	Slide out the worm wheel shaft with spacer using special
								  tool ‘worm wheel puller’ tool.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 21:	Firmly fasten
								  and secure the tool with the EDL carcass to the crane with slings
							  </para
>
							  <para>
								  Step 22:	Insert the slings into the 22 diameter apertures provided
								  on either side of the winch drum and lift slightly upwards for securing
								  its drum shaft/flange so as to avoid any damage
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 23:	Remove
								  8 in no’s M20 nuts located at gear box structure.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6
>Dismantle encoder housing </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 24:	Dismantle encoder
								  housing by removing 4 in no’s M20 screws. (Starboard side)
							  </para>
							  <para
>Step 25:	Slide out gear box assembly from the winch.  </para>
							  <para
>
								  <note>
									  <para style="color:red">
										  Additional lifting arrangement should be provided when gear
										  box assembly is being removed from the winch.
									  </para>
								  </note>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <h6>Overhauling: </h6>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <ol type="a">
									  <li>
										  Replace sealing.<para>
											  <note>
												  <para style="color:red">Do not re-use seals</para>
											  </note>
										  </para>
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Clean the threading of bearing plate / mating parts and apply
										  a thin layer of grease on the cleaned part.
									  </li>
									  <li>
										  Inspect the internal parts of gear box assembly for dirt and corrosion;
										  check the presence of any cracks, bends or any other external damages
										  / abnormalities
									  </li>
								  </ol>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <note>
									  <para style="color:red">
										  Slings/ropes being used should have sufficient strength and
										  capable of holding the winch drum along with gear box assembly and
										  encoder assembly. Ensure that there is no load on the gear box assembly
										  and encoder assembly when the winch drum is being hoisted otherwise
										  it can cause damage to the gear box assembly shaft.
									  </para>
								  </note>
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.6.5.2 Level Wind Assembly" level="5">
						  <title>2.6.5.2 Level Wind Assembly</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  <table frame="box" rules="all">
									  <colgroup>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
									  </colgroup>
									  <tbody>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">
												  <h6>Sl. No.</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td align="center">
												  <h6>Description</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td align="center">
												  <h6>Part No.</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td align="center" colspan="3">
												  <h6>Related documents</h6>
											  </td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td>1</td>
											  <td>Level Wind Assembly</td>
											  <td>MDNS-62-01-03-00-000 R0</td>
											  <td>
												  (<a
										   onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_3_13.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
										   actuate="user">Wiring Diagram</a>)
											  </td>
											  <td>
												  (<a
										   onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Fig_5_39_Level_Wind_ASM.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
										   actuate="user">GA</a>)
											  </td>
											  <td>
												  (<a
										   onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Level_Wind_Assy_PL.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
										   actuate="user">PL</a>)
											  </td>
										  </tr>
									  </tbody>
								  </table>
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  This assembly can be overhauled onboard ship
								  or work shop/dockyard.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 1:	Remove 10 in no M20 bolts
								  that fix the base of the level wind assembly to the plinth.
							  </para
>
							  <para>
								  Step 2:	Firmly fasten the slings to the eye bolts provided
								  on either side of the level wind assembly
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 3:	Lift
								  the level wind assembly.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 4:	Dismantle the motor
								  with bracket by removing 4 in no’s M10 dowel pins.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step
								  5:	Hold the motor with pulley.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 6:	Remove 4 in no’s
								  M16 bolts that are fastened to the bracket/level wind.
							  </para>
							  <para
>
								  Step 7:	Slide out the motor from the coupling until it disengages
								  from the shaft coupling.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 8:	Remove M6 grub screw
								  that has been secured with in the shaft coupling. Take out the coupling.
							  </para
>
							  <para>
								  Step 9:	Disengage the threaded lock nut on either side of the
								  level wind assembly.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 10:	Remove the tapper bearing
								  on either side along with lock nut.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 11:	Remove bearing
								  hub by removing 4 in no’s each M12 nuts on either side.
							  </para>
							  <para
>
								  Step 12:	Remove the lead screw by hand rotating clock wise until
								  it comes out from the assembly.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  <note>
									  <para style="color:red">
										  The lead screw can be removed quickly if the guide structure
										  assembly is parked at the extreme end of the starboard side of the
										  level wind assembly.
									  </para>
								  </note>
							  </para>
							  <h6>Dismantling of Sliding C assembly:</h6>
							  <para>
								  Step
								  13:	Remove dowel pin.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 14:	Secure eye bolt and lift
								  guide structure assembly.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 15:	Remove 16 in no’s M16
								  nuts each from both sides
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 16:	Take out the guide
								  structure assembly, bracket and sliding shaft.
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 17:	Disengage
								  the sealing cover plate by removing 8 in no’s M8 nuts both sides.
							  </para
>
							  <para>Step 18:	Take out the rubber seal along with sealing plate</para
>
							  <para>
								  Step 19:	Remove 4 in no’s M8 screws on right side of the guide
								  structure assembly and remove the threaded bush
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 20:	Replace
								  threaded bush with new one (Oiling/greasing shall be done during installation)
							  </para
>
							  <para>
								  Step 21:	Inspect the lead screw for dirt and corrosion; check
								  for the presence of any cracks, bends or any other external damages
								  / abnormalities
							  </para>
						  </content>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.6.5.3 Encoder Assembly" level="5">
						  <title>2.6.5.3 Encoder Assembly</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  <table frame="box" rules="all">
									  <colgroup>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
										  <col/>
									  </colgroup>
									  <tbody>
										  <tr>
											  <td align="center">
												  <h6>Sl. No.</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td align="center">
												  <h6>Description</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td align="center">
												  <h6>Part No.</h6>
											  </td>
											  <td align="center" colspan="3">
												  <h6>Related documents</h6>
											  </td>
										  </tr>
										  <tr>
											  <td>1</td>
											  <td>Encoder Assembly</td>
											  <td>MDNS-62-01-02-04-000 R0</td>
											  <td>
												  (<a
										   onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Plate_3_11.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
										   actuate="user">Wiring Diagram</a>)
											  </td>
											  <td>
												  (<a
										   onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Encoder_Housing_ASM.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
										   actuate="user">GA</a>)
											  </td>
											  <td>
												  (<a
										   onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/EncoderhousingAssy_PL.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
										   actuate="user">PL</a>)
											  </td>
										  </tr>
									  </tbody>
								  </table>
							  </para>
							  <para>Dismantle the encoder assembly as given below:</para
>
							  <para>
								  Step 1:	Using Allen key, remove the 15 No’s Allen Bolts (M6x1x25)
								  that has been fastened to the closing plate of the Encoder Housing
								  Assembly (Stack the removed bolts properly until the procedure is
								  completed).
							  </para>
							  <para>
								  Step 2:	Remove electrical connections that
								  have been terminated at the Rotary encoder and Rotary Cam Limit Switch.
							  </para
>
							  <para>Step 3:	Remove the seals.</para>
							  <para>
								  Step 4:	Loosen the timing
								  belt.
							  </para>
							  <para>Step 5:	Slide out the encoder arm from the shaft. </para
>
							  <para>Step 6:	Remove seal by means of unfastening 4 in no’s M12 bolts.</para
>
							  <para>
								  Step 7:	Inspect the encoder assembly for dirt and corrosion
								  and take corrective measures
							  </para>
						  </content>
						  <section id="2.6.5.3.1 Belt Tension Setting Procedure " level="6">
							  <title>2.6.5.3.1 Belt Tension Setting Procedure </title>
							  <content>
								  <para>
									  The main objective of this test is to check whether
									  the belt is capable of holding its tension when a moderate pressure
									  of 25N is applied.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <h6>
										  Test equipment &amp; accessories
										  required
									  </h6>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <ol type="1">
										  <li>Digital Belt Tensioner Meter	-	01 No.</li>
										  <li>Measuring probe with cable	-	01 No.</li>
									  </ol>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <h6>Test Setup</h6>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  The test setup is
									  shown in Fig. 2.7 below:
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/2_6_5_3_1.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>
											  Fig. 2.7: Digital Belt Tensioner Meter showing force and
											  deflection of belt
										  </figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <h6>Test Procedure</h6>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Carry out
									  the following:
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 1:	Ensure that power supply to the
									  Encoder Housing Assembly is switched OFF.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 2:	Using
									  Allen key, remove the 15 No’s Allen Bolts (M6x1x25) that has been
									  fastened to the closing plate of the Encoder Housing Assembly (Stack
									  the removed bolts properly until the procedure is completed)
								  </para
>
								  <para>
									  Step 3:	Ensure that all timing pulleys are on the same parallel
									  plane with each other.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  For Timing Pulley Installation,
									  (<a
							   onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/TIMING_PULLEY_INSTALLATION.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
							   actuate="user">
										  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
									  </a>)
								  </para
>
								  <para>
									  Step 4:	Align the steel rule with the Timing Belt. On the Analog
									  Belt Tensioner Meter (see Fig. 2.8), set the large O-ring at value
									  less than 10mm and apply a force of 25 N at the location on belt (until
									  large O-ring touches the steel rule) (see Fig. 2.7(a)).
								  </para>
								  <para
>
									  Step 5:	Repeat Step (3), until the Force of 25 N displaces the belt
									  by value less than 10 mm. Adjust the displacement of belt by tightening/loosening
									  the lock nut at the Belt Tensioner Assembly.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 6:	Once
									  the belt is adjusted to the desired tension, tighten the lock nuts
									  (both LH threaded &amp; RH threaded of size M10, see Fig. 2.7(b))
									  of Belt Tensioner Assembly.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <note>
										  <para style="color:red">An improperly adjusted belt can cause damage to the system.</para>
									  </note>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/2_6_5_3_1_2.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.7(a)</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/2_6_5_3_1_3.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.7(b)</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/2_6_5_3_1_4.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.8: Inner view of Rotary Encoder Housing Assembly</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
							  </content>
						  </section>
						  <section id="2.6.5.3.2 Timing Pulley Installation " level="6">
							  <title>2.6.5.3.2 Timing Pulley Installation </title>
							  <content>
								  <para>Carry out the following</para>
								  <para>
									  Step 1:	Ensure
									  that power supply to the Encoder Housing Assembly is switched OFF.
								  </para
>
								  <para>
									  Step 2:	Using Allen key, remove the 15 No’s Allen Bolts (M6x1x25)
									  that has been fastened to the closing plate of the Encoder Housing
									  Assembly (Stack the removed bolts properly until the procedure is
									  completed)
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 3:	Ensure proper mounting and fitment
									  of Timing pulley (A) on the drum shaft with shaft key. (a step provided
									  on the shaft helps in locating the pulley on the shaft)
								  </para>
								  <para
>
									  Step 4:	Place the circlip and tighten the grub screw (M4x15 lg).
									  Ensure there is no play between circlip and timing pulley.
								  </para>
								  <para
>
									  Step 5:	Mount the Timing Pulley (B) on the shaft of the Rotary Encoder
									  and tighten the corresponding Grub Screw.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 6:	Similarly,
									  mount the Timing Pulley (C) on the shaft of the Rotary Cam Limit Switch
									  unit with shaft key and tighten the Grub Screw.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/2_6_5_3_2.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.8: Inner view of Rotary Encoder Housing Assembly</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 7:	Fix the Belt Tensioner Assembly to the
									  internal surface of the Encoder Housing Assembly by fastening 2 No’s
									  M10 Allen Bolts.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 8:	Check the parallelism of other
									  pulleys with reference to the Drum Shaft Pulley, by placing the Steel
									  Rule and using Filler Gauges. (The gap should be less than 1mm).
								  </para
>
								  <para>
									  Step 9:	Release the grub screw on the Timing Pulleys (B &amp;
									  C) and adjust location of pulleys until the achieved gap with respect
									  to Drum Shaft Pulley is less than 1mm.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 10:	Once the
									  Timing Pulleys are fastened, wind the Timing Belt on the pulley.
								  </para
>
								  <para>
									  <note>
										  <para style="color:red">
											  Before closing the Encoder Housing Assembly, make sure that
											  Belt Tensioning and Rotary Cam Limit Switch Setting is done.
										  </para>
									  </note>
								  </para>
							  </content>
						  </section>
						  <section id="2.6.5.3.3 Rotary Cam Limit Switch setting procedure   "
						  level="6">
							  <title>2.6.5.3.3 Rotary Cam Limit Switch setting procedure   </title>
							  <content>
								  <para>Carry out the following:</para>
								  <para>
									  <h6>
										  1.	 Zero Setting
										  on Cam
									  </h6>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 1:	Disassemble the Rotary Cam Limit
									  Switch. For dismantling RCLS,(<a
onclick="javascript:parent.showPDF(&quot;../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/Dismantling_RCLS.pdf&quot;);parent.masterframe.rows=&quot;70%,30%&quot;"
actuate="user">
										  Click here.<img src="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/book.jfif" style="height:40px;width:50px;" />
									  </a>)
								  </para
>
								  <para>
									  Step 2:	Rotate shaft clockwise to match 0 on scale disc of
									  Cam Limit Switch.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/2_6_5_3_3_1.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.9: Location of Rotary Cam Limit Switch</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <h6>2.	Cam alignment tools</h6>
								  </para>
								  <para
>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/2_6_5_3_3_2.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.10: Cam alignment tools</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/2_6_5_3_3_2_1.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.11: Inner view &amp; parts of Rotary Cam Limit Switch</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 1:	Base in 0° position (scale disk is at
									  0°)
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Step 2:	Using Adjusting Key (1), disengage the Cross-hole
									  nut so that program discs can be rotated.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <h6>
										  3.	Setting
										  of the Program
									  </h6>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/2_6_5_3_3_3.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.12: Rotary Cam Limit Switch-Program setting</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <table frame="box" rules="all">
										  <colgroup>
											  <col/>
											  <col/>
										  </colgroup>
										  <tbody>
											  <tr>
												  <td>
													  <h6>CAM No.</h6>
												  </td>
												  <td>
													  <h6>Program disc</h6>
												  </td>
											  </tr>
											  <tr>
												  <td>CAM 4 </td>
												  <td>Program disc A and B </td>
											  </tr>
											  <tr>
												  <td>CAM 3</td>
												  <td>Program disc C and D </td>
											  </tr>
											  <tr>
												  <td>CAM 2</td>
												  <td>Program disc E and F </td>
											  </tr>
											  <tr>
												  <td>CAM 1</td>
												  <td>Program disc G and H </td>
											  </tr>
											  <tr>
												  <td>CAM 5</td>
												  <td>Program disc I and J </td>
											  </tr>
										  </tbody>
									  </table>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/2_6_5_3_3_3_1.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.12(a): Rotary Cam Limit Switch-Program setting</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <h6>4.	Setting of the Cams:</h6>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <ol type="a">
										  <li>During Recovery Cam rotates from 360 ° to 0 °.</li>
										  <li>During Deployment Cam rotates from 0° to 360°.</li>
										  <li>
											  For SW1, 2 and 3 pole position at 120° and for SW 2 and 4 pole
											  position at 240° when Cam degree set at 0°.
										  </li>
										  <li>
											  Used normally closed contact for switch 1 to 4 and Normally Open
											  contact for Switch 5.
										  </li>
										  <li>Set all the Switch cam with respect to the figure given below. </li>
										  <li>Use adjustment key 2 set up tool for setting Cam.</li>
									  </ol>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_6_5_3_3_4_1.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.13: Rotary Cam Limit Switch-Position</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <h6>Setting of Cam 4</h6>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Turn seat
									  at 340° position by “adjustment key (2)”. Adjust the program disc
									  A and B by rotating, so that the switch release and remains in release
									  condition till the Turn seat at 344° position. After that switch remain
									  pressed between 344° to 334°.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <h6>Setting of Cam 3</h6
>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Turn seat at 308° position by “adjustment key (2)”.
									  Adjust the program disc C and D by rotating, so that the switch release
									  and remains in release condition till the Turn seat at 344° position.
									  After that switch remain pressed between 344° to 308°.
								  </para>
								  <para
>
									  <h6>Setting of Cam 2</h6>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Turn seat at 212° position
									  by “adjustment key (2)”. Adjust the program disc E and F by rotating,
									  so that the switch release and remains in release condition till the
									  Turn seat at 344° position. After that switch remain pressed between
									  344° to 212°.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <h6>Setting of Cam 1</h6>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Turn
									  seat at 148° position by “adjustment key (2)”. Adjust the program
									  disc G and H by rotating, so that the switch release and remains in
									  release condition till the Turn seat at 344° position. After that
									  switch remain pressed between 344° to 148°.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <h6>
										  Setting
										  of Cam 5
									  </h6>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  Turn seat at 354° position by “adjustment
									  key (2)”. Adjust the program disc I and J by rotating, so that the
									  switch release and remains in release condition till the Turn seat
									  at 356° position. After that switch remain pressed between 356° to
									  354°.
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <h6>5.	Tighten the fixing</h6>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_6_5_3_3_5_1.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>Fig. 2.14: Rotary Cam Limit Switch-Close view</figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <ol type="a">
										  <li>Tighten the capstan nut with Adjusting Key (1). </li>
										  <li>
											  Hold the program slices (especially I and J) and press direction
											  scale disk.
										  </li>
										  <li>
											  Cross-hole nut so alluring, that the program discs can no longer
											  be rotated.
										  </li>
									  </ol>
								  </para>
								  <para>
									  <figure>
										  <graphic fileref="../Author/Contents/NTDS/The_New_Torpedo_Defence_System/Technical_Manual/Images/sec_2_6_5_3_3_5_2.gif"></graphic>
										  <figtitle>
											  Fig. 2.15: Recommended connections for Fiber Pigtails for
											  Optical Repeater
										  </figtitle>
									  </figure>
								  </para>
							  </content>
						  </section>
					  </section>
					  <section id="2.6.5.4 Band Brake Assembly" level="5">
						  <title>2.6.5.4 Band Brake Assembly</title>
						  <content>
							  <para>
								  Step 1:	Inspect the brake for any damage and replace
