  <trouble_shooting id="Troubleshooting">
    <title>Troubleshooting</title>
    <section id="Introduction" level="2">
      <title>Introduction</title>
      <content>
        <para>
          The purpose of fault finding is to isolate hardware
          faults upto the Line Replaceable Unit (LRU) level as quickly as possible.
          Fault finding procedures are subject to the following assumptions:
        </para
  >
        <para>
          <ol type="a">
            <li>There is one faulty LRU at a time.</li>
            <li>The fault is continuously present.</li>
            <li>The fault is not wiring fault or bad connection.</li>
            <li>Prior to occurrence of fault, the system was functioning correctly.</li>
          </ol>
        </para>
      </content>
      <section id="1.1 Fault Detection  " level="3">
        <title>1.1 Fault Detection  </title>
        <content>
          <para>
            A fault is said to exist when the system does not perform
            within the laid down specifications. A fault can manifest itself in
            the following:
          </para>
          <para>
            <ol type="a">
              <li>
                Through an indication (lamp, Light Emitting Diode (LED), alphanumeric
                display) generated by the hardware and or software of the system
                (e.g., lamp, fuses).
              </li>
              <li>Defects observed in BITE exploitations.</li>
              <li>
                Through perceptible degradation of the performance of the system
                (e.g., malfunctioning of discrete components, converters, displays,
                etc.).
              </li>
            </ol>
          </para>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="1.2 Fault Isolation" level="3">
        <title>1.2 Fault Isolation</title>
        <content>
          <para>
            Once the fault is detected, software and hardware aids
            are used to Isolation the fault. The procedure followed is to Isolation
            the fault to a specific subsystem and then to an LRU. Fault diagnosis
            and Isolation can be carried out from the LCU/RCU for Launcher
            and by Error Codes displayed on MCP display for Winch.
          </para>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="1.3 Built in Test Facilities  " level="3">
        <title>1.3 Built in Test Facilities  </title>
        <content>
          <para>
            The system is provided with a BITE facility to check
            the health of the system and to localize faults up to the Unit/LRU
            level with the power ON. On switching ON, the various lamps on the
            front panel of LCU/RCU/MCP will glow and confirming their initial
            status. Essential self checks of all the units are carried out automatically
            and the results displayed by means of glowing lamps. With the power
            ON Console, LED indicators (+3.3V, +5V and ±12V) located on the front
            panel of display (monitor) will glow and subsequently the built-in
            LCD will become alive and display Power-On-Self-Test (POST) messages
            and confirming their initial status.
          </para>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="1.4 Fault Finding Procedure"
      level="3">
        <title>1.4 Fault Finding Procedure</title>
        <content>
          <para>
            After the detection of a fault, the maintainer must
            initially refer to the procedures described in the following paragraphs.
          </para
  >
          <para>
            A fault especially power failures occurring in any of the subsystems
            like FVA, EDL, LCU &amp; RCU is presented on front panel of the LCU
            and RCU by illuminating the blown fuse or by illuminating the LED
            indicators with the power ON/OFF switches to ON position.
          </para
  >
          <para>
            A fault especially link failures occurring between any of the
            subsystems like RCU and Cabinet are presented on their respective
            front panel by illuminating the LED indicators.
          </para>
          <para>
            A fault
            especially power failures occurring in Winch (MCP) is presented on
            its front panel by illuminating the blown fuse or by illuminating
            the LED indicators with the power ON/OFF switches to ON position.
            In addition, with the power ON, the system carryout the self test,
            failure of any subsystem (with in the MCP) is displayed on the MCP
            display; the failed subsystem is identified by its LRU code, unit/card
            name and Failure symptom.
          </para>
        </content>
      </section>
